<HTML>
<title>MILNET:  Terrorism - Worldwide Acts of Terrorism</title>
<center>
<img src="milnetsm.gif" align=middle, alt="Milnet">
<p>
<p>
<a href="milnet.htm"><img src="milico.gif" align=middle alt="Milnet Main"></a>
<a href="terror.htm"><img src="terror.gif" align=middle alt="Terrorism"></a>
<p>
<p></center>
<H1>Worldwide Acts Of Terrorism </H1>
Below we list a history of acts of terrorism, starting in 1968 and through 1986.  Of 
course terrorism has continued since 1986.  A few of the major events since 1986 are included as well, but data is not complete from 1986 onward, as the volume of events has outpaced the author's ability to report on them.  To make this point clear we also have compile 
brief snapshots of terrorism since 1986 in the  <a href="terrfile.htm">Terrfile</a> .            
<p>
Note that the majority of terrorism reported before 1980 occurred in or around Isarael and the Middle East.  This is due to the fact that world terrorism spread from the Middle East as Arab and Jew continued their ancestorial struggles.  The State of Israel considered Arab attacks on their kinsmen as an act of War, and not to be outdone, began their own retalitory acts of terror.  Their own band of terrorist/assassins ran free until the crew accidentally killed some innocents, at which time the Israeli government reigned them in (see "<i><b>The Hit Team</b></i> #25 in the <a href="biblio.htm#25">Milnet Bibliography</a>.
<p>
Since then, Israeli retaliation has been in a more miltary fashion, with excursions into neighboring countries, seizing land to create buffer zones around them.<p>
Today, the Gaza Strip, a contentious holding of the Israelis has been the scene of most of the Middle East violence over the last decade.
<p>
However you will also note from the data that Central Europe and London, United Kingdom have also had their share of terrorism from Middle Eastern concerns.
<p>
Until recently, the only country which has not faced Middle East terrorism
within its borders was the United States.  
The World Trade Center explosion was attributed to a radical Jordanian moslem 
group.  Only time will tell whether this trend continues in the U.S..  And of
course terrorist activities that target U.S. serviceman, while described by
terrorist groups as "acts of war", cannot be treated as such as their is no
declaration of war in place, nor is their a nation to declare war against. 
<p>
You will note a few instances where an act of violence is on the very gray 
edge of the line separating political violence versus terrorism... 
the difference being nearly indistinguishable at times.  
For instance, what were the motives of the assassin who took a shot at the 
Pope?  Was it anti-catholicism, anti-Rome/anti-Italy, or just a nut case 
trying to get his moment of dubious "fame"?
<p>
Here is the promised chronology on World Terrorism:  
