<HTML><head></head>
<TITLE>Programming for Early Childhood Care and
Development</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFE0" TEXT="800000" LINK="8E2323" 
VLINK=""0000FF">

<H1>Programming for Early Childhood Care and
Development</H1>
<IMG SRC="orange.gif" ALT="*"><A HREF="e13.html">ECCD Programming Principles</A><p>
<IMG SRC="orange.gif" ALT="*"><A HREF="e14.html">Program Strategies in Early Childhood Care and Development</A>
<p>
<IMG SRC="orange.gif" ALT="*"><A HREF="e15.html">Program Structure in ECCD </A><p>
<IMG SRC="orange.gif" ALT="*"><A HREF="e16.html">Program Content -- Curricula in ECCD</A>
<p>

<p>
<b>What is the basis for ECCD programming and action?</b><p>
<p>
	The burgeoning of programme experiences over the last two decades has provided
a wide range of effective and financially feasible models to promote integrated
care, development and learning in the early years.  That experience offers us
options that go well beyond a narrow, "institutional" preschool approach, which
is often expensive and age-restricted. The experience with early childhood care
and development embraces complementary approaches that enhance early
development and learning in a variety of ways.  These approaches may be
directed toward a variety of different actors and programme participants such
as: parents, community workers, policy-makers, law-makers, and the public at
large (as well as young children and their siblings). These are described under
<b><A HREF="e14.html">Program Strategies</b></A><p>
<p>
	Under <b><A HREF="e10n.html">Projects and Program Profiles </b></A>, case studies are
provided of programmes that focus on parental education, on community-based and
non-formal pre-school centres, and on integrated home-day care programmes.
Descriptions are also available of experiences taking such lines of action as:
adding in a developmental component to existing health or nutrition or women's
credit programmes, working through home visits with a "cartoon curriculum,"
working with upper primary school children in a child-to-child programme, and
teaching groups of mothers to teach their children.  Lessons learned from these
and other programmes can help show how to adapt programmes to local conditions
and how to handle constraints, including cost and financial constraints.  The
examples can be adapted easily to varied conditions.<p>
<p>
<p>

<HR>
