<html><head>
<title>CHILDREN CARING FOR CHILDREN: NEW APPLICATIONS OF AN OLD IDEA</title>
</head><body><center><H2>CHILDREN CARING FOR CHILDREN:
NEW APPLICATIONS OF AN OLD IDEA</H2>
<p>
by<p>
<p>
Barnabas Otaala, Robert Myers and Cassie Landers<p>
with assistance from Laura Otaala<p>
<p>
This review of programmes and approaches has been prepared by<p>
The Consultative Group on Early Childhood Care and Development<p>
<p>
October, 1988<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>CHILDREN CARING FOR CHILDREN:<p>
NEW APPLICATIONS OF AN OLD IDEA<p>
<p>
INTRODUCTION</u></b></center><p>
<p>
<p>
	Millions of infants and young children in Third World countries die every
year. And, for most children under the age of six who manage to survive, the
world is a threatening place. For an increasing number of these children growth
and development are delayed and disability is common.<p>
<p>
	Infant death and problems of growth and development in the early years have
many causes. Famine, war, and unemployment all take their toll. Lack of potable
water and poor sanitary conditions are common. Childhood and tropical diseases
continue to kill because health and social services fail to reach many places
with preventive and curative services that could save lives. These causes and
conditions are exacerbated by recent declines in economic development in many
countries, and an associated need for major adjustments in government budgets
and programmes. (Bennett, 1982; Cornia, Jolly and Stewart, 1987).<p>
<p>
	In such circumstances, assuring proper care and development for children is a
major challenge -- for families, governments, and international organizations alike. As discussed
during a WHO/UNLCEF workshop on alternative approaches to care of the young
child:<p>
<p>
	<ul>"In many developing countries, women have tried different ways to meet the
need for services for their children. Governments too, and other institutions,
have recognized the need for programmes for children and have made essential
inputs, both financially and by way of legislation to facilitate the operation
of such services, International agencies, particularly UNESCO, UNICEF, and WMO,
have made inputs by way of equipment, buildings, and sponsorship of
conferences, seminars, workshops and training programmes and dissemination of
materials. Despite all of  these commendable efforts, the problem of provision
of services for children are nowhere near solution. Despite major efforts and
huge investments in early childhood education, the gap between care, health and
educational needs at that level and the resources available continues to
widen." (Heron and Otaala, 1982, p. 4).</ul>
<p>
	A child's continuing struggle for survival and healthy development in the
early years emphasizes the need for low-cost approaches that can reach many
children. The institutionalised response, such as hospitals and formal
preschools or child care centers, are usually costly solutions, reaching only a
privileged few. Campaigns to vaccinate children and to educate adults may reach
many people, but are short-run
solutions; attitudes and practices are seldom changed in a fundamental way.
Primary health care systems are still limited in coverage and are not always
used by those who most need the service. Each of these approaches has some
effect on survival and development, and taken together, they. have helped to
reduce infant mortality significantly. But the vulnerability of young children
is profound, and alternate programme approaches are needed that look beyond
survival and that help to overcame vulnerability through more adequate care.<p>
<p>
<b><u>An Alternative</u></b><p>
<p>
	This paper describes and reviews experience with one promising programme
approach to care and development that is being applied increasingly, and in
diverse settings throughout the world: the care of children by children. In
most parts of the world, such care is part of a time-honored,
traditional system for helping to meet child care needs. Older children are
routinely expected to look after the health and development of a younger
brother or sister. That traditional practice provides a foundation for
programming that is not new but is being rediscovered and applied in new
ways.<p>
<p>
	Building programmes around the idea of children caring for children is an
attractive and a potentially effective complement to other programmes for at
least four reasons. First, working with child care givers offers the
possibility of affecting directly the health and development of younger
children by providing older children with information they can use in a
caretaking role. Where care of younger siblings is common, a naturally
occurring practice exists that can be reinforced and improved. For example,
sibling care givers or "Little mothers" (Mallya, I.P., 1983) can be trained to
help assure that the children under their care are vaccinated, treated with
oral rehydration salts when needed, fed properly, talked to, cuddled, and
played with. Second, Child-to-Child
programmes have a potential for being effective because the older caretakers,
although still children, will soon be parents themselves. By learning about
proper ways of caring for younger children, they will be better prepared for
their own parenthood. This outcome is particularly relevant in places where the
traditional, naturally occurring child care apprenticeship that mothers have
given to older siblings is diluted because children are now in school for large
portions of the day.<p>
	A third potential benefit of working with child care givers derives from their
communication abilities. Children can provide information about new practices
to peers, parents, families, and community members. That communication can take
place through direct conversations, or indirectly through skits or by
example.<p>
<p>
	Finally, children of primary school age can have an effect on care and
development through direct actions taken in the community, identifying health
problems or organizing to clean up the environment in which they and their
younger siblings live.<p>
<p>
	To realize these potential benefits --- to the younger child, the prospective parent in the older child, other family
members, and the community at large --- mechanisms of educating and mobilizing child care givers are needed. Many such
ways exist and experiences with them are multiplying rapidly. Indeed, the idea
of children caring for children has spread. In some places that has occurred
naturally as, for instance, local primary school teachers have taken advantage
of the presence of younger children in the classroom, brought by sisters or
brothers who could not leave them alone at home. In other cases, a programme
has been introduced from the outside. And, in 1978, an international programme
called Child-to-Child
was begun in order to articulate, operationalize and spread the idea over a wide front.<p>
<p>
	Although programmes building on children caring for children have taken hold
in many places, experience is still relatively recent. Moreover, in the
execution of activities and programmes, the original idea has often been
transformed. A number of issues and ideas have emerged that deserve
systematic review. That is the principal purpose of this paper.<p>
<p>
	More specifically, the objectives of this review are:<p>
<p>
<ul><li>	  To examine the idea of children caring for children, placing it in historical context.<p>
<p>
	 <li>To describe and analyze the translation of the idea into various programme
forms.<p>
<p>
	 <li>To review selected projects and report results of project evaluations.<p>
<p>
	 <li>To present the University of London's Institutes of Child Health and Education Child-to-Child
Programme and its activities.<p>
<p>
	 <li>To draw some conclusions about the Child-to-Child
approach, with a view to aiding 	policy formulation and the operationalisation
of programmes and activities to promote 	better care and development of
vulnerable young children.</ul>

	The paper is organized in five sections, each dealing with one of the
objectives listed above. A list of references is annexed and appendices
providing more detailed information about specific programmes are attached.<p>
<p>
<b><u>SECTION I</u></b><p>
<b><u>Children Caring for Children: The Idea and History</u></b><p>
<p>
<p>
	In many societies, children caring for children has been a necessary and accepted practice, existing, at the very least, for centuries. That practice has, at the same time, provided a practical solution to child care needs and functioned as a form of socialisation to the future role of parent.<p>
<p>
	In highly industrialised countries, although some caring for infants and
children of preschool age by older siblings still occurs, the practice is
limited and in some countries has virtually disappeared, In their
pre-industrial periods, however, the care of younger children by older children
was common in these countries as well. Large families and subsistence living
requiring hard work by all family members meant that children had to contribute
from an early age. One important way to help, particularly for girls, ages 6 or
7 to 15, was to care for younger brothers and sisters. With urbanisation,
industrialisation, shifts toward nuclear families, and the reduction in family
size, child care needs changed and, with the extension of formal schooling, the
availability of child caretakers was restricted.<p>
<p>
	These same factors are affecting traditional child care patterns in all parts
of the world today. Urbanization is preceding at a rapid rate. Family
structures are changing. Primary schooling has expanded rapidly. However, in
many parts of Asia, Africa, Latin America and the Middle East, large families
and subsistence living are still dominant, and sibling care is still an
important practice. A recent study from rural Nigeria, for instance, indicated
that 16% of the child care was carried out by older siblings. (Wilson-
Oyelaran,
E.B. and Ladipo, P.D., 1987).<p>
<p>
<b><u>A Traditional View</u></b><p>
<p>
	Differences in the reliance on older children to care for younger children are
related to cultural beliefs as well as to family structure, livelihood, and
other factors described above. Each culture has its own beliefs about a child's
capacities and needs as the child passes from an infant to a toddler to a young
child to a pre-adolescent
and adolescent. For instance, there are variations in beliefs and attitudes
about the point at which older children are responsible enough to take on child
care duties and about when young children are considered old enough to be
trusted to the care of other children (Weisner and Gallimore, 1977). The point
at which it is thought appropriate
for a mother to allow others to care for her child also varies.<p>
<p>
	What form does sibling care take? How is it learned? How does it vary?
Autobiographical and anthropological accounts are two sources which help to
identify and understand similarities and differences in child caretaking within
and across cultures. These accounts provide useful insight into the natural
practice of children caring for children in "traditional" societies, We will
draw briefly on both of these in setting a base for discussion of the more
formalized and institutionalized programmes that are being carried out in
transitional settings.     <p>
<p>
	<i>Autobiographical sketches.</i><p>
<p>
	The following is taken from an account of childhood and caretaking
responsibilities provided by Lijembe, as he was growing up among the Abaluhga
in Kenya:<p>
	<ul>"Because there was no sister in the family, and my mother had to go off to
work in the <i>shamba</i> (gardens) everyday, it wasn't long before I was
obliged, though still a very young child  myself, to become the day-to-
day
"nurse" for my baby sister. For my mother to make me succeed in this function,
she had to train me --- to give me instructions and to see how well I carried them out... As her shamba
work increased, so did my nursing duties...Before moving off to the shamba, she
would give me instructions.'Do not leave the home unguarded, she would tell
me,"' (Lijembe, as quoted in Weisner and Gallimore, p. 171).</ul>

	Lijembe also describes leaving home while his younger sister was sleeping to
play with his friend nurses from other homesteads. He describes taking his
sister with him to play and to go bathing. He tells how he toilet-trained
her and how he fed her. He also says that punishment of the child caretaker for
poor performance was swift. (Weisner and Gallimore, p. 171).<p>
<p>
	<i>Anthropological accounts</i>.<p>
<p>
	The anthropological literature contains many, and sometimes very vivid
accounts of caretaking by older siblings. In her classic study, "Growing Up in
Samoa," Margaret Mead observes that:<p>
<p>
	<ul>"A Samoan caretaker learns to shout, 'Come out of the sun' before she herself
has fully appreciated the necessity of doing so. By the time Samoan girls and
boys have reached sixteen or seventeen years of age, these perpetual
admonitions have become an inseparable part of their conversation, a monotonous
irritated undercurrent to all their comments... The little nurses are more
interested in peace than in forming the characters of their small charges and
when a child begins to howl it is simply dragged out of earshot of its elders."
(Weisner and Gallimore, p. 172).</ul>

	Liederman and Liederman (1973) have provided a detailed account of how Kikuyu
caretakers (Kenya) execute their tasks.<p>
<p>
	<ul>"Kikuyu child caretakers are usually 7 to 12 years old, female, and siblings
cousins or neighbours. They may have had some schooling, but probably very
little. The child caretaker's role begins around the infant's fourth month and
gradually expands until the child is in charge half the day, or more, by 7 or 8
months.<p>
<p>
	"The caretaker is usually old enough to know the responsibilities of the
household, yet young enough to want to be included in the children's games and
activities. In her typical day, she gets up with the mother and helps about the
house. She frequently accompanies the mother to collect fuel and water, usually
taking responsibility for the infant on these journeys. If needed, she goes
with the mother to the fields where she either assists in cultivating and
planting, or cares for the child while the mother performs her chores. If the
younger girl is left at home to care for the infant, she is solely responsible
for his care. She provides food, if he is old enough to take supplemental food,
or, if he is still nursing she carries him to the mother in the fields.
Depending on the interests and sense of responsibility of the young caretaker,
she might watch the child extremely carefully, or do so in a more desultory
manner, giving in to the temptation of playing with her friends and siblings
while overseeing his activities. However, most caretakers take their
responsibilities very seriously, and many are genuinely interested in, and
involved with the younger infant, in play as well as in caretaking tasks." (p.
113)</ul>

	Whiting has examined the behaviour of 3 to 8 year old Kikuyu (Kenya) children
towards their two-year old siblings. The results show that there is marked increase with age in the proportion of nurturant caretaking behaviour toward 2-year old children and a decrease in the amount of aggressive and social interaction. Children aged eight are more consistently nurturant. Whiting concludes, "I have speculated
that this is the age of the greatest identification with the mother before the onset of puberty."<p>
<p>
	The effect on caretaking of age found by Whiting has an interesting counter-part
in a laboratory study by Cicirelli (1973) Using concept learning tasks to study
the effect of sibling interaction, Cicirelli found that children working with
siblings four years older made larger gains than children aided by siblings two
years older. In another study, older sisters were significantly more effective
teachers of younger siblings than were older brothers, and they tended to use
more deductive teaching methods (explaining and describing, demonstrating and
illustrating attributes, etc.).<p>
<p>
	Two accounts of sibling care on the West Coast of Colombia are provided by
Uribe (1982), one from a marginal urban area (Buenaventura) and one from a
fishing village (Puerto Merizalde).<p>
<p>
	<ul>"Almost all children were responsible for taking care of siblings during the
day. Those who did not engage in these activities were the youngest in the
family. Mothers were pointed out as the ones that instructed children about
this particular chore. 'My mother told me not to let the baby fall down or she
will punish me. My little brother is very playful. When I leave the room he
goes right behind me and I have to take him with me. I don't like him to take
nothing from the floor. I give him his bottle when he asks for it.... And when
he wants to pee he pushes himself forward so that I put him down and pees. When
he does something I don't like, I take him, and ask him why he is doing that
and he gets mad. I don't beat him....'.<p>
<p>
	"Children described their responsibilities with siblings in terms of feeding,
bathing, making them sleep, changing their clothes, and protecting them from
harm or other children.<p>
<p>
	 <li>'I don't let my younger brothers go out to the street because a car may come
and kill them.'<p>
<p>
	 <li>'I close the door so that he cannot go out to the street, a dog may come and
bite him.'<p>
<p>
	 <li>'I sit near her and I play with her, and I help her to drink soup with a
spoon.'<p>
<p>
	 <li>'When he gets soiled I clean him with a damp cloth, then I put him in clean
pants and a clean shirt.'<p>
<p>
	 <li>'When it gets dark I hang our <u>toldillo</u> (piece of material that
protects from mosquitoes and that is hung over the bed) and I wash my feet and
my brother and I close  the door and go to sleep."' (Uribe, pages 99-

100).</ul>
	In transitional societies, schooling and child care often represent
conflicting demands on the time of children, particularly for girls. It is
difficult to know how real that conflict is. For instance, Skinner writes, in
an anthropological study of a Nepali community where a child care centre was
introduced:<p>
<p>
	<ul>"Of 65 mothers, only three mothers said they would have kept their older
daughters home from school with out the day care centre to care for their
younger children; however, I believe several more mothers would have done so if
the centre had not been operating. Often children do not attend school even
though enrolled because they are kept out to watch younger siblings who do not
attend the day care centre." (Skinner, p. 16).</ul>
	From the few illustrative accounts provided above, it is evident that although
there are several similarities in caretaking functions, there are significant
variations as well, depending on the relative ages of caretaker and younger
child, on parental availability and expectations, on different cultural
conceptions of a child's maturity, on other tasks and demands on the older
child, and on community and household circumstances.<p>
<p>
	These accounts point to the fact that some caretaker training is given by
mothers, although they do not describe that training in detail. They suggest
that boys as well as girls can be pressed into caretaking service, although in
most cases girls perform the caretaking role. In addition, the accounts suggest
that caretaking outcomes are associated, among other things, with the
seriousness of purpose with which the task is carried out.<p>
<p>
<b>Some advantages and disadvantages</b><p>
<p>
	There are some obvious benefits to younger children of caretaking by older
siblings, if that caretaking is carried out consciously. Children are not left
alone. They may be attended to much more closely than would be possible by a
harried mother. They have a non-adult
source for learning, modelling, and play.<p>
<p>
	However, if child caretakers are distracted, irresponsible, improperly trained
and supervised by their parents, or inadequately, informed, the substitution of
child for adult in caretaking may be disadvantageous. Food preparation and
feeding may suffer, for instance. Preventable accidents may occur. Language and
other areas of cognitive development could suffer. This issue was addressed in
a study conducted by P.M. Shah, et. al., 1979. The authors identified 108
families in 9 villages participating in the Kasa Model Integrated MCH Nutrition
Project in rural Maharashtra. Their results indicated that the incidence of
malnutrition decreased as the age of the mother substitute increased. The
prevalence of these negative outcomes and the circumstances under which they
are most likely to occur, however, are not fully understood.<p>
<p>
	For the older children, caretaking provides an opportunity to learn and
practice adult roles. Exercising the caretaking function broadens parent-

child
relationships by presenting circumstances in which parents can accord their
older offspring some measure of enhanced status. The sense of responsibility
may be enhanced. Personality, attitudes and values may be influenced rather
dramatically. Weisner and Gallimore (1977) indicate:<p>
<p>
	<ul>"Suggested consequences (of personality development must be interpreted in
terms of the role demands a child must eventually meet as an adult. While child
caretaking may not foster individual differentiation, it may prepare well for
societies in which personal achievement and independence are not common
options." (p, 179).</ul>
	Perhaps the most general conclusions that can be drawn from the above brief
anthropological account of the practice of children caring for children are:<p>
<p>
	<ol>1. The practice continues to be important in some locations and is not so
important in others. Where it continues as a main child care strategy, working
with the older children holds promise for directly affecting the health and
development of younger children. Where it has diminished in importance, there
is a need to fill in a socialization gap. The effects of teaching children of
primary school age about child care are likely to be realized parents.<p>
<p>
	2. There are potential advantages and disadvantages of children caring for
children - to both the younger and older children involved.<p>
<p>
	3. The outcome of the practice is influenced by the ages of those involved and
by a series of social and cultural factors surrounding the practice, not all of
which are well documented or understood.<p>
<p>
	4. Training and supervision, and a well-

developed
sense of responsibility in the older child are crucial to successful Child-to-Child
care.</ol>

	The degree to which these conclusions, drawn from anthropological accounts,
are reflected in current programming efforts are discussed in further detail in
the following sections.<p>
<p>
<b><center>SECTION II<p>
<p>
Translating the Idea into Programmes: A Typology</center></b><p>
<p>
	We turn now to ways in which the practice of children caring for children is
being built upon and adapted to a variety of contemporary settings. In this
section, we will set out a typology that will help to frame the examination in
Section III of specific projects and of the global initiative called the Child-to-Child
Programme.<p>
<p>
<b>The Role of Older Children</b><p>
<p>
	Older children, somewhere between the ages of 8 and 15, constitute the focus
of attention for programmers building on the principle of children caring for
children. These children are the main group to be mobilized. However, as seen
in the previous section, these older children may be treated primarily as:<p>
<p>
<ul><li> Caretakers,<br>
	 <li>Future parents,<br>
	 <li>Communicators of messages to other caretakers, and/or<br>
	 <li>Agents to improve conditions affecting health and development.</ul>
<p>
The emphasis given to these respective roles in a particular project is closely
related to the definition of the primary beneficiary and influences the
project's organization and content. As the idea of children caring for children
has been translated into programmes, more attention seems to have been given to
the latter three roles than to the role of actual caretaker.<p>
<p>
<b>Participants and Beneficiaries</b><p>
<p>
	Corresponding to the above distinction in roles the primary beneficiaries in a
Child-to-Child
programme may be:<p>
<p>
<ul><li> Younger children,<br>
	 <li>Older children,<br>
	 <li>Adult caretakers, or<br>
	 <li>The community at large.</ul>

	In most instances it is hoped that several or all of the above will
participate and benefit from the programme.<p>
<p>
	Another participant and potential beneficiary is the person who helps to teach
and mobilize the older children. These may be:<p>
<p>
<ul><li> School teachers and supervisors,<br>
	 <li>Health personnel,<br>
	 <li>Social service personnel, and<br>
	 <li>Youth leaders.</ul>
<p>
<b>Institutional Location</b><p>
<p>
	Programmes of children caring for children can be found within a wide variety
of institutions. The most common attachment has been to primary schools,
sometimes to individual schools and districts, and sometimes at a national
level. In these cases, the mobilizer is usually the primary school teacher who
incorporates information and activities within the school routine that are
intended to bring about improvements in child care outside the school. However,
Child-to-Child
programmes have bean organized also in conjunction with activities of hospitals
and primary health care centers, community associations, municipal governments,
universities, and other independent organizations such as the nutrition
centers, child care organizations, and youth groups. Examples of the
institutional locus of a project or programme will usually define who is to be
the teacher/mobilizer as well as determine the specific content of activities.
The range of institutional variability will be discussed in more detail in the
examination of particular projects in Section III.<p>
<p>
<b>Programme Content</b><p>
<p>
	As specific examples of programmes of children caring for children are
discussed, more specifics about content will be provided. For purposes of the
typology, it is sufficient to note general areas of programme content:<p>
<p>
<ul><li> Health care,<br>
	 <li>Nutrition,<br>
	 <li>Accident prevention, and<br>
	 <li>Mental and social development.<br></ul>
	In addition to the above, special emphases may be taken in a particular
programme, dealing for instance with physical disabilities or sanitation, or
community work, An integrated view of child care may be taken or content may be
focussed on one or more particular areas. In some programmes, for instance,
health dominates and older children are helped to identify diseases,
promote immunization, etc., but they are not involved in education or play with
younger children.<p>
<p>
<b>Methods and Materials</b><p>
<p>
	While programmes building on the practice of children caring for children
adopt many methods of teaching and mobilizing children, emphasis is most often
placed on the development of an active and participatory approach to learning
and teaching. In this approach teachers are taught to act as a catalyst to
encourage children to help each other and their communities. In accomplishing
this goal, programme instructors are encouraged to:<p>
<p>
<ul><li> Explore ways children can identify health needs, problems, and priorities.<p>
<p>
	<li>Discuss ways of addressing these problems.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Understand through the use of role-play
and drama another's feelings and views.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Design appropriate activities which are acceptable and easily implemented.</ul>

	Child-to-Child
materials are often developed from locally produced materials and based on
simple clear messages. Emphasizing an active participatory approach, these
materials often include songs, plays, skits, puppetry, posters, and stories.<p>
<p>
<b>Scale</b><p>
<p>
	Child-to-Child
programmes vary in scope. At one end of the continuum are programmes delivered
to groups of 8 to 10 children in private homes, while at the other extreme are
massive national programmes reaching all students enrolled in a school system.
According to a recently completed survey of Child-to-Child
Programmes affiliated with the Institute of Child Wealth, University of London,
an average project has just under 250 participants, with three quarters of the
projects reviewed reaching fewer than 1,000 participants (Somerset, 1988). One
question raised by the variability in programme coverage is the degree to which
large-scale
programmes can successfully influence behaviour. The way in which scale and
impact are related is a critical issue in need of further investigation.<p>
<p>
<b><center>SECTION III<p>
<p>
An Examination of Selected Projects</center></b><p>
<p>
<p>
	In this section we will take a look at five specific programmes or projects,
selected from a wide variety of initiatives in the Caribbean, Latin America,
Africa, Asia, and the Middle East, These examples only begin to show the
creativity applied in translating into action the idea that children of primary
school age have an important role to play in caring for their younger brothers
and sisters and in improving the conditions in which they are struggling not
only to survive but also to develop to their full potential.<p>
<p>
	The examples were chosen in part because each has been submitted to an
evaluation. It is possible to draw on those evaluation results to see whether
proposed goals of the project are being met and, if they are pilot projects,
whether they are feasible and replicable on a larger scale. Looking at the
examples will also provide some insight into the outcomes achieved, forms of
organization, and differences in content and methods.<p>
<p>
<b>An Overview</b><p>
<p>
	As indicated in Table 1, each project is described according to: country and
location; the project type; institutional attachment; and content covered. In
addition, for each project the target group, expected beneficiaries, and the
reported outcomes are indicated. The following brief summary is accompanied by
a more detailed discussion of each project.<p>
<p>
	<i>Country and Location</i>. The selected projects have been carried out in
Jamaica, Colombia, India (two), and Botswana, These locations represent
considerable variety in culture, size, and economic and social conditions. The
projects represent also both urban and rural settings.<p>
<p>
	<i>Type of project</i>. Three of the six projects (Jamaica, and the two Indian
projects) started as demonstration or pilot projects but are being extended.
The project in Colombia was implemented on an experimental basis with less
direct possibility of "going to scale." In Botswana, the project is large
within the context of the country and is being carried out in 28 schools.<p>
<p>
	<i>Institutional Attachment</i>. Two of the projects were carried out in
primary schools, two in conjunction with activities of primary health care
centres, and one in relation to an on-going
programme of institutionalized child care.<p>
<p>
	<i>Content</i>. All projects focused on health care issues and four included
the additional component of nutrition education. Two of the five projects paid
specific attention to child development issues and one include information
related to dental care.<p>
<p>
	<i>Target Group and Beneficiaries</i>. In four of the five projects, the
target group mobilized as the primary focus of attention was primary school
children, ranging from grades 3 to 7. In Botswana, the programme targeted
younger primary school children in grades 1 to 3. The groups who benefited in
some way from the programmes included younger children, parents, and
communities. In four of the projects reviewed rather unexpected benefits were
received by
the teachers and schools participating in the programme.<p>
<p>
