</pre>
<p>
	<i>Benefits</i>. The benefits listed in the Table summarize those reported
through a range of evaluation activities. Benefits to the older children
reported by the projects included increased knowledge of health, nutrition and
education, improved personal hygiene and habits, and positive attitudes
including more nurturant attitudes towards younger siblings. In addition, the
older children acquired communication skills as well as the ability to
influence their local community.<p>
<p>
	For parents, especially mothers, an increase in self confidence and improved
child rearing practices (less physical punishment) were reported by two of the
projects. Increased knowledge about health, nutrition and education was found
in several projects, but without concomitant change in behaviours.<p>
<p>
	In at least two of the projects, school teachers charged with helping the
older children be better caretakers were also beneficiaries, they improved
their own knowledge of the subject matter as well as their teaching methods. In
the Botswana project, they had an easier job in helping first graders adapt to
school because much of that adjustment had been accomplished through the
project.<p>
<p>
	Quantifying the positive outcomes to younger children was somewhat more
difficult. It was assumed that they benefittcid directly from the activities
performed with them or indirectly through the positive effects on the older
children, parents, or teachers. In the one attempt made to study the impact on
younger children, no measurable effect was found in health, nutrition, or
developmental status.<p>
<p>
<b><center>JAMAICA<br>
Using Primary School Children to Improve Child-rearing</center></b><p>
<p>
	This experimental project was begun in Jamaica in 1979 by the Tropical
Metabolism Research Unit (TMRU) of the University of the West Indies (Knight
and Grantham-Macgregor,
1985). The purpose was to teach prinrary school children basic health and
developmental concepts with the aim of improving their knowledge, and child-rearing
practices and those of their parents or guardians. The project was conducted
in a rural community where social and health services were deficient. Unstable
family patterns in the community were reflected in the fact that over one-third
of the children involved in the project were not residing with their biological
mother. Both mothers and guardians tended to be unmarried. Housing stardards
were low with inadequate sanitation and overcrowding. The project school was
overcrowded as well with generally poor facilities and a shortage of basic
materials and teaching aids. The children's literacy level was generally low.<p>
<p>
	In this inpropitious setting, 94 children in primary school grades 3, 5, and
7, were given lessons (about 30 hours in total, over the course of one year)
dealing with child health and development.<p>
<p>
	The child development component of these sessions included information about
different areas of development, important developmental milestones, and
appropriate child management techniques. The children were taught how to make
toys from waste household materials, and how to play with them so as to
encourage a younger child's development. Dental care lessons included the care
of teeth, and information about foods which are good and bad for teeth.
Immunization lessons dealt with the purpose of immunization, the diseases which
immunization can prevent, and the times when the baby should be immunized. The
curriculum is described as "action-oriented"
and suitable for the children's level of reading and writing. Activities such
as role play, group discussions and demonstrations were included. Toy making,
drama, and poster competitions provided reinforcement. In the weekly sessions
classroom teachers were assisted by staff from the project.<p>
<p>
	To evaluate the project, a questionnaire was administered to guardians at home
and a test was given to the children at school, both at the beginning and end
of the year. Guardians were asked about their knowledge of material covered and
certain of their child care activities as well as about the school child's
activities with younger ones at home. In addition, at the end of the project
they were asked about the number of project toys brought home. School children
were tested on their knowledge of the topics taught and asked about their
activities with younger children at home.<p>
<p>
	Summarizing the results of this experiment, the following effects occurred:<p>
<p>
<ol>	1. <i>On younger children</i>. No observable change was reported in the
health, nutritional, or developmental status of pre-school
siblings.<p>
<p>
	2. <i>On primary school children</i>. Improvements occurred in the knowledge
of health, 	nutrition, and early development, as measured by tests geared to
the curriculum. This included recognition of the educational value of toys and
play and knowledge of suitable concepts to teach young children with toys.
Guardians reported that some health behaviours changed and that school children
instructed their younger brothers and sisters to clean their teeth and made
toys for them.<p>
<p>
	3. <i>On adults</i>. Guardians improved their knowledge and encouraged the
school children to play with younger children, but changes in adult caretaking
behaviour were not found.<p>
<p>
	4. <i>On teachers</i>. One unanticipated effect of the project was on the
teachers who improved their own knowledge of health and development. They were,
as well, introduced to some new forms of teaching.</ol>
	This project was considered a success, primarily because of its effect on the
knowledge and behaviours of the primary school children. It is suggested that,
the inability to document changes in the health, development, and nutrition of
preschool children reflects the difficulties in the measurement of these
changes. Moreover, the impact of the programme may not be apparent in the short-run,
but may necessitate the development of a longitudinal evaluation scheme to
monitor the impact of the programme over time. Thus, the absence of positive
programme effects must be interpreted with caution.<br><p>
	On the basis of the initial results, the project was expanded to 14 schools
and approximately 1000 students in the 4th and 5th grades. A teacher-training
programme was implemented utilizing the curriculum and activities developed
during the pilot project. Although a formal evaluation of this extended project
has not been implemented, it has been well received by teachers, parents, and
the health and education authorities. The activities are now integrated into
the primary school curriculum. In short, the experiment that began from the
perspective of helping older children care for younger children has had an
effect on the education system.<p>
<p>
	Additional information concerning this project is contained in Appendix III.<p>
<p>
<b><center>COLOMBIA<br>
The "Little Brothers" (Hermanitos) Project</center></b><p>

<p>
	This research project was undertaken by CEDEN (Centro de Educacion No-                                                                                       
Formal)
in 1983 with three purposes in mind (Ortiz, N, and Unda, M., 1985):<p>
<p>
<ol>	1. To design and implement an educational strategy directed at the training of
older siblings as socialising agents and developmental facilitators of younger
siblings (2-5 years of age).<p>
<p>
	2. To evaluate the effect of the training on behaviours of older siblings with
respect to the care and stimulation of younger siblings.<p>
<p>
	3. To evaluate the impact of training older siblings on the psycho-social
development of the younger siblings and on the knowledge and child-rearing patterns of the mother.</ol>

	The study was based on evidence in Colombia of a tendency to leave younger
siblings in the care of older ones. Apparently children not only accepted the
role but assumed it with a certain degree of satisfaction because it provided
them with "social value" and status within the family.<p>
<p>
Four groups were initially selected for the study, two of which were to
participate in the training, and two to serve as comparison groups. One urban
and one rural group was identified, respectively, for training and for
comparison. However, the original design had to be modified to eliminate the
rural comparison group. A minimum of forty families was identified for each
group in which there were two children, one aged 2 to 4 and the other aged 8 to
12 and in the forth or fifth grade. The older child had implicit or explicit
responsibility for taking care of the younger child.<br><p>
	The rural families, selected from an area 55 kilometers from Bogota, were
largely farmers who either worked their own small plot of land or were day
workers in larger farms. The average educational level was three years and the
average family size was slightly over 8. The urban population was similar in
educational level and almost the same with respect to average family size
(7.6). Living in a marginal area of Bogota, these families often lacked public
services -                                                                                
electricity, water, sewage. Most parents were unskilled laborers whose
employment was sporadic.<p>
<p>
	Training for the older siblings was provided outside the school by CEDEN. Each
Saturday morning for 25 weeks, two hour sessions were held dealing with
nutrition, health, psycho-social
development, and the physical environment of the house and community.<p>
<p>
	To evaluate the programme, pre- and post-tests
were administered with both older and younger children, and the interaction
between older children with younger siblings was observed. Tests and
observations were repeated following the training (pre- and
post-tests
were conducted by the same individuals). Approximately 20% of the sample was
lost to follow-up.
Information was collected from parents in four sessions (one at the beginning
and end, and at the end of the second and fourth weeks).<p>
<p>
	Results of the experiment may be summarised as follows:<p>
<p>
<ol>	1. <i>On younger children</i>. No significant difference was found in the
developmental level of the experimental vs. control children in the urban area
that could be attributed to the training of older siblings. The lack of a
significant difference must take into account the difficulty of measuring such
changes. In addition, the positive benefits may not be observed in the short-run
but may be manifested at some later point in the developmental process. In the
rural group, for which there was no comparison, improvements were found in each
of the areas measured by the Griffiths test.<p>
<p>
	2. <i>On older children</i>. At the end of the project, the interaction
between older and younger children was observed for 19 pairs in the urban
experimental group, 23 in the urban control group, and 31 in the rural
experimental group.<p>
<p>
	The educational programme was successful in increasing the interest of the
older children in activities that favoured the development of their younger
siblings. Both urban and rural groups of siblings who participated in the
weekly training liked to take care of their younger siblings; they played with
them, fed them, played games, and punished them less. These behaviours were not
apparent in the urban control group. Moreover, the results indicated a tendency
to reinforce or accentuate positive characteristics of interactions. For
instance, improvements were observed in requests, gestating, less
overproduction, and more verbal modelling. In the interaction the younger
children tended to be more attentive to the requests of older children.<p>
<p>
	3. <i>On mothers</i>. Favourable changes were observed in terms of talking
with, and to, the child, being with the child, expressing affection, and
playing. There was some improvement in feeding and hygiene, particularly with
the prevention and treatment of diarrhoea.</ol>

	The results from this experimental project are in general agreement with those
reported form the Jamaican study even though the institutional setting and
conditions for the projects varied tremendously. In both, the older child
received the most benefits. However, in the experimental conditions of the
Colombian study, changes in the behaviour, as well as the knowledge of
parents
were observed. In neither of the studies was there an observable impact on the
younger children that could be attributed specifically to the project. Although
the Colombian study indicated a positive effect on children in the rural areas
neither study reported improvements received by the younger children. The
absence of results may be attributed to the shortcomings of the measurement
techniques rather than an inability of the programme to affect change.<p>
<p>
<b><center>INDIA<br>
The Malvani Project</center></b><p>
<p>
	The Malvani Project, as reviewed by Somerset (1988), began in 1978 as an
ambitious project involving doctors and para-medical
workers responsible for primary health care in the low-income
suburb of Malvani on the outskirts of Bombay. The objectives of this project
were to change awareness, attitudes, and practices of the community regarding
preventive health care and community hygiene. To accomplish these objectives,
older children were trained by the local health centre staff as "communicators"
and equipped with the skills and knowledge to affect changes in their own as
well as the community's health.<p>
<p>
	During this initial phase, the results described an extremely successful
initiative. During the first year (1978-1979),
1,330 individuals were identified and brought to the health centre by 600
trained volunteer child health workers. The reported diseases included 471
cases of scabies, 233 cases of vitamin deficiency, and 150 cases of
tuberculosis. As the programme progressed, the preparation of oral rehydration
solution became a major activity.<p>
<p>
	In order to maintain the level of programme effectiveness, the project moved
from the health centre into the schools. In this scheme, a team of health
centre personnel worked with teachers to incorporate practical health
information into the science curriculum. A team of seven para-professionals
visited the schools twice each week to instruct students in the following
areas: Immunisation, Vitamin B Complex, Anemia, Tuberculosis, Malaria, and
Leprosy. Formal classroom instruction was combined with a variety of action-oriented
activities including outings, plays, public performances, and community
surveys.<p>
<p>
	The following summarizes the results available at the present time.<p>
<ol>	1. <i>On older children</i>. Students increased their knowledge and skills
related to the detection and treatment of disease and nutrition-related
disorders. Results from an anemia survey of 1,815 students implemented by the
trained child health workers found that 36% of those surveyed had positive
signs. Of these, 19% were confirmed anemic. In addition, reports indicated high
rates of immunisation as a result of a Child-to-Child
campaign.<p>
<p>

	2. <i>On the community</i>. The work of the volunteer health educators was
reflected in the community's increased awareness and need for preventive health
programmes thus reducing the need for curative intervention. For example, a
community survey was conducted in which the trained child health volunteers
found clinical signs of anemia in 27% of the 2,354 community members
examined.</ol>

	Qualitative reports of the Malvani project were highly favourable. The student
participants were exposed to an unusual set of teaching opportunities which
stressed observation, enquiry, and the practical application of information.
The pupils taking part were exposed to a set of learning opportunities. The
project's implicit message is that education can be more than just preparation
for life in the future, it can also enhance enjoyment of the present.<p>
<p>
<b><center>INDIA<br>
Mobile Creche/Child-to-Child,
Bombay</center></b><p>
<p>
	Mobile Creche is a voluntary organization which provides care and education to
the children of migrant construction workers. Mobile Creches are located at a
construction site in a part of an unfinished building or in a separate
structure. A team of four to five workers and teachers organizes the day care
programme for children who range in age from 2 weeks to 12 years. Each unit
consists of an infant creche, preschool, and a primary school. There is a
strong emphasis on preventive health through visits by medical personnel. Two
meals are prepared on the premises for the children who eat, play, study, and
rest within this sheltered surrounding.<p>
<p>
	The Mobile Creche began in Delhi in 1969. Today 21 centres in New Delhi
provide services to approximately 1,500-1,800
children. In Bombay the programme, which began in 1972, provides services to
approximately 1,800 children through the 19 creches currently in operation.
Children attending the creche come from homes characterized by extreme levels
of deprivation. Their parents, migrants who have come from rural areas in
search of work, are marginalized not only by poverty and illiteracy but also by
a language barrier which cuts them off from the mainstream of city life. Both
parents work on the construction site and older children are responsible for
the care of infants and young children, A major goal of the Mobile Creche
project is to relieve older children of this burden and give them access to
opportunities for cognitive and personal growth available to their more
privileged peers. (Annual Reports: Mobile Creche, 1986-1987).<p>
	Usually a child attends a creche for as long as his parents are employed on
the building site where the centre is located. While the period is often less
then a year, for many this may be their only educational opportunity. The
programme aims to develop basic cognitive competencies including literacy,
numeracy, and simple health knowledge as rapidly as possible, In achieving
these goals much emphasis is placed on activity-based
methods. Children work together in small groups using a variety of teacher-made
learning materials. Because the groups are of mixed age, older children provide
a great deal of help to younger children, the majority of which occurs
spontaneously and informally. Thus, the pattern of care familiar to all
children residing in communities served by the Mobile Creche is simply
transferred into the creche centres.<p>
<p>
	In Bombay, Mobile Creche has formally incorporated Child-to-Child
activities into its programmes. To facilitate implementation and evaluation of
programme impact, the content has been limited to several topics including
personal hygiene, environmental hygiene, water-borne
diseases, and balanced diet and vitamins. In this programme, efforts are made
to use the primary school children as conveyors of health messages to their
younger siblings as well as parents and the community.<p>
<p>
	At present, Child-to-Child
is treated as a separate subject with its own place in the daily set of
activities. The long-term
goal is to develop a fully integrated health, numeracy and literacy curriculum.
Based on materials developed and designed by mobile Creche teachers, Child-to-Child
activities include: action songs, role plays/skits, story telling, posters,
puppetry, games, matching cards, and student teaching. Although a parental
involvement component was initially conceived, it has been difficult for
teachers to interact directly with parents. Thus, much of the activities focus
on the child as the "message communicator" to parents and families.<p>
<p>
	Efforts have been made to assess the impact of Child-                
to-                                                                                        
Child
activities on the overall functioning of the creche. A variety of data
collection techniques have been utilized, including: case studies; interviews
with teachers, project managers, and children; diaries; and direct observation.
Based on the preliminary findings from the application of these techniques on a
sample of Bombay's creches combined with the insights from the direct
observations of the programme, the following comments are offered. (Somerset,
1988).<p>
<p>
<ol>	1. <i>Children</i>. Based on teacher interviews, the Child-to-Child
Programme has helped reinforce skills and focus attention on new health
information. Given the limited time most children spend in the creche, efforts
are continuously made to repeat the message in as many forms as possible. The
teachers interviewed indicated that children have started to use dust bins,
food is covered, and an improvement in personal cleanliness was observed.
According to the reports, it was more difficult to engage children in community
activities and they cautioned that the popularization of songs may at times de-emphasize
the importance of the content of the health messages.<p>
<p>
	2.<i> Parents</i>. Based on parental interviews, Child-to-Child
messages have reached the parents particularly as related to the use of 0RS and
other dietary habits including the negative impact of alcohol, pan, and chewing
tobacco. The majority of parents, recognizing the value of this information,
accepted the communication of these messages by their children.<p>
<p>
	3. <i>Teachers</i>. The success of the programme is largely attributed to the
efforts of teachers in all phases of programme design and development, An
unanticipated benefit of the programme was the positive impact on the teacher
both in terms of health knowledge gained as well as opportunity to design and
implement creative teaching strategies.</ol>
	In summary, it appears that the success of the Mobile Creche's Child-to-Child
programmes lies in the participatory management style as well as its on-the-job
training programme and follow up. The participatory management style fosters
joint decision making through consultation at all levels of the organization.
Teachers are included, motivated and encouraged to develop curriculum materials
and innovative methods. Management is deeply committed to their staff and as
such foster a non-hierarchial
interactive managerial style. The establishment of this mode of operation is
facilitated by the voluntary nature of Mobile Creche and the absence of formal
rules and procedures characteristic of other bureaucratic organizations. The
relatively small size of the organization encourages such managerial style. If
the number of sites were to increase substantially, one wonders whether
management would become more formalized and grass-roots
participation in decision-making
and problem-solving would diminish.<p>
<p>
<b><center>BOTSWANA<br>
The Botswana Child-to-Child Project</center></b><p>
<p>
	Child-to-Child
projects have been initiated in many African countries and focus largely on
health activities. The Botswana project was selected because of its emphasis on
the educational and psychological components of the Child-to-Child
Programme.<p>
<p>
	It has been found that a number of children in Botswana, especially in the
rural areas, have difficulty adjusting to school life. (Government of Botswana,
1986). The setting is unfamiliar, the teachers strange, and much of what they
encounter, books, pencils, crayons, etc,, are often foreign to their previous
experience. If children can become familiar with concepts such as these before
beginning school, the adjustment process is made easier, and the formal
education process begins sooner and with less difficulty. (Otaala, B.1984;
1987).<p>
<p>
	As described by Somerset (1988), the Child-to-Child
Programme in Botswana has been designed to provide informal preschool education
for young children while enhancing the educational experience of older, primary-level
children. The older children ("little teachers") help prepare the younger
children ("preschoolers") for school entry and in turn enhance their own
cognitive and affective development. Beginning in 1979 with two schools, the
programme is now in operation in 28 schools reaching approximately 5,000
children. Formal control of the programme is held by the Board of the Child-to-Child
Foundation of Botswana, which includes representatives from Ministry of
Education and local government, multilateral and bilateral aid donors, and the
American Women's Association.<p>
<p>
	Initially the Child-to-Child
Programme functioned as a one-to-one
outreach programme. "Little teachers" drawn from Standards 1, 2 and 3 (7, 8 and
9 years) received two additional periods of instruction each week. To guide the Child-to-Child
teachers, lesson booklets focussing on four major themes were developed:
"Feelings and Who Am I?," "Preparing for School," "Health in the Home," and
"The Village." More recently, greater emphasis is being placed on the
development of school readiness skills including drawing, writing and number
skills.<p>
<p>
	Since 1981, the programme has shifted its emphasis from out-of-school
to in-school
activities. Preschoolers come to school several times each week to participate
in Child-to-Child
sessions in which each preschooler is paired with a little teacher. Although
there is programme variability between schools, the work of the little teachers
is divided between school and home. Child-to-Child
teachers herd a training session for the little teachers before each visit by
the preschoolers. Although teachers are present during the in-school
sessions for the preschoolers, their role is mainly organisational and
supportive. Most of the instruction is delivered by the little teachers.<p>
<p>
	After the in-school
sessions, the pair continues to work at home practicing writing letters and
numbers and learning simple songs and games. Sometimes the little teacher uses
a worksheet prepared during the training sessions, but often the children write
in the sand, using a finger as a writing instrument. In the next training
session with the Child-to-Child
teachers, the little teacher has an opportunity to report on his experience
during these home lessons. Thus, the demand for an in-school
programme for the preschoolers has been met, but at the same time the original
programme for the little teachers has been maintained.<p>
<p>
	Several factors have contributed to the shift in focus from the home to the
school, Child-to-Child
teachers felt that the original approach did not allow enough opportunity to
supervise the work of the little teachers. Furthermore, the organisation of home-based
programmes is likely to have caused problems that could be easily avoided by
moving the activities to the school. However, parental demand for
institutionalised preschool education has perhaps been the most important
factor in the recent shift. In Botswana, as in many other developing countries,
the value of preschool education has risen steadily over recent years. As
competition for formal employment has intensified, parents have sought to
provide children with educational opportunities that will improve their chance
of success. It is believed that children who get an early start to their
education have an advantage in this competition.<p>
<p>
	Unfortunately, little quantitative systematic information of the impact of
this programme on its beneficiaries is available. However, given the rapid
expansion and acceptance of this programme, it has been considered a tremendous
success. Several qualitative studies and feedback substantiate its
accomplishments. The following summarizes the benefits accrued by the intended
audiences.<p>
<ol>	1. <i>Younger children</i>. In one of the schools, a Child-to-Child
Programme has been running long enough for the first group of preschoolers to
complete primary school. In this school, results in the Primary School Leaving
Examination (PSLE) showed a sharp improvement in 1986 - the first year that there had been ex-preschoolers
among the candidates. Both the headmistress and the Chairman of the Parent
Teachers Association are convinced that the Child-to-Child
Programme has played a major role in this improvement. This success is largely
attributed to the programme's ability to provide the preschool child with
opportunities to explore the school environment gradually, making the
difficulty transition to primary school a positive experience.<p>
<p>
	A second advantage of this approach is the invaluable impact of one-to-one
tutoring in the young child's acquisition of basic cognitive, psychomotor, and
social skills. Finally little teachers are important as "communication
facilitators," since preschoolers speaking local dialects are often
misunderstood by the adult teachers.<p>
<p>
	2. <i>Older children</i>. The "little teachers" have increased self-
                                                                                        
confidence
and sense of responsibility through assisting in the instruction of younger
children. Moreover, many teachers reported improved performance in the basic
early learning skills which come from the additional training and attention
received.<p>
<p>
<p>
	3. <i>Parents and community</i>. The parents of children involved in this
programme are exposed to the school system and its operation, thereby
benefiting from the message that reaches them on health and education issues.
In addition, the programme has the ability to favourably impact a parents'
knowledge, attitude, and beliefs towards the importance of educating the
preschool child.<p>
<p>
	4. <i>Teachers and school system</i>. Teachers are exposed to and have the
opportunity to implement a set of new teaching methodologies and approaches.
Through this programme teachers have the opportunity to design receptive
learning with activity based approaches which assist children in the
construction of their own knowledge. Moreover, through the success of the
little teachers, teachers are themselves relieved of much of the time and
energy devoted to the adaptation of children to the first year of school.
Finally, the efforts of this initiative have been both a vehicle for extending
the availability of preschool education and for enhancing the quality of
primary education in the early years of school.</ol>
	From these case studies, a number of preliminary conclusions regarding
programme emphasis and results begin to emerge. However, before attempting to
extract these lessons, we turn to a description of the activities and
experience of the London-based Child-to-Child
Programme which seeks to institutionalize and promote the idea of children
caring for children around the world.<p>
<p>
<b><center>SECTION IV<br>

The Child-to-Child
Programme<br>
University of  London<br>
Institution Child Health and Education</center></b><p>
<p>
	Child-to-Child
is an international programme which was conceived by the Institute of Child
Health of the University of London, together with an International Committee,
to mark the International Year of the Child (IYC) in 1979. The programme moves
to yet another level the adaptation and institutionalisation of the idea of
children caring for children by promoting
the idea widely and providing assistance in getting local projects started.<p>
<p>
	The Child-to-Child
Programme is intended to teach and encourage older children, especially school
children, to concern themselves with the health and general development of
their younger brothers and sisters, or other young children in their community.
It pursues its goal by developing and providing materials tied to an
established and tested method, by giving start-up
financing and technical assistance to local or national programmes, and by
disseminating information about the Child-to-Child
approach, directly in workshops and meetings called for that purpose, and
indirectly through publications and a newsletter. A description of Child-to-Child
materials<p>
prepared and distributed by the Institutes is presented in Appendix I.<p>
<p>
	First and foremost an educational programme, Child-to-Child
encourages an active participatory approach to learning and teaching. The
originators of the programme, emphasize the importance of teachers perceiving
their role as helping children to help each other and to help their
communities. They suggest that in playing this helper role, teachers need to:<p>
<p>
<ul><li> Explore with children what the needs, problems and priorities in their
communities are ("find out"),<p>
<p>
	 <li>Discuss together ways of meeting these problems using what is already
available ("talk it over"),<p>
<p>
	 <li>Seek sympathetic understanding of other people's feelings and views (through
role playing, drama and other methods),<p>
<p>
	 <li>Design activities which will help, which will be acceptable, and which can
easily be 	undertaken, and<p>
<p>
	 <li>Be constantly ready to improve programmes in the light of experience
gained.</ul>
	The "teacher" may be a primary school teacher or a primary health care worker
or youth leader or another. And, the primary-school
aged children become teachers as well. The general strategy for working with
school-aged
children and communities is set out in a book titled <i>Child-to-Child</i>,
published in 1979 and now translated into several languages.<p>
<p>
	For the most part, projects affiliated with the Child-to-Child
programme have been carried out through primary schools or primary health care
centres. The primary school seems to be the central vehicle because many rural
areas in the Third World have at least one primary school, allowing coverage
over a wide area. In addition, the primary school teacher is usually a
respected and accepted figure, helping assure acceptance of the idea and the
programme at the local level. Primary health care centres also offer a good
entry point for a Child-to-Child
programme, as staff from these centres visit homes and schools and other
institutions where they can introduce activities from the programme.<p>
<p>
	The content of the materials produced by the Child-to-Child
programme covers various aspects of child care. Specific areas of concern
include: health related actions, nutrition and growth, prevention of accidents,
fostering mental and social development through play, and creating a supportive
environment. The selection of these areas was based on two main considerations:
(1) their importance in the hierarchy of problems in the community and
particularly their relevance to the health of young children, and (2)
availability of a realistic role for a primary school-aged
child to play in relation to the problem. (Webb, 1985). As these topics are
pursued within local settings, adaptations of priorities and materials in
response to the particular setting is crucial.<p>
<p>
	Topics are treated in a set of "activity sheets" prepared specifically for use
by teachers with the primary school-aged
child. The activities are chosen to fall within the experience of this age
group and lend themselves to constructive, participatory actions. They provide
factual information on a selected topic or subject and suggest relevant
activities in which to involve children in school, at home or in the community.
A list of the topics covered by activity sheets available from the programme is
provided in Appendix II together with an example of activities for one area.<p>
<p>
	In addition, the programme has developed a set of supplementary readers which
can be used in formal classes or as references, but which carry health and
educational messages. These are geared to particular reading levels of primary
school children and written in simple language with appropriate
illustrations.<p>
<p>
<b>The Spread of Child-to-Child</b><p>
<p>
	In the course of the almost 10 years that the international programme has been
functioning, the Child-to-Child
Programme has spread over a wide area. Projects affiliated with the
international programme are now found in at least 48 countries. (Somerset,
1988). This spread has been assisted by the central office in London which, in
addition to providing prepared materials, has organised workshops to enable
local groups to prepare, or update, activity sheets, and to help them launch
local projects.<p>
<p>
	Child-to-Child
affiliated projects are funded locally, often with partial start-up
funding from London. Each country manages its own activities, sometimes through
a Child-to-Child
foundation and sometimes through a relevant government organization such as the
Ministry of Education or Health.                                      <p>
<p>
	Several of the projects previously described in Section III have been assisted
by or originated with the Child-to-Child
Programme in London. Evidence of potential benefits from programmes building on
the practice of children caring for children was indicated by the discussion of
the results of these projects. The Child-to-Child
Programme adds to that evidence with a range of examples. The following section
briefly summarizes the benefits of Child-to-Child
programmes and activities.(l.) The examples are presented in the following
categories:<p>
<p>
<ul><li>	 Child-to-Child
school-based
programmes organized by the Ministry of Education.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Child-to-Child
school-based
programmes organized by the Ministry of Health.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Child-to-Child
Programmes supported by nongovernmental organizations.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Child-to-Child
programmes integrated into the training of medical personnel.</ul>

<b>Child-to-Child
School-Based
Programmes<br>
Organized by the Ministry of Education</b><p>
<p>
<ul><li>	 <i>Burkina Fasso</i>. A co-ordinating
Child-to-Child
unit has been set up to service and assist different initiatives undertaken by
government, ministries and voluntary agencies. Such a unit also initiates and
organises training but in no way "directs" Child-to-Child
activities.<p>
<p>
	 <li><i>Chile</i>. The Child-to-Child
Programme, instituted through the Ministry of Education and initially centred
on health education, uses 12-and 13-year-old
children as "helpers" with young children in rural schools. Each older child is
responsible for about seven young ones. The curriculum has been extended to
include basic skills and value education. The programme has been so successful,
particularly with the "helpers" themselves, that 1-1/2
million children are now affected, and all schools in Chile will be involved in
1988. Much supporting and background material has been produced.<p>
<p>
	 <li><i>Guatemala</i>. This Child-to-Child
Programme emphasises not only health messages but the important role of
children within the educational system. Much material is produced, including a
newsletter, comic strips, and books of writing by children that can be used as
reading material for other children. Children also take part in radio
broadcasts.<p>
<p>
	 <li><i>New Guinea (Papua)</i>. Child-to-Child
approaches emphasising health education have been incorporated into the
community school syllabus. The approach also stresses the relationship of
schools to the community and the responsibility of children. One example is a
publication of a booklet by the Ministry of Education called "Finding out about
our school: Is it healthy?". Children and teachers have a checklist that they
fill out each week, month, and term.<p>
<p>
	 <li><i>Tanzania</i>. A new school health programme emphasising child survival and
development has been launched by the Ministry of Education with support from
UNICEF. Child-to-Child
approaches have been incorporated into this programme and into the teacher
training that accompanies it. Schools use a Swahili translation of Child-to-Child
materials and also Child-to-Child
readers in their English lessons.<p>
<p>
	 <li><i>Zambia</i>. National and local Child-to-Child
Committees have been established throughout the country, with participation
from both the Ministry of Education and the Ministry of Health. Local
committees have considerable autonomy to adapt approaches in schools. Child-to-Child
concentrates particularly on certain key health priorities, e.g., oral
rehydration, immunisation, nutrition; and emphasises the use of children as
information gatherers and communicators within their communities.</ul>
<b>Child-to-Child School-Based Programmes<br> 
Organized by the Ministry of Health</b><p>
<p>
<ul><li><i>Bangladesh</i>. A school health magazine, Mitali, has been produced by
UNICEF. It is specifically aimed at children who take care of their younger
brothers and sisters, and is entirely based on Child-to-Child
activities.<p>
<p>
	 <li><i>Liberia</i>. A locally produced Child-to-Child
booklet is issues by the Ministry of Health and used with school children. The
Child-to-Child
readers prove useful, and children are encouraged to tell the stories to their
parents.<p>
<p>
	 <li><i>Nepal</i>. Child-to-Child
materials and approaches have been used extensively by the Health Education
Unit of the Urban Development programme in Kathmandu. School children are
initiated into the activities by their teachers. They form teams and take the
messages to younger children in school, to children outside schools, and to
their families and communities. Some 10,000 children are said to be involved.<p>
<p>
	 <li><i>Oman</i>. Following a national seminar organised at the Ministry of
Health, plans are now being developed to spread the ideas widely through the
school system. Ministries of Education and Culture as well as UNICEF and other
voluntary agencies are all cooperating.<p>
<p>
	 <li><i>Zimbabwe</i>. Child-to-Child
activities are being undertaken both nationally and provincially. In one
province teachers are encouraged to include activities in their social studies
teaching, and at the same time the activities are reproduced informally through
the school health magazine, which is provided as a resource for all teachers.</ul>
<b>Child-to-Child Programmes<br>
Supported by Nongovernmental Organisations</b><p>
<ul><li><i>Angola</i>. The Children living in the area surrounding the Bongo Mission
Hospital were gathered once a week for three months in the village church and
presented with different topics of Child-to-activity sheets.<p>
<p>
	 <li><i>Indonesia (Jakarta)</i>. A "little doctor" programme is in operation.
Children in school are specially selected to receive "little doctor" status.
Once appointed, they work with the school health officer and have certain
specific duties to perform. They must also keep records of community hygiene
and report findings. Similar Health Scout programmes are reported in Peru and
Pakistan.<p>
<p>
	 <li><i>Kenya (Nairobi)</i>, A group of Health Scouts, working from a community
centre in Mathare Valley, was able through the use of songs to spread health
messages. Similar programmes are described in South Africa.<p>
<p>
	 <li><i>Nigeria</i>. The Boy Scouts of Nigeria use Child-to-Child
activities in various states. Emphasis is particularly on community hygiene and
safety. Training and awards for proficiency are given. Similar activities are
reported from the <i>People's Republic of Benin</i>.<p>
<p>
	 <li><i>Pakistan</i>. The Aga Khan School Health Service provides Child-to-Child
material both to teachers and to social workers and has prepared much
additional material. Some 12,000 school  children are affected. The Aga Khan
Foundation in partnership with UNICEF also gives substantial support to six
programmes in India.<p>
<p>
	 <li><i>Sierra Leone</i>. Plan International, a community development and foster
parent's agency, produces its own local version of Child-to-Child
material especially aimed at poor families. The programme trains teachers,
organises children's talks and plays, and maintains a monthly "reporting
session" by siblings on the growth and development of their younger brothers
and sisters using an "under five" clinic card.<p>
<p>
	 <li><i>Sudan</i>. Secondary school pupils (11-13
years of age) in the Eastern and Northern Gezira Province operate a Health
Scout Project under the direction of an area coordinator. Each school is
divided into Health Scout Committees under the supervision of a Master. Each
Committee takes an area, and each pupil takes three families. The pupil is then
responsible for teaching and monitoring certain key health priorities within
these families.<p>
<p>
	 <li><i>Uganda</i>. An association of Child-to-Child
schools exists, which is organised by a committee of teachers with funds
provided mainly from a group of parallel schools in Norway. Child-to-Child
schools carry out health-based
activities within those schools and in the community. Much material has been
produced including a calendar; a childrens' magazine, and a book written by
children and teachers. Other activities include the production of radio
programmes, and health campaigns carried out within their communities.</ul>
<b>Child-to-Child Programmes with Special Focus</b><p>
<p>
	<b>Focus On Handicapped Children</b>:<p>
<p>
<ul><li> <i>Honduras</i>. Students in the Department of Special Education in one of
the Teachers Colleges (Escuela Normal) are taught how to help school children
make apparatus for handicapped students.<p>
<p>
	 <li><i>India (Andra Pradesh)</i>. Since 1982, activities have been organised in
Tirupati with "child leaders" identified to spread messages in schools,
families, and communities in the slum areas. A particular emphasis is being
placed on the identification and prevention of eye diseases and even more so on
the causes of these - poor nutrition, failure to immunise, and poor personal hygiene. The programme
has received funding from the Royal Commonwealth Society for the Blind.<p>
<p>
	 <li><i>Kenya</i>. A number of schools, with encouragement from the Charity Action
Aid (which also organises similar programmes in other countries), have taken
action to help local schools for handicapped children. Child-to-Child
material has been specially adapted.<p>
<p>
	 <li><i>Mexico</i>. Project Projimo, located in western Mexico, is a
community-based
project for the disabled. Project members, themselves usually disabled
villagers, cooperate to make aids for disabled children. Child-to-Child
cooperation is constantly stressed, and many of the project workers are
children and youth.</ul>

	<b>Focus On Refugee Children</b>:<p>
<p>
<ul><li> <i>Djibouti</i>. Child-to-Child
material was used to teach children attending feeding centre in refugee camps.
At the same time, community health workers were trained in the use of Child-to-Child
messages for children in the villages.<p>
<p>
	 <li><i>Somalia</i>. Following a Child-to-Child
seminar in 1986 activities have been designed for refugee children. Child-to-Child
activities are also being used with refugees in Lebanon, Thailand, and Pakistan
(for Afghan refugees).</ul>

	
<b>Focus On Street and Other Displaced Children</b>:<p>
<p>
<ul>	 <li><i>Brazil (Itabuna Municipality)</i>. "Childrens' farms" have been
established for street children organised by the Mayor and his wife who are one
of the original founders of the Child-to-Child
Programme in Brazil. In this environment, children of' all ages work
together.<p>
<p>
	 <li><i>Philippines (Manila)</i>. The LINGAP Centre in Manila gives alternative
education for street children and abused children. Children work in groups of 10-12
with games, role-playing,
and group sharing. They learn to help each other and to apply the Child-to-Child
messages outside the Centre.</ul>
	<b>Focus On Children in Hospitals</b>:<p>
<ul><li> <i>India (Baroda)</i>. Older children in the pediatric ward make puppets and
read stories to the younger ones. After leaving they were encouraged to take
Child-to-Child
messages back to their villages. Similar activities are reported from Kenya
(Northern Province) where children in hospital wards have been encouraged to
read and translated Child-to-Child
readers to younger or non-school
children.</ul>

	<b>Focus On Children in Remote Areas</b>:<p>
<p>
<ul><li>	 <i>India (Maharashtra)</i>. Children of health workers who travel into tribal
areas regard themselves as child health workers and are taught to work with
local children. Qualities such as, understanding and humility are particularly
emphasised so that they will be trusted and accepted.</ul>

<b>Child-to-Child Programmes<br> 
Integrated Into the Training of Medical Personnel</b><p>
<p>
<ul><li>	 <i>Indonesia (Samarang)</i>. In the Department of Community Health in the
Faculty of Medicine all students are required to study the Child-to-Child
approach. The use of Child-to-Child
also forms part of their practical training. A team of' faculty members has
adapted the Child-to-Child
material to meet the particular context and purpose of the training.<p>
<p>
	 <li><i>Nigeria (Lagos)</i>. Child-to-Child
activities are integrated into the programme for teaching medical students and
community health care officers at the Institute of Child Health and Primary
Care at the College of Medicine, University of Lagos. The college also
maintains contact with local primary schools and tries out materials there.
Children also gather information about health problems under the direction of
the Institute.<p>
<p>
	 <li><i>Tanzania (Zanzibar)</i>. Child-to-Child
activities and approaches are used in the training of nurses. Because of the
educational and language levels of the nurses, it has been found that the Child-to-Child
readers are a very suitable means of conveying messages to them. In <i>Sri
Lanka</i> Child-to-Child
is similarly used in the university-based
training for child care workers.</ul>
<b><center>SECTION V<br>
Conclusions and Recommendations</center></b><p>
<p>
	While the practice of older children caring for younger siblings is
decreasing, as a result of changing family structures and increasing school
enrollments, it still occurs at significant levels in many parts of the third
World. As this review suggests, "children caring for children" provides one
alternative in a range of programme options intended to improve early childhood
care and development. Increasingly, justification for these Child-to-Child
efforts lies in their positive effect on the primary school child who increases
his level of health information as well as parenting skills. In addition, their
participation in the programme has had a direct impact on behaviours which
support an enhanced child rearing environment.<p>
<p>
	As a conscious strategy to improve child health and development, Child-to-Child
programmes are barely a decade old. What can be learned from this decade of
actions? Is the idea accepted?  Does it work to enhance the knowledge,
attitudes, and practices of older children, parents and communities? Does it
improve the health of younger children under their care? What content, methods,
and organization seem to be most effective? How can programmes be sustained?
This review has attempted to provide some preliminary responses to these
questions.<p>
<p>
<b>Is the Idea Accepted?</b><p>
<p>
	It is clear that the concept of children caring for children provides an
acceptable and even sought-after
basis for programming to improve the well-being
of children, families, and communities. This acceptance is evident in the rapid
spread of successful Child-to-child
programmes both as independent initiatives and those affiliated and promoted by
the Institutes of Child Health and Education in London. The Child-to-Child
idea that is currently being promoted and accepted is primarily a creative and
effective health education programme focussing on older primary school
children. In this recent set of initiatives, little attention is focussed
directly on the
immediate care and development of the younger child. Although the merits of
Child-to-Child
programmes emphasizing health education, and the acceptance of that strategy
are real and should not be minimized, it is important to recognize a shift in
most programmes away from the traditional practice of children caring for
children which provided the starting point.<p>
<p>
<b>Does It Work? For Whom?</b><p>
<p>
	Reports of the benefits of successful Child-to-Child
activities to older and younger children, families, schools, and communities
are numerous. Many of these reports are anecdotal, but they support the
relatively few systematic evaluations that have been carried out.
                    <p>
	<ol>1. <i>Older children</i>. In their dual role as the providers and recipients
of Child-to-Child
activities, older children benefit directly in terms of increased knowledge of
health, nutrition, and education, improved health practices and beliefs, and
more nurturing attitudes towards younger siblings. In addition to these
positive outcomes, older children receive benefits through their role as
"message carriers" to younger siblings and other children within the community.
In the process, children develop a sense of increased self-esteem
and confidence through school-based
and/or community activities, Moreover, it is expected that these newly acquired
skills and the emphasis on preventive rather than curative solutions to health
problems will exert an intergenerational effect on the offspring of these soon-to-be
parents.<p>
<p>
	2. <i>Family and community</i>. Families and communities have benefited from
the dissemination of health knowledge designed to change negative practices and
from surveys of health problems made by older children leading to
identification of cases needing attention to conditions requiring corrective
actions. Finally, communities have benefited from direct actions to improve the
environment and community conditions, such as cleaning up garbage and helping
to build latrines.<p>
<p>
3. <i>Teachers and schools</i>. The activity-oriented,
participatory approach used in many Child-to-Child
programmes often provides an appealing alternative to teachers seeking escape
from traditional practices. Moreover, this approach provides a low-cost
opportunity to enhance the quality of primary school health education. School-based
health education is generally integrated into the science curriculum, with
sparse coverage of such critical topics as the prevention and treatment of
diarrhoea. Child-to-Child
activities, emphasizing a creative and active approach to learning, have
strengthened the primary school's health education curriculum. In some cases,
the programmes have dramatically improved the health conditions and
environments of the schools.<p>
<p>
	4. <i>Younger children</i>. From the data reviewed, benefits to younger
children are somewhat  more difficult to capture and define. Programmers
assumed that younger children would benefit directly from the activities
performed with them or indirectly through the benefits received by older
children, parents, or teachers. The absence of adequate documentation reflects,
in part, the shift toward programmes concentrating on older children. This
situation is further complicated by the fact that influencing the nutritional
status or the psycho-social
development of young children is a continuous and long-term
process, influenced by many factors. Thus, it is difficult to measure the short-term
impact of interventions. At the same time however, a number of programmes
claimed direct and measurable effects through the identification, treatment and
reduction of scabies and through an increase in levels of immunisation promoted
though the
programme.</ul>
<b>What Is Effective?</b><p>
<p>
	<i>Linkages and integration</i>. For a variety of reasons; Child-to-Child
activities linked to and integrated within existing programmes are most
effective. Efforts to design new programmes creates competition that is seldom
welcomed. Experience suggests that schools are the most promising collaborating
institution. In most Third World countries, there are many more schools and
teachers than there are health facilities and health workers. Moreover,
substantial portion of school-aged
children attend school where they provide a captive audience for programme
implementation.<p>
<p>
	While many programmes illustrate the potential of schools to mount effective
programmes a range of complex barriers and constraints can undercut
effectiveness. These include absence of financial and material resources, low
levels of teacher morale and qualification, high rates of turnover, and teacher
overload. The ability of programmes to overcome such barriers is enhanced when
they have the active involvement and support not only of educators, health care
providers, and community workers, but also of policy-makers
and administrators. Success is also enhanced through proper training of
teachers and by assuring that the programme does not constitute an extra burden
but is, rather built upon and related to knowledge that they are expected to
impart within the regular curriculum. Teachers, through a system of rewards and
incentives, should be encouraged to design and implement creative teaching
strategies.<p>
<p>
	In addition, children-caring-for-children
programmes must be closely integrated with other ongoing programmes and
institutions operating within the schools and community, including women's
groups, child care programmes, primary health care centres, and youth groups. A
possible drawback to some school-based Child-to-Child approaches is their treatment as a separate classroom subject isolated both by
distinctive content and innovative teaching methodologies. In the long run,
this isolation renders projects vulnerable to the withdrawal of resource
support after the initial funding period. By contrast, the programmes that
persist beyond an initial critical period are those that both enhance and
strengthen existing curricula.<p>
<p>
	<i>Methods and materials</i>. Experience suggests that health education
materials developed for use in primary schools should be kept simple and
practical, written in easily understood language, and well illustrated. The
teaching methods used, where possible, should be discovery based, and encourage
children to observe, ask questions and come to conclusions for themselves.<p>
<p>
	Also effective are programmes which include:<p>
<p>
<ul><li>	 A demonstrative, participatory, problem-solving
approach;<p>
<p>
	 <li>A "child-centered" approach;<p>
<p>
	 <li>An integrated approach, involving content about health and nutrition and
child development;<p>
<p>
	 <li>An approach using varied materials and teaching techniques; and,<p>
<p>
	 <li>An approach involving applications - learning-by-doing.</ul>    
	One element of learning-by-doing
that, as suggested above, seems to have been left aside in many programmes is
the application of what is learned in direct care for younger children.
Although it is clear that not all primary school children will have younger
brothers and sisters, it is still possible to "adopt" a younger child as part
of the programme (a first grader, for instance). The obligation to work with
the younger child means that older children must learn what they are to teach,
must be good role models, and must practice. There is a strong argument,
therefore, for reintroducing the younger child more prominently into the
programme.<p>
<p>
	<i>Cultural sensitivity</i>. The material discussed within this review
emphasizes that an understanding of cultural values is essential to child care
and development programming. Programmes are most effective when the content
focusses on problems that are salient and relevant to the concerns expressed by
the community. This can be accomplished through the recognition of positive
practices, not merely discouraging negative practices. Thus, programming must
be flexible, in order to encourage possibilities of local adaption and cultural
adjustment to a changing array of child health care and developmental concerns.
There is a challenge to design activities that capitalize on existing positive
beliefs and practices at the same time that they discourage those that may be
harmful.<p>
<p>
	One set of cultural sensitivities refers to beliefs about disease and its
treatment:. Do mothers withhold food and drink when a child has diarrhoea? Why?
Are there home remedies for diarrhoea that are effective that are different
from the ones being recommended from outside?<p>
<p>
	Another set of cultural sensitivities has to do with communication strategies,
both with respect to content and as they are related to social relationships.
In what circumstances can a child be expected to communicate what kinds of'
messages to parents and community members?<p>
<p>
	In the first place, messages should be couched in the local language. These
may involve an analysis of  local vocabulary. Second, messages need to be
tested and revised before widely used. Third, programmes should respect local
protocol. Experience in Child-to-Child
programmes shows that children often bring home ideas that are considered
radical and challenging, If parents have fixed ideas not only about content,
but also about protocol - when a child can speak and whether they are allowed
to say things that contradict their parents - then messages are often
ignored.<p>
<p>
	In programmes where the emphasis is on the older child as a communicator to
adults, the question of culturally related communication strategies is not a
trivial one. For example, in many African countries, respect for age is
emphasised in the child's upbringing. Fafunwa (1974) states: "Age is an
important element in the life of the African. Reverence for those who are older
than one is particularly strong among the Yoruba....The elder is assumed to be
a man or woman of wisdom and he is expected to demonstrate this in speech and
action lest he lose his position in the company of those who look up to him for
leadership" (page 5). Under this relationship, situations where a child would
feel encouraged to pass health messages to parents and community must be
cautiously conceived.<p>
<p>
	Suggestions about how to overcome or at least allay the suspicions and
resistance of the parents and community to messages brought to them by school
children have been made by several programme developers. For example,
information should be presented with respect for the knowledge of the parents
and the traditions of the community. Parents must understand what it is their
children are doing, and children should not be placed in a position to
criticize or contradict their parents' behaviour, especially in the presence of
others.<p>
<p>
	Parents' fears may be partially allayed through discussion, newsletters
(possible only when adults can read) and entertainment-evenings
with skits and role-plays
that transmit the health messages that are being taught to children. To ensure
a correct approach teachers or youth leaders should encourage children to
practice "passing messages" to adults.<p>
<p>
<b>What Can Be Done to Promote Institutional<br> 
Innovation and to Sustain
Programmes?</b><p>
<p>
	The question of programme sustainability is particularly significant
considering recent reviews (Fuerstein, 1981; Somerset, 1988) of Child-to-Child
activities which revealed the difficulty in sustaining programmes over time.
Research evidence suggests that for one to institutionalise a new programme or
innovation, attention focussed on the following factors is crucial: (1)
adopter, (2) change agent, and (3) participatory control. For example, if the
<u>adopter</u> perceives that the innovative process or the social system in
which they work is supportive of the programme, he may react positively to it.
Secondly, if <u>change agents</u>: (1) incorporates adopters in the decision-making
process surrounding the selection, development, and training of an innovation,
(2) does not separate the role of the programme implementor from the local
national staff, (3) listens to or acknowledges adopter concerns, the
programme's chance of survival is increased. A system based on models such as
problem-solving,
social interaction, or linkage, in which the change agent collaborates closely
with the adopter population might assist the agent in avoiding the resentment
and apathy frequently evident. Finally, <u>participation</u> of local adopters
as early as possible within the innovation process is essential, and they
should be actively engaged in the definition of programme goals and
objectives.<p>
<p>
<b>Recommendations</b><p>
<p>
	Based on the foregone review, it is suggested that tile following
recommendations be considered in the design and implementation of programmes
based on children caring for children.<p>
<p>
<ol>	1. Continued support should be given to experimentation with and extension of
programmes based on the principle of children caring for children.<p>
<p>
	2. When introducing such a programme:<p>
<p>
<ul><li>		 Use a participatory model from the beginning of the process.<p>
<p>
		 <li>Incorporate participants into decisions about initial selection, development
and introduction.<p>
<p>
		 <li>Set up a coordinating body from various groups involved in and affected by
the programme.<p>
<p>
		 <li>Base training and the development of materials on a valid needs assessment,
with sensitivity to cultural differences.<p>
<p>
		 <li>Build-in
continuous assessment of the programmes.<p>
<p>
		 <li>Attach to ongoing programmes.<p>
<p>
		 <li>Avoid dependence solely on donor agencies for funding.</ul>
<p>
	3. Reassess ways in which the cross-age
concept can be refined and strengthened in current Child-to-Child
activities. Older children must be provided with real opportunities to put into
practice the concepts stressed through the programme. In addition to the
current health/nutrition emphasis, the importance of creative and active
interaction of older children with the younger children in their care must
receive renewed programming attention. Programme developers need to more fully
explore the possibilities for pairing primary school children with preschool
children and establishing greater linkages between primary and preschool
institutions.<p>
<p>
	4. Encourage and improve research and programme evaluation of Child-to-Child
programmes.</ol>

	<i>Research</i>. In many Third World countries the current body of knowledge
on the physical, psychological, learning and emotional needs of children is
sketchy and incomplete. Development of children is inextricably interwoven, and
therefore, successful programmes are those based on knowledge of the child in
interaction within his total environment. In order to design more efficient and
effective Child-to-Child
programmes which are based on the needs of the child as perceived and expressed
by the community, it is essential that a research agenda addressing critical
issues in child development be put forth.<p>
<p>
	In this regard, multi-disciplinary
research must be developed to identify the effectiveness of culture-specific
child rearing practices, patterns and beliefs, with particular attention to
their relevance in today's changing and economically constrained environment.
Country-specific reviews should identify and analyze positive practices which could be
reinforced and strengthened as well as the practices which negatively impact
upon health and development. In addition, research designed to understand the
complex set of interactions between the health, nutritional, and psycho-social
aspects of development must be conducted.<p>
<p>
	<i>Programme evaluation</i>. The investigation of the impact of programmes on
recipients has been plagued by the set of constraints confronting the
evaluation of all service-oriented
programmes. Thus the design of programme evaluation strategies utilizing both
quantitative and qualitative techniques must become a priority. Such search
should be designed to systematically address the following set of issues in
Child-to-Child
programmes.<p>
<ul><li>	 What are the short- and long-term
impacts of the programme? How effective is the approach for changing the
knowledge, beliefs, and attitudes of the intended programme audience? Is the
programme able to enhance positive behaviours of younger and older children,
parents, families, schools, and communities?<p>
<p>
	 <li>Who are the most responsive recipients of this programming approach? What are
the important antecedent variables derived from a child's background and
experience that influence an individual's ability to respond successfully to
the programme?<p>
<p>
	 <li>How can projects and activities be modified to reach the children at highest
risk?<p>
<p>
	 <li>What are the contextual and environmental factors that contribute to a
programme's success, such as institutional setting, programme incentives,
training, and teaching methods?<p>
<p>
	 <li>Which teaching and learning methodologies are most effective in transmitting
competency? What incentives drive the project?<p>
<p>
	 <li>What happens to the impact of programmes when they move from small-scale
projects to broad-based
programmes reaching large numbers of beneficiaries?</ul>
	In summary, given both the widespread acceptance and rapid spread of
programmes capitalizing upon the idea of children caring for children
throughout this past decade, the resulting programme adaptations and shifts in
emphasis suggested through this review seem to have some merit. While no one
paradigm or model can be described, it is hoped that this discussion has
succeeded in its effort to identify and understand the complex set of factors
which enhance and constrain the design and implementation of effective
children-caring-for-children programmes<p>
<p>
