<b><center>APPENDIX I<br>

Child-to-Child
Programme Materials:<br>
Insitutes of Child Health and Education<br>
University of London (1.)</center></b><p>
<p>
	1. <i>Child-to-Child
Book</i>. Prepared for the International Year of the Child, this book describes
how older children can help younger children's health and development. Now in
its fifth printing, it has been translated into many languages, including
French, Spanish, Portuguese, Arabic, Indonesia, Telugu, Swahili, and Lesotho.<p>
<p>
	2. <i>Child-to-Child
Readers</i>. These booklets use stories to teach children health messages while
learning to read. Six booklets have been prepared: (1) Dirty Water, (2) Good
Food, (3) Accidents, (4) A Simple Cure, (5) Teaching Thomas, and (6) Down with
Fever, Several of these
booklets have been translated into French, Chinese, and Nepali. Translations
into Arabic and Spanish are in preparation.<p>
<p>
	3. <i>Activity Sheets</i>. These materials reflect the basic concepts of the
Child-to-Child
approach. Twenty-
three
activity sheets are available providing activity-based
learning in five content areas: personal and community hygiene and safety,
prevention and control of disease, child stimulation and development,
recognizing and helping the handicapped, and better nutrition. These activity
sheets provide essential factual information combined with suggestions for
constructive learning
activities. Designed to target the primary school child, they have become how-to-do-it guides allowing project initiators to select and modify the materials to meet
the specific demands of their audience. Activity sheets have been adapted and
translated into the following languages: French, Spanish, Portuguese, Arabic,
Chinese, and Gujarati. Hindi translations are in progress.<p>
<p>
	4. <i>Pamphlets, Booklets and Other Materials</i>. Additional materials
designed to compliment the Activity Sheets have been developed and include:<p>
<p>
<ul>	 <li>"Child-to-Child
and the Refugee Programme."<p>
<p>
<li>	 "Child-to-Child
Health in Kenya." Activity Books for English schools, produced by Oxfam.<p>
<p>
	 <li>"Do You Know a Handicapped Child?"<p>
<p>
	 <li>"Child-to-Child Uganda." Written and illustrated by teachers and their
children.<p>
<p>
	 <li>"Toys for Fun: A book of toys for pre-school
children" (MacMillian Publishers, 1988). This book, edited by June Carlile,
contains ideas for toys which can be produced from locally available
materials.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Child-to-Child
<i>Newsletter</i>. Published periodically and circulated widely.</ul>

	5. <i>Child-to-Child
Material in Other Publications</i>. Child-to-Child
material is copyright free and is therefore widely incorporated into other
publications. It forms a major part of several important books with chapters
specifically devoted to Child-to-Child.
These include:<p>
<p>
<ul><li>	 Werner, David and Bower, B. "Helping Health Workers Learn," Hesperian
Foundation, 1982.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Werner, David. "Disabled Village Children," Hesperian Foundation, 1987.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Young, Beverly and Durston, S. "Primary Health Education," Longman, 1987.</ul>
	6. <i>Proposed Materials</i>. Additional child health materials are being
produced and include:<p>
<p>
<ul><li>	 Editing and revision of the Activity Sheets.<p>
<p>
	 <li>A series "Health Across the Curriculum" has been planned. This will integrate
health education materials and the Child-to-Child
approach into four main school subjects (Mathematics, Language, Social Studies,
and Moral and Religious Education). The first book, "Mathematics and Health
Education: A Child-to-Child
Approach" is being written using Kenyan schools as the model.<p>
<p>
	 <li>"Child-to-Child:
Another Path to learning." A description of the programme and its educational
impact is being prepared for publication by UNESCO in 1988.<p>
<p>
	 <li>A workshop has been held to develop additional readers. A number of new
titles are projected for 1988-89.</ul>
<p>
<p>
(1) The Child-to-Child materials described in this Appendix as well as a wide
selection of addditional child health books, slides and accessories are
available from:<br>
<p>
<center>Teaching Aids at Low Cost<br>
P.O. Box 49, St. Albans<br>
Herts, AL1 4AX, United Kingdom<br>
<p>
Telephone:  (0727) 53869<br>
Telex: 266020 Corald G Ref: TALC</center><br>
<p>
<b><center>APPENDIX II<br>
HEALTH EDUCATION AND<br>
THE ROLE OF PRIMARY SCHOOL CHILDREN:<br>
A STRATEGIC PLANNING FRAMEWORK</center></b><br>
<p>

	1. Prepare a<i> Situation Analysis</i> (at country, district, community/
school level).<p>
<p>
<ul><li> Useful step in developing an effective programme of health education.
Information based to serve as foundation for developing the programme.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Analysis should include:<p>
<p>
<ul><li>		  Major health problems and needs of the community and school-age
children.<p>
<p>
		 <li>Inventory and assessment of health facilities and services.<p>
<p>
		 <li>Inventory of other related development activities/projects.<p>
<p>
		 <li>Assessment of existing health programmes.<p>
<p>
		 <li>Assessment of the degree of intersectorial cooperation existing and
achievable.<p>
<p>
		 <li>Assessment of existing and potentially available resources, solutions,
priorities, 		and strategies to be adopted for implementation.</ul></ul>

	2. Discuss the Situation Analysis.<p>
<p>
<ul><li>	 Develop public awareness and enthusiasm.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Political support and will, and acceptance with commitment by key policy
makers and decision makers. (Use mass media and organisations concerned with
the welfare of children.)<p>
<p>
	 <li>Consider all ways by which children can learn about health and apply their
learning.</ul>
	3. Develop a plan of action.<p>
<p>
<ul><li>	 The plan should be innovative. (An important strategy is to involve
parents/teachers/children in cooperative action to improve the environment of
the school and undertake special projects.)</ul>

	4. Develop guidelines for implementation.<p>
<p>
<ul><li>	 Point out various measures that are a <u>MUST</u> if the plan is to succeed.
(For example, policy support, intersectorial collaboration, mechanisms for
coordination, and monitoring.)</ul>

	5. Experimentation.<p>
<p>
<ul><li>	 Pilot project to accumulate useful experiences and lessons for expansion.
(Note: Project, as far as possible, accommodated within existing institutions;
no new cadres should be created;  lessons/experience be continuously diffused
into the system.)</ul>
	6.   Develop a research/evaluation strategy to explore such areas as:<p>
<p>
<ul><li>	 How and where the children learn about health.<p>
<p>
	 <li>What sources of information they find accessible and credible.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Opportunities in existence to permit the application of knowledge, skill and
undertaking.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Behaviour research, e.g. motivation of teachers.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Impact on children of conflicting values and behaviour; relative
effectiveness of different methodologies and approach.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Communication research, e.g. advertising on health attitudes and behaviour of
children, the relative effectiveness of various media.</ul>

	7. Establish effective machinery to coordinate inputs (urgently needed, long-sought
but rarely found).<p>
<ul><li> A task force might be formally created with sufficient autonomy to influence
policy and practice.</ul>

<b><center>APPENDIX III</center><br><p>
Child: care, health and development, 1985. 11, 81-90.<p>
<p>
<center>USING PRIMARY-SCHOOL CHILDREN TO<br>
IMPROVE CHILD-REARING PRACTICES IN RURAL JAMAICA</b><br><p>
Jennifer Knight and Sally Grantham-McGregor<p>
Tropical metabolism Research Unit<br>
University of the West Indies<br>
St. Andrew, Jamaica</center><br>
<p>
Accepted for publication 14 November 1984<p>
<p>
<b><u>Summary</u></b><p>
<p>
	Many children in Jamaica suffer from poor development, inadequate dental care
and low immuniration status. There is a need for low-cost
innovative programmes to reach these children. We piloted an approach to
teaching primary-school
children basic child health and development concepts with the aim of improving
their knowledge and practices and those of their guardians. The programme was
conducted with 89 children from three grade levels in a remote rural school.
The topic was taught throughout the school year with an action-oriented
curriculum. Evaluation showed improvement in school children's knowledge and
practices and guardians' knowledge. This approach is seen to be a feasible, low
cost way of improving the quality of future child care.<p>
<p>
	The development of children living in deprived envirorrments is a cause for
great concern in many parts of both the developing and developed world. This is
the case in Jamaica where large numbers of children live in poverty and suffer
from poor health, growth and development.<p>
<p>
	In particular these children show a marked decline in developmental level from
12 months of age, and by 4 years of age they are seriously behind their middle-class
peers (Powell et. al., 1982; Wein, 1972a). This decline has been attributed to
the quality of their environments. The homes lack toys, books and other
educational material, and mothers make little conscious attempt to improve
young children's development through play (Grantham-McGregor
et al., 1983; Leo-Phynie
&amp; Gaynor, 1981). Discipline is generally authoritarian (Grant, 1974). Rural
children have usually been found to have worse physical and mental development
than urban children (Wein, 1972b).<p>
<p>
	Health care is inadequate and low levels of immunizatiun (CARES, 1980, 1982;
Puffer &amp; Serrano, 1983) and dental care (Ashworth &amp; Waterlow, 1970;
Stephenson, 1969) present major public health problems.<p>
<p>
	Social, and health services cannot reach a1l high-risk
children, thus there is a need for innovative low-cost
intervention strategies which focus on all aspects of the child's development.
Using primary-school
children is one such approach, whereby older children are taught how to care
more adequately for their younger siblings at home, and also to spread concepts
of child health and development to the rest of the family.<p>
<p>
<b><u>Rationale for Using School Children</u></b><p>
<p>
	In Jamaica, families are large and children spread over many years.
Frequently, older children are left to care for their younger siblings. This
practice is not unique to Jamaica, and other studies (Bianco &amp; Chodorow,
1964; Goldberg, 1972; Leiderman et al., 1977) have shown that it is a well-accepted
practice elsewhere, particularly in Third World countries.<p>
<p>
	The school, in spite of its many problems, is still a natural channel through
which the health and development of the community could be improved, with
school children as natural change agents.<p>
<p>
	In this paper we report the results of a project carried out in a remote rural
Jamaican school. The aims were to improve school children's and their
guardians' knowledge and practices related to immunization, dental care and
child development.<p>
<p>
	The study was carried out in a school (approximately 400 children) situated in
a rural mountainous area. The school had generally poor facilities, was
overcrowded and short of basic materials and teaching aids. The children's
level of literacy was generally low.<p>
<p>
<b><u>Methods</u></b><p>
<p>
	<i>Samples</i>. The sample comprised allchildren in grades 3, 5, and 7 of the
school and their guardians. At the beginning of the project all children on the
school register were chosen. Table 1 gives a description of their age and sex
by class.<p>
<p>
	The mothers or guardians of the school children were identified by visiting
the homes of each project child in the summer vacation preceding the project.
Over one-third
of the children (37%) were not living with their mothers, and both mothers and
guardians tended to be unmarried. This reflects the somewhat unstable family
patterns found in Jamaica. Housing standards were generally poor with
inadequate sanitation and overcrowding.<p>


<center>TABLE 1<br> 
Age and Sex Distribution of the Sample by Class</center><br><p>                                                                                 
<pre>
                  Age (Years)                                                               
   Class        Mean       3. d.        Boys      Girls       Total      
     3         10.09       0.9           24        11           35        
     5         11.02       1.32          23         9           32        
     7         11.96       1.99          15        12           27        
                                                                                          
   TOTAL       10.0        1.6           62        32           94        

</pre>
<p>
	<i>The Intervention</i>. Each week of the school year the children spent
approximately 1 hour learning about child health and development. Thus the
students participated in approximately 30 sessions over three terms.The
principal researcher assisted the class teacher during these periods.<p>
<p>
	The child development curriculum included the different areas of the
development of children, important developmental milestones and appropriate
child management techniques. The children were taught how to make toys from
waste household materials, and how to play with them so as<p>
to encourage a younger child's development.<p>
<p>
	The dental care lessons included the care of teeth and information on foods
which are good and bad for teeth. The immunization curriculum dealt with the
purpose of immunization, the diseases which immunization can prevent and the
times when the baby should be immunized.<p>
<p>
	The curriculum was action-oriented
and suitable for the children's low level of reading and writing. Activities
such as role play, group discussion and demonstrations were included. The
topics were reinforced with toy-making,
drama and poster competitions. An open day was also<p>
mounted at the end of the year.<p>
<p>
	<i>Evaluation</i>. At the beginning and end of the project a questionnaire was
administered to the guardians at home and a test was given to the children at
school. Information was obtained from the guardians on their social background,
knowledge of topics taught and certain of their child<p>
care activities. The guardians were also asked about the school child's
activities with the younger ones at home. In addition, at the end of the
project they were asked about the number of project toys brought home. The
school children were tested on their knowledge of topics taught.<p>
<p>
	<i>Analysis</i>. The data were analysed by computing frequencies of responses
on the items from both the school children's tests and the guardians'
questionnaires. Chi-square
analyses were then carried out to ascertain the significance of any differences
which may have occurred between the pre- and post-intervention
measures. In those instance where the differences between scores were large and
the number in the cells was too small for this test, statistical analysis was
not done. Five school children missed their initial test because they were
absent from school. By the end of the study, nine guardians and another 12
school children were lost. This was caused by guardians moving from the area
and poor school attendance of children on the day the test was given.<p>
<p>
<b><u>Results</u></b><p>
<p>
	Generally, the project was well received by the teachers, children and health
personnel involved. Fifteen toys were made throughout the year.<p>
<p>
	iSchool children's test</i>. The baseline information revealed that the school
children knew little of the topics to be taught. Responses concerning
immunization on the first test (Table 2) indicate that the school children's
knowledge of immunization was poor. Although about half had heard of
immunization, very few know its purpose or the number of injections or "drops"
which were required. There was a similarly low level of knowledge of basic
dental care.<p>
<p>
	The post-intervention
test results showed that there was a highly significant improvement in
knowledge of both immunization and dental care following the project.<p>

<center>TABLE 2<br>
 School Children's Knowledge of Health <br>                                        
      Messages Before and After the Project</center><br>
<p>                                             
<pre>                                              Percentage of Total Giving                      
                                                   Correct Response                    
                                                Before n=89      After n=77     
Immunization
   Heard of Immunization 			   53		    99b
   Immunizationprotects for diseases	            7		    87b
   Child needs more than three                                       
      immunizations in the first year 	            7		    76b                                                        
 
Diseases Protected Against
   Polio					    3		    56b 
   Lockjaw 					    0		    60a                
   Diphtheria					    0       	    44a
   Measles					    0		    49a                                                                      

Dental Care
   Things that are bad for teeth:
      Sweets					   63	            86b      
      Aerated water				    0		    14a
      Feeding bottle (i.e. prolonged sucking)       1		    69a
   Things that are good for teeth:
      Cleaning 				           26		    70b                                      
      Sugar Cane				    6		    70a
      Carrots					   15  	            62b
      Milk					    2		    58a 						   
a = not tested; b = P less than 0.001                                                   
</pre>
<p>
	Table 3 shows the school children knowledge of appropriate child management
techniques and play activities for young children. In the first test 66% of the
school children chose positive motivation as a good teaching tool for young
children although few favoured this approach when<p>
managing young children's behaviour. A very small portion of school children
recognized toys and play as having educational value. Similarly, few children
know the suitable concepts to teach young children with toys.<p>
<p>

<center> TABLE 3<br>
School Children&#146;s Knowledge of Health<br>                                                
   Messages Before and After the Project</center><br><p>                                                               
<pre>
                  Item                        Percentage of Total Giving                       
                                                   Correct Response                              
                                            Before n = 89    After* n = 77      
Correct idea of use of positive rather                                        
   than negative motivation:
      When teaching                               66               97
      When managing child's behavior              36               88                          

Recognizing educational value of:
      Toys                                        17               82         
      Play                                        12               62

Correct idea of suitable concepts to teach:                                              
      With blocks                                 18               73
      With 'pull-along'                           25               65     

*P less than 0.001                                                                     

</pre>
<p>
	The post-intervention
results indicated that a significant improvement in knowledge in all areas had
taken place.<p>
<p>
	The school children were asked to choose between a number of methods which
could improve the language development of very young children. Firstly, they
were asked how to look at a book with young children (Table 4).<p>
<p>
    Very few school children knew that talking about pictures and stories were
better techniques than insisting on the child sitting still and reading every
word carefully.<p>
<p>
    They were then asked about talking with young children and playing with
pencil and paper. Here again, they school child chose the more formal and
inappropriate approaches of teaching the alphabet and writing sentences rather
than naming things in the immediate environment and drawing picture.<p>
<p>
    By the end of the project significantly more children chose the correct
responses to each item.<p>

<center>   TABLE 4<br>
 School Children&#146;s Choice of                                                 
  Appropriate Language Activity<br> of Very                                                
   Young Children Before and After the                                                 
                 Project</center><br>                                                               
<pre>
      Choice of Activity                  Percentage of Total Giving                        
                                                Correct Response                              
                                         Before n = 89      After* n = 77      
When Reading to Young Child
   Talk about pictures                         44                92           
   Read every word carefully                                                     

   Talk about story                            49                81           
   Child to sit still and quiet                                                                                  

When talking with Young Child                  32                86           
   Name things in yard
   Teach alphabet                                                          

When playing with Pencil and Paper             15                88           
   Draw pictures 
   Write sentences                                                               

*P less than 0.001                                                                     

</pre>
<p>
<i>	Guardians</i>. The guardians were asked similar but fewer questions about
their knowledge of health care and child development. Many of them were aware
of what caused tooth decay (Table 5). Less than half were aware of the
educational value of toys and play and recognised the importance of chatting
with children to promote language development.<p>
<p>
	The guardians were also asked about their own activities with the children
(Table 5). After the project a significantly higher portion of guardians
reported that they encourage the older children to play with the younger ones.
There was no differences in the number of guardians reading, looking at
pictures and playing with the younger ones.<p>
<p>
<center>    TABLE 5<br> Guardians' Knowledge and                                                   
 Practices Concerning<br> Child Care Before                                                
            and After Project</center><br><p>                                                          
<pre>
Type of Knowledge and Activity              Percent of Total Giving                          
                                                Correct Response                              
                                         Before n =94       After* n = 85      
Guardians' Knowledge
   Mentions correct causes of tooth decay     66                  88         
   Recognizes educational value of:                                                      
      Play                                    40                  72
      Toys                                    15                  50                                      
   Recognizes importance of chatting          48                  84                                         

Guardians' Actions                                   
   Encouragesolder children to play
      with younger child                      12                  52                                
   Reads and looks at pictures                                                
      with younger child                      65                  63ns
   Plays with child and his toy               45                  65ns                                 

*P 0.001; ns = not significant                                                         

</pre>
<p>
	The guardians were also asked about the school child's previous activities in
the home (Table 6). They reported that the older child did not usually tell the
younger ones to clean their teeth. Very few reported that the children reminded
them about immunizing the baby. They also said that the school children
infrequently made toys for the younger ones. The post-intervention
results revealed a highly significant improvement in all these areas.<p>
<p>
<b>Discussion</b><p>
<p>
    Baseline data support the need for intervention in those areas of child
development and health care focussed on in this project.<p>
<p>
   The study was reasonably representative of remote rural schools in Jamaica
and had no special advantages. It is therefore probable that this approach
could be reproduced elsewhere.<p>
<p>
    This mode proved to be both feasible and successful; we managed to improve
the school children's knowledge of' the topics taught, and also change their
practices in certain areas. Some of the information reached the homes, and we
improved the guardians' knowledge; however, we could not detect any concomitant
improvement in their actions. A similar project in Indonesia was successful in
improving parents' knowledge of health matters, but practices were not
evaluated (Rhode and Sadjinum, 1980).<p>

  <center>TABLE 6<br> Guardians' Reports of School                                                 
   Children's<br> Activities with Younger                                                  
                Children</center><br>                                                               
<pre>
              Activity                   Percent of Total Giving                                                                                                                                       
                                             Correct Response
                                           Before        After* 
                                           n = 94        n = 85          

School child reminds younger child
   to clean teeth                            43            72                    
                                                                            
Reminds guardian to get young child                                                
   immunized                                 14            53                            

School child plays every day with                                                 
   younger child                             41            66                           

School child makes toys for younger
   child(out of school)                      32            50

*P 0.001                                                                               
                                                                               

</pre>

Our success was obviously limited by the quality of the school, and we were
seriously handicapped by poor attendance, overcrowding and a high noise level.
It is probable that in situations where the educational system has fewer
problems. This approach would be more successful. There is a great need to
improve child care in all areas, and the curriculum is being extended to
include hygiene, nutrition, and health care. In addition, we are presently
training teachers rather than working with the children ourselves and this will
enable us to reach larger numbers of children at relatively low cost.<p>
	In conclusion, the success of this project suggests that if the expanded
curriculum was incorporated into the government school curriculum for all
primary grade levels, there would be a real opportunity to improve the quality
of child care in the future.<p>
<p>
