<html>
<title>The Intersecting Needs of Women and Children</title>
<head></head><body>
<h1>The Intersecting Needs of Women and Children	</h1><p>
<b></b>	<b>Women&#146;s Work and Child Care</b><p>
<p>
	To meet the intersecting needs of  women and children, programming that is
created to benefit women and girls must also be responsive to and take into
account women's childrearing responsibilities.  And programs created for
children must be designed in relation to women's needs.   <p>
<b></b><p>
<b>Women do not exist in isolation.  </b><p>
<p>
	Their lives are interwoven with their family 's lives. Thus a woman's status,
the supports she has available to her, her level of education, and her ability
to earn income all affect children's growth and development.  And conversely,
the presence of a child (children) markedly affects a woman's personal growth
and development as well as her social participation and economic
productivity.<p>
<p>
	Too often in development projects, women become casualties rather than success
stories, because the project design does not support them as producers
<i>and</i> parents. Too often there is a false dichotomy set up between
"productive" and "reproductive" activities.  Women are whole people, who need
both their productive and reproductive inter-connections with others in order
to survive and thrive.  They work to get the food, clothing and shelter they
need, they create families, they parent the next generation, they learn, they
teach, they create expressions of their culture.  Within this larger pattern
parenting a child and creating goods for income both have value.   When a
program seeks to improve a woman's life, it needs to strengthen her within the
context of her whole life. <p>
<p>
<b>Children are a reality in women's lives</b>.  <p>
<p>
	For the great majority of the women in the world, childrearing is a
centerpiece of their lives.  For this reason women are often precluded from
income-generating activities because they cannot find ways to simultaneously
work outside the home and care for their children.  Child care responsibilities
begin at a young age.  Often young girls do not attend primary schools because
the costs to the family are too high; the need for the girl child to care for
younger siblings, cook, clean and gather water is often greater than the
perceived need for her to receive an education.  <p>
<p>
	However, this does not mean that caring for children and obligations to the
family must be considered liabilities.  In order for a development program to
successfully help a woman, it must find ways to help her address the
responsibilities and needs she brings with her, including her interdependency
with children.   Otherwise her participation or her children are doomed to
failure.<p>
<p>
<b>When children's needs are being met, women can expand their earning and
learning possibilities. </b><p>
<p>
	Women in both the formal and informal sectors who are preoccupied with
concerns about the safety and well-being of their children cannot focus on
their own development.  Traditionally in many settings women have had support
from other family members, neighbors, and members of the community -- both in
their caretaking roles with children and in meeting their children's material
needs.  Today, however, many systems of social support and child care that used
to be available to women have eroded in the face of such forces as migration,
urbanization, changes in family structure and extension of schooling. Thus
women are increasingly faced with the dual challenge of providing both monetary
and non-monetary supports for their families.  The demands on women's time are
often greatest when their need is greatest:<p>
<UL>
 <LI>in conditions of poverty<br>
 <LI>in single parent, women-headed households<br>
 <LI>during the first year of the child's life<br>
 <LI>when alternative child care options are lacking<br>
 <LI>if work is poorly paid, without benefits, far from home or physically
demanding<br>
 <LI>in heavy work seasons (e.g. harvest) or "wet" seasons<br>
 <LI>where culture strongly dictates an exclusively domestic role for women,
irrespective of their actual situations.<br></UL>

	When women have quality child care available to them, when they have good
information about how to make sure their children are receiving adequate
nutrition, stimulation, and nurturing, then they are able to turn their
attention to expanding their learning and earning activities.  At present, the
lack of adequate child care options inhibits the earning and learning
possibilities of women and inhibits the participation of girls in the formal
school system.  Yet we know there are benefits for both the women and children
when women earn and retain their own income. When women earn income that they
control, children benefit.  Women are more likely than men to devote the income
they earn to benefit the health and education of their children.  Thus if
mothers are earning money and they can determine how that money is spent,
children are the beneficiaries.<p>
<p>
When women are educated, children also benefit.  Each year of education a girl
receives correlates with her ability to provide better health and education for
her children.<p>
<p>
<b>Linking child care and development programs with programs for women is a
good investment.  </b><p>
<p>
	During the first six years of a child's life, foundation stones are laid
through good nutrition, appropriate interactions and stimulation, and nurturing
safe care.  Upon this foundation can be built a more successful future -- for
girls and women, and for the boys and men in their lives as well.  Studies in
both developed and developing countries have shown that an investment in young
children pays off in many types of social benefits.  Children who receive
quality care in their early years are more likely to become productive
participants in their communities.  Children who do not receive adequate care
-- who are left with slightly older siblings, who are left alone, who do not
get appropriate interaction and nurturing -- fail to thrive.  They perpetuate
the cycles of poverty  which <i>Women in Development</i> programs are seeking
to eradicate.  <p>
<p>
	Child care needs to be seen as a legitimate form of employment and income
generation for women.  Failure to recognize and classify child care as a valid
and worthwhile form of work means that the individuals providing organized
child care -- mostly women-- have low status in society, are poorly paid and
lack social benefits.	<p>
	<p>
<b>Educating girls is the first step in educating women.</b><p>
<p>
	Organized child care offers multiple benefits.  Not only can it help children
develop the appropriate basis for later learning and development, but it can
also serve women to help them meet their responsibilities. The provision of
child care in a community also frees girls, the informal caretakers in many
societies, to attend school.  <p>
<p>
<b>Quality child care needs to be promoted and created wherever efforts are
being made to improve the situation of women.</b>  <p>
	The word <i>quality</i> means that children need more than custodial care.
Child care needs to be set up in a way that promotes children's health,
nutrition, psycho-social and mental development. <p>
<p>
	Many alternative forms of child care can be available within a community.
These can include strengthening of traditional care in families, establishing
programmes of home day care for groups of children, setting up self-standing
programmes of center-based care, and linking programmes of alternative care to
programmes of community development, credit, community<p>
gardens, co-ops or markets, care in the workplace, etc.<p>
<p>
	Alternative care should be affordable, accessible, flexible, run by trusted
and accountable persons and meet minimum quality standards.<p>
<p>
<b>Good parenting can help break the cycles of poverty and ignorance.</b><p>
<p>
	Parenting programs can stimulate parents to re-think childrearing practices
and beliefs which lead to gender inequalities.  By making parents aware of
their child's individual development, and helping them learn to be responsive
to their child's needs, it is possible over time to make a substantial
difference in how both men and women view girls and women.  More important,
through supporting parents it becomes possible to create an environment where
children can become engaged problem-solvers and active participants in their
surroundings, breaking the cycles of poverty and ignorance. <p>
<p>
<b>Some Policy Implications</b><p>
<UL>
<LI> There is a need to improve and enforce legislation that defines women's access
to child care and regulates policies of maternal and paternal leave.  Without
supportive legislation, young children often fall through the cracks of funding
and social development projects.<p>
<LI> Governments need to invest financially in adequate child care, particularly
for children whose parents are involved in the informal sector and for
woman-headed households in marginal circumstances.<p>
<LI> It needs to become accepted practice that programmes organized to improve the
productivity, participation and welfare of women also take the needs of their
young children into account.  Similarly, programmes directed toward the
development of young children need to routinely address their family's
circumstances.<p>
<LI> Programmes of adequate child care can be built using local experience and
capacity, responding to local needs with community -based approaches. This
generally requires a subsidy from outside the community.  In such programs the
goals of quality and local ownership of the program must be consistently
reinforced.<p>
<LI> Child care is both a social investment and an area of income-generation.  It
is important that those who work in child care jobs be provided with proper pay
and benefits, and be recognized for their contributions to their community.<p>
<LI> Child care is a whole-community responsibility.  Although women are
traditional care-takers, men and elders need to be invested in young children
too.  Ways should be explored to integrate men and elders into the provision of
care for young children, and to promote greater participation of women and men
at all levels of decision-making that affect young children.<p>
<LI> Domestic labour, including child care, supports the fabric of a society.  If
women are to be integrated more fully into economic equations, then their work
to care for the next generation of citizens needs to enter into national
accounting systems.<p>
</UL>
<p>
<b>CASE STUDIES</b><p>
		<p>
	
<b>Related Documents</b>:<br>

