<HTML><TITLE>ECCD and Community Development Efforts</TITLE>
<HEAD></HEAD><BODY>
<H3>ECCD and Community Development Efforts</H3>

	Many community development efforts begin with a focused goal, such as
providing immunization or improving water quality.  However, when those who
wish to help a community listen to the community&#146;s understanding of what
they need, a more complex picture emerges.  <BR>
<p>
	<b>A community&#146;s needs are inter-related</b>.  <BR>
<p>
	Health, education, sanitation, nutrition, agriculture, economy and other
aspects of the community life can all be strengthened through engaging the
active participation of community members, supporting existing strengths, and
working from the motivation and interests of the people who are the intended
recipients of the community development effort.  Many efforts to strengthen a
community ultimately can improve the quality of life for the children living
there.  In addition, efforts to improve the care and attention to young
children can help to activate community participation and to focus community
members in defining their development needs.<p>
 <p>
	<b>An early childhood care and development programme (or component within a
larger effort) can</b>:
<UL>
 <LI>help women to participate in local development efforts, <BR>
 <LI>provide training opportunities for women (and men), <BR>
 <LI>serve as a rallying point for other development efforts, such as women&#146;s
saving schemes, community building efforts, health education projects, <BR>
 <LI>facilitate participation of girls in primary school.  <BR>
</UL>
<b>	ECCD offers a forum in which parents, teachers and children can:</b><UL>

<LI>build self-esteem,<BR>
<LI>develop practical skills in organizing, collaborating, teaching, planning,
etc.  <BR>
<LI>re-establish cultural practices that have been disrupted by difficult
circumstances, <BR>
<LI>and identify what they value and wish to pass on to the next generation.<BR>
</UL>
	As we have mentioned elsewhere in this Web Site, numerous studies have shown
that mono-dimensional programs (e.g. those that provide only a nutrition
supplement or focus only on immunization, or even provide only pre-natal care
for the mother without adequate follow-up once the child is born), are much
less likely to be successful than multi-dimensional programs. Mono-dimensional
programs, which may meet short term goals, are not likely to be sustainable
over time.  It is rarely helpful to impose a single solution that ignores the
need for individuals and communities to control their own destinies. <p>
<p>
	Multi-dimensional programs, on the other hand, are built on an awareness of
the importance of meeting the multiple needs of children and their families.
They are generally created from a culturally-sensitive understanding of
people's beliefs, perceptions, needs and concerns, and the services they
provide meet the intersecting needs of children and families.  An example would
be a program that provides children with a nutritional supplement in a child
care setting, which also provides children with stimulation and emotional
support.  Another component of such a program would be to work with parents to
improve family nutrition.  Thus the need to address the whole young child,
within the child&#146;s family and community context, becomes a model for a
range of community development efforts. <p>
<p>
	<b>Attention to children can serve as an entry point to larger community
development efforts</b>.<p>
<p>
	In many parts of the world, children are highly valued.  Because of this,
programs that focus on ECCD can be used to rally community members, to engage
them in creating solutions to the problems they are facing, and to open up
dialogue that can lead them to address a whole range of community development
efforts.  <p>
	For example:	<i>Child care programs can serve as an entry point to communities
not currently receiving health services. </i> <p>
<p>
	In some areas of the world Western medical practices and services are not
easily accepted.  Services may be underutilized because people lack an
understanding of the benefits.  Because they are socially attractive and
acceptable, child care programs can serve as an entry point into the community.
The <i>Sang Kancil</i> project in Malaysia is a good example of this
approach.<p>
<p>
<b>Malaysian <i>Sang Kancil</i>, Community-based Services Project.</b>  The
<i>Sang Kancil</i> Project was developed within the squatter settlements of
Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia.  It was begun in 1978 by the health sector in an
attempt to meet the health needs of those living in urban squatter settlements.
The rationale for working in squatter communities was based on the fact that
they are a growing phenomenon in the developing world, constituting nearly 50%
of the total urban population.  It is widely recognized that the environment
within squatter settlements is threatening to people's health--physically,
mentally and in terms of psycho-social development. <p>
<p>
	In Malaysia there was difficulty in providing services for squatters because
they occupy the land illegally and thus are not entitled to city services
(water, sewage, medical care, education, etc.).  Nevertheless many squatter
settlements are stable communities, including people from a variety of income
levels.  The stability comes from affordable housing within the settlement that
may not be available outside, well-developed support systems, and/or leadership
positions within the settlement.  <p>
	<p>
	Developers of the <i>Sang Kancil</i> project, University faculty in
collaboration with Ministry of Health personnel, used a strategy that
recognized, valued, and built upon the complex social systems that exist in the
settlements. While the health sector personnel who began the project were
interested in establishing primary health care centers within <i>kampungs</i>
(districts) in the settlements, they began their efforts by conducting meetings
with community members to determine their needs and priorities.  The community
wanted a child care programme and income-generating activities for women.
Health care was not seen as a priority.  Program planners listened to the
community.  Rather than building a health center, they established a pre-school
and an income-generating project.  When these were well established, then it
was possible to introduce primary health care, which is now widely accepted.


