<H1>The Consultative Group on ECCD</H1>

<H3>The Consultative Group on Early Childhood Care and Development</H3>

	The Consultative Group is an international, inter-agency group dedicated to
improving the condition of young children at risk.  Working on several levels
to <i>keep young children on the agenda</i> of policy-makers, funders and
programme developers, the Consultative Group consists of a broad membership of
international organizations, a Secretariat and a group of Field Representatives
active in ECCD networks in diverse regions of the world.<p>
<p>
	Growing awareness of the importance of and demand for early childhood
programming has created a need for knowledge and processes that can inform
planning and program choices in what is a rapidly advancing field.  It has
created a need for basic scientific information about child development, about
the conditions affecting that development, and about strategies and programmes
that can be employed in different circumstances to assist children at risk of
delayed, debilitated or distorted development.<p>
<p>
	Increasing involvement in the field has made it even more important for whose
who plan, implement and fund such programmes to communicate with one another,
to share lessons learned, and to avoid costly duplication.<p>
<p>
	To help meet those needs, and, more generally, to enhance the well-being of
young children, The Consultative Group on Early Childhood Care and Development
was established in 1984.   Since then the Consultative Group has functioned as
an inter-agency mechanism for gathering, synthesizing, and disseminating
knowledge about early childhood development and about programmes affecting the
development of young children. <p>
<p>
<b>The Participants of the Consultative Group</b><p>
<b></b><p>
Nineteen organizations <b>[1]</b> have participated in
the Consultative Group (CG). Under the auspices of the Group, an active
Knowledge Network has been established that presently incorporates
approximately 1,800 individuals or institutions in 120 countries, crossing
disciplinary and sectoral lines. <p>
<p>
<p>
<b>Organisations that are presently active in the Consultative Group
include</b>:<p>
<b></b><p>
<b>UNICEF</b><UL>
<A HREF=po.html>TOWARDS A COMPREHENSIVE STRATEGY
FOR THE DEVELOPMENT OF THE YOUNG CHILD</A>
An Inter-Agency Policy Review</UL>
<b>UNESCO</b><BR><p>
<b>USAID</b><BR><p>
<b>World Bank</b><UL>
<b><a href=mary.html>Investing in the Future</b></a>-The World Bank's Vice Presidency for Human Capital Development<br>
<b><A HREF="wbbroch.html">WB Activities in Early Childhood Development </b></A><BR>
<b><A HREF= "http://www.worldbank.org">WB Home Page  </b></A><BR>
</UL>
<b>Christian Children&#146;s Fund</b><BR><p>
<b>The Aga Khan Foundation</b> (Geneva, Switzerland)<BR><p>

<b>Aga Khan Foundation, US</b><BR><p>

<b>Bernard van Leer Foundation</b><BR><p>

<b>Inter-American Development Bank</b><BR><p>

<b>High/Scope Educational Research Foundation</b><BR><p>

<b>Save the Children</b><BR><p>

<b>Pan American Health Organization (PAHO)</b><BR><p>

<b>Inter-American Development Bank (WID division)</b><BR><p>

<b>IDRC</b><BR><p>

<p>
<b>Affiliates include</b>:<BR>
<A HREF="eccap.html">Education Development Center (EDC)</A><BR>
Childwatch International<BR>
Save the Children UK<BR>
Peter Hesse-Stiftung<BR>
Congressional Human Rights Foundation<BR>
Plan International<BR>
Save the Children, Nicaragua<BR>
<p>
<b>Field representatives come from</b>:<BR>
India<BR>
Jamaica<BR>
Colombia<BR>
Turkey<BR>
Namibia<BR>
the Philippines<BR>
<p>
<b>The Consultative Group Secretariat</b><p>
<p>
Judith L. Evans. Ed.D. (chief contact person) - 6 The Lope, Haydenville, MA
01039 US tel:(413) 268-7272 fax:(413)268-7279.  E-mail: 
<A HREF="mailto:jlevans@ecdgroup.com">Jlevans@ecdgroup.com</A><BR>
<p>
Robert G. Myers, Ph.D. - Insurgentes Sur 4411, Ed 25-304, Tlalcoligia, D.F.
14430, Mexico. Tel/Fax: (52-5) 573-0924.  E-mail: 
<A HREF="mailto:Rmyers@laneta.apc.org"> Rmyers@laneta.apc.org </A><BR>
<p>
Ellen M. Ilfeld, D.A. -   (Web site manager) 6 The Lope, Haydenville, MA 01039,
US.  Tel:(413)268-7272; Fax: (413)268-7279.  E-mail: 
<A HREF="mailto:eilfeld@ecdgroup.com">Eilfeld@ecdgroup.com</A><BR>
<p>
<p>
	In addition to publishing the <b>Coordinators' Notebook</b>  twice a year, and
the <b>Funders Folio </b>(recently renamed the <b>Network Notes</b>)<b>
</b>quarterly, the Group, through its Secretariat, has been responsible for
producing concept papers, reviews, case studies, digests, evaluations,
summaries of meetings, manuals, booklets and periodic mailings of current
materials to Network participants.  The Group has also been responsible for a
major book dealing with various aspects of programming for early childhood care
and development (<b>The Twelve Who Survive, </b>by Robert G. Myers).  The
Secretariat of the Group has organized at least two international meetings each
year.  It has been called on increasingly to identify people who can provide
particular kinds of programme advice and for direct programming assistance.<p>
<p>
<b>CONSULTATIVE GROUP GOALS AND FUNCTIONS</b><p>
<b></b><p>
Since its inception, the Consultative Group has taken as goals:<p>
<p>
 <LI>To increase the knowledge base: The Secretariat gathers, synthesizes and
disseminates information on early childhood care and development, drawing from
field experiences, traditional wisdom and scientific research;<p>
<p>
<LI> To serve as a catalyst: The Secretariat increases awareness of issues
affecting children, developing materials and strategies which help move
communities, organizations and governments from rhetoric to practice, from
policy to programming;<p>
<p>
 <LI>To build bridges: The Secretariat fosters networking among those with common
concerns and interests, working across sectoral divisions, putting people in
touch with the work of others by organizing meetings, by disseminating
information through publications, and by serving as a communications point; <p>
<p>
<LI> To serve as a sounding board: The Secretariat engages in dialogue with funders
and decision-makers about developments in the field, providing the base for
policy formulation, planning, programming and implementation.<p>
<p>
<p>
	There are two functions that frame the work of the Consultative Group and its
Secretariat:<b>  improving and extending the knowledge base</b> by gathering
and disseminating information; and<b> moving knowledge to action</b> for the
purposes of expanding options for children and families.  This is accomplished
through building partnerships and alliances, networking, convening meetings and
doing advocacy work.<p>
	The first function, knowledge-gathering and dissemination encompasses such
activities as:<BR>
<UL>
<LI> mapping and monitoring developments in the field, <BR>
<LI>publishing a periodic bulletin, <BR>
<LI>writing reviews and concept papers, <BR>
<LI>preparing case studies, <BR>
<LI>preparing articles and general publications, <BR>
<LI>distributing documents, <BR>
<LI>maintaining the ECCD Web site<BR>
<LI>identifying generic issues and writing guidelines, and<BR>
<LI>working with organizations and government to develop policy. <BR>
</UL>
	<p>
	Recognizing the importance of direct and personal communication if knowledge
is to move to action, the Secretariat of the Consultative Group has included as
an essential part of its operation a networking and convening function.
Networking and convening has taken several forms:<BR>
<UL>
 <LI>Networking is carried out as participants in the Group or as staff of the
Secretariat communicate via letter, telephone, fax and e-mail and travel.<p>

 <LI>Annual meetings of the CG are organized so that participants can exchange
programming information.  In most meetings a substantive topic is also
discussed. This meeting also serves as a way of involving participating
organizations directly in the information gathering and disseminating
process.<p>

<LI> The publication of the <b>Coordinators' Notebook</b> is linked to a networking
process in which the approximately 1800 recipients of the notebook are asked
to: 1) contribute to it, 2) copy and distribute it to others in their personal
knowledge networks, and 3) communicate directly with others whose addresses
appear in the notebook in conjunction with reporting of programmes or
publications or meetings.  In addition, <p>

 <LI>The <b>Funders' Folio/Network Notes</b>, a quarterly publication, provides
participants in the Consultative Group with up-to-date developments within the
early childhood field and updates on conferences, workshops and developments
within agencies and organizations.<p>

 <LI>The electronic network is becoming an increasingly important communication
tool.  Through connecting participants through the electronic network the CG
facilitates better and more frequent communications among donors and other
individuals working to promote Early Childhood Care and Development
internationally.<p>

<LI> Incipient regional networks are being bolstered, particularly in Africa and
Latin America,  with a network emerging in Asia. <p>

 <LI>Individuals or organizations have been convened under the auspices of the
Consultative Group to discuss a topic of general interest, such as <i>A Child
Readiness Profile</i>, <i>Principles and Guidelines to Strengthen Programmes of
Early Childhood Development and Learning</i>,  <i>Meeting Basic Learning Needs
through Programmes of Early Childhood Care and Development</i>, the
<i>Situation of Children in Eastern Europe</i>, and the <i>Intersecting Needs
of Women and Children.</i><p>
</UL>
<p>
	 Staff of the Secretariat and the participants in the Group use accumulated
knowledge directly by, for instance, participating in fora where investments in
early childhood care and development are (or should be) advocated.  The need to
<i>keep children on the agenda</i> through continuing advocacy efforts is
judged by participants of the Consultative Group to be of high importance and
basic to the functioning of the Group and its Secretariat.<p>
<p>

<HR>
<b>[1]</b> 
The nineteen organizations, in
alphabetical order are: The Aga Khan Foundation, The American Health
Foundation, The Bernard van Leer Foundation, The Carnegie Corporation,
Christian Children's Fund, The Ford Foundation, High/Scope Educational Research
Foundation, The Inter-American Foundation, The International Child Development
Centre, The International Development Research Centre, The Organization of
American States, The Rockefeller Foundation, Save-the-Children/USA, The Swedish
International Development Agency, UNICEF, UNESCO, USAID, the World Bank, and
the World Health Organization.  <hr>

