<title>Present Activities of the Consultative Group</title>
<HEAD></HEAD>

<A HREF=outline.html>Outline of this site</A> | <A HREF=abeccd.html> Young children and development</A> |
<A HREF=abcg.html>About our group</A> |
<A HREF=inter.html>Global efforts</A> |
<A HREF=program.html>Program design</A>  |
<A HREF=research.html>Research</A> |
<A HREF=policy.html>Policy</A> |
<A HREF=litavr.html>Resources</A> |
<A HREF=key.html>Hot topics</A> |
<A HREF=seek.html>Search this site</A> |
<A HREF=whats.html>Announcements</A> |
<A HREF=related.html>Related Internet Sites</A> |
<BR>


<H1> Present Projects of the Consultative Group</H1><p>

<b>Present Projects</b><p>
<p>
<b>1.  Basic activities</b> <p>
<b></b><p>
<b>Producing the <i>Coordinators' Notebook</i></b><p>
<p>
Two issues of the <b><i>Coordinators' Notebook</i></b> are produced each year.
The <b><i>Notebook</i></b> helps to map and monitor the field.  At present,
each issue contains: a focus article dealing with a major issue, accompanied by
references and descriptions of relevant experiences;  profiles of programs
being implemented with support from CG participants, news from CG network
participants; and information about recent publications, meetings and
workshops.<p>
<p>
<b>Producing the <i>Funders' Folio/Network Notes</i></b><p>
<p>
	The <b><i>Funders' Folio</i></b> was created in 1993 as a way to have more
immediate contact between the Secretariat and participants in the CG.  This
brief bulletin, renamed the Network Notes and produced quarterly, provides
participants with up-to-date news on what is happening within donor agencies,
international fora, and governments in relation to programming for young
children and their families.  It includes information on upcoming meetings,
describes new initiatives and provides participants with an update on
activities of members of the Secretariat.  <p>
<b></b><p>
<b>Moderating the ECCD Web site and facilitating the Electronic Network</b><p>
<p>
	At the 1994 meeting of the Consultative Group, the participants agreed to the
establishment of an electronic communications network focussing on
International Early Childhood Care and Development. This effort is being
organized by the CG Secretariat.  It is linked to the <a href="http://childhouse.uio.no/index.html">Children&#146;s
House</a>, a cyberspace project to link all international development efforts
on behalf of children. [http://childhouse@uio.no]<p>
<p>
<b>Convening the Consultative Group</b><p>
<p>
	One meeting of the Consultative Group is organized each year.  The meeting is
devoted to discussion of a particular topic to be agreed upon in advance and
for which background documentation is prepared.  <p>
<b></b><p>
<b>2.  Project Coordination and Technical Assistance</b><p>
<p>
<b>A Child Status Profile.</b> <p>
<p>
	Initial funding for this project was obtained from IDRC, UNICEF and USAID to
move ahead with the action research project focussing on establishing a profile
of the developmental status of children in three countries.  The project is set
within a framework of <i>Preparing Children for School and Preparing Schools
for Children</i>.  It includes, therefore, a proposal to develop and try out a
set of indicators to monitor the learning environment of children as well as
their developmental status.<p>
<b></b><p>
<b>The Status of Children in Eastern Europe.</b> <p>
<p>
	Funding was received from USAID and the World Bank to undertake an analysis of
the situation of care for young children in four Eastern European countries:
Hungary, Bulgaria, Romania, and Poland.  This study was completed in October,
1995<p>
<p>
<b>ECCD Policy Study.</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b> 	During the past five years a number of countries have developed
specific ECCD policies, and there are others that are beginning the process.
This study addresses the issue of policy and its relation to program planning
and implementation, with the goal of developing some guidelines for those who
anticipate being involved in a policy development process. The CG Secretariat
is coordinating this effort, with support from USAID and UNICEF. The first step
in the process is to pull together existing policies that are related to ECCD
concerns. . We would also appreciate hearing about any sources that you know of
that we should pursue.<p>
<p>
<b>Study on the Young Girl Child</b><p>
<p>
	In recent years there has been considerable international interest in the
plight of the girl child--particularly in terms of girls' participation in the
formal education system.  However, what has received less attention is the
plight of the girl child prior to her entry into the formal system.  What does
the girl child bring with her as a foundation for learning and development?
What is  her overall health, her current nutritional status and her nutritional
history?  What type of psycho-social stimulation has she received and what type
of socialization has she undergone? <p>
In order to better understand girls' ability to participate fully in the formal
educational system, it is critical to have an understanding of what the girl
child brings with her, and it is important to know how and to what extent she
has been raised differently from her male siblings.  These issues are being
explored in a project which will look at the situation of young children in 6-7
countries, with a focus on understanding the ways in which current beliefs,
values and practices affect gender development, and to identify plausible
points of intervention.<p>
<p>
	Participants in the study include USAID (Emily Vargas-Baron and Frank Method)
the Aga Khan Foundation (Kathy Bartlett), EDC (Andrea Bosch) and the IDB (Sarah
Howden).  We also hope to involve Save The Children.  A meeting was held on
October 3rd to discuss the project and finalize a strategy. It was decided that
the countries to be included in the study will be Indonesia, Bolivia/Peru,
Morocco, India, South Africa, Mali and Jamaica.<p>
<p>
	We are seeking linkages with ECCD and/or girls education and /or research
projects in these countries with whom we can work.  If you know of some, please
get in touch with Judith Evans at the CG Secretariat. <p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>3.  Developmental Activities</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>Developing the Group and New Ideas</b><p>
<p>
	This category of activities includes both the development of the Consultative
Group and the development of ideas for activities to be carried out under the
auspices of the Group.<p>
<p>
<center><b>THEMES TO BE ADDRESSED: 1995-1998</b></center><p>
<p>
<b>	EFA: A Continuing Concern.</b>  General responsibility for keeping
organizations informed of progress, for seeking extended cooperation, for
monitoring and for synthesizing results from the various activities within the
<b>Plan of Action </b>was assigned to the Secretariat of the Consultative
Group. Thus this will remain a key activity in the coming years. [link to Plan
of Action, Web 11, global initiatives, EFA]<p>
	<b></b><p>
<b>	Financing/funding of ECCD programs</b>.  This theme was addressed in the
<b>Twelve Who Survive, </b>but there has been increasing interest in the topic
since the publication of the book.  A study on financing was funded by the
World Bank in 1994, but considerably more work needs to be focussed on this key
issue.<p>
<p>
	<b>Linkage between Women and Children.</b>  The UN Women's Conference to be
held in Beijing in September 1995 has brought this issue to the fore once
again. In preparation for the Conference the Secretariat  produced a document
on <b>the Intersecting Needs of Women and Children</b>.  Our field
representative from the Philippines was able to attend, and her experiences
will be filed with the document just mentioned.  (Click on the Intersecting
Needs of Women and Children). <i> </i>[link to Web4, related topics, the
intersecting needs of Women and Children]<p>
<p>
	<b>Girls and Women's Education.</b>  This theme is a priority within many of
the organizations participating in the CG.  ECCD links into both the education
of girls and of women.  The rationale for addressing the theme through ECCD
will be further expanded and articulated, and programs illustrating the
linkages will be identified and highlighted.<p>
	<p>
	<b>Children Living in Difficult Circumstances</b>.  In 1991 an issue of the
<b>Coordinators' Notebook</b> was devoted to <i>Protecting Children from the
Scourge of War</i>.  Since that time the situation for a vast number of
children has worsened.  The number of children living in refugee camps, being
traumatized by war and being resettled after having been displaced as a result
of war, have increased dramatically.  It is time once again to address this
issue, particularly in terms of providing information on the type of
programming that has been successful, both in terms of meeting children's needs
and in terms of providing a focal point for re-organization of a community of
people.  (This topic will be the focus of Issue # 19 of the CN.)<p>
	<b>Early Childhood as an Entry Point for Democratization.</b>  The Eastern
European study made it evident that both women and children have been
negatively affected by the shift from communism to a market economy.  And, in
general, this shift has negatively affected the society as a whole.   Educating
people for democracy begins with the education of young children in terms of
decision-making, problem-solving, and living with differences.  Through the
training programs created in support of ECCD programs it is also possible to
work on these same dimensions with adults.  Ways of developing appropriate
programming will be explored and disseminated.<p>
<p>
	<b>The Development of National Early Childhood Policy.</b> In the future, the
policy line will have two aspects to it: analysis of policy and direct
involvement in policy formulation. Experiences of the Secretariat over the past
two years in working with governments to institute national policies in support
of young children has demonstrated the importance of this line of action.  This
activity will be developed further.  To begin with, Issue #17 of the CN will
focus on <i>ECCD Policy.</i>  In the Issue we will outline a process for
developing a national ECCD policy.  As we gain more experience along this line
we will develop a manual that can be used by governments and /or donors working
with governments to strengthen national ECCD policy.<p>
<p>
	<b>Capacity Building at the Regional level.</b>  Attention will be given to
supporting regional networks in order to improve the communication and use of
knowledge.  In part that will occur through support for regional <i>Focus
Groups.</i> Funds are budgeted for a staff person from the Secretariat to
travel to Asia, Africa, and Latin America at least once each year to
participate in regional <i>Focus Group</i> meetings.  Furthermore, a modest
amount of money is included in the budget to be made available to an
institution in each region to support a Secretary whose part-time task would be
to work on strengthening an early childhood development network in the
region.<p>
<p>
<HR>
<TABLE><TD> <A HREF="cgroup.html"><IMG SRC=logo.gif ALT = "[logo]">
</A></TD><TD><BR>Presented by: <BR>The Consultative Group on<BR>
 Early Childhood Care and Development.<BR></TD><TR></TABLE> E-mail: 
<A HREF="mailto:info@ecdgroup.com">info@ecdgroup.com</A>




