<title>Bulletin Board</title>
<body>
<h1><center>Bulletin Board</h1></center><hr>
<center><h3><a href=mary.html>Investing in the Future</a></h3>-The World Bank's Vice Presidency for Human Capital Development</center> <hr>
<b> ANNOUNCING: GLOBAL PARTICIPATION NET (GP-
NET)!
</b>
</center><p>
<p>
You are cordially invited to subscribe to USAID'S new electronic discussion
group, GP-
NET,
which will open September 11.  GP-
NET
uses Internet to enable interested USAID staff and other
development practitioners anywhere in the world to engage in a conversation
about participatory approaches.<p>
<p>
The conversation will have a facilitator (or "manager" of the list), Wendy
Kapustin, who will make subscribing and participating "user friendly."  More
important, Wendy will encourage the group to focus attention on specific
experiences and lessons learned about participatory approaches, as well as to
share useful information and resources for participation.  <p>
<p>
Short case studies that focus on the use by USAID of a particular
"participatory practice" and explore results and lessons learned about its use
will be disseminated for discussion.  GP-
NET
participants will be encouraged not only to comment on these cases and the
issues they raise, but to describe other instructive experiences.  With your
help, some of these, in turn, will be fleshed out as Participatory Practices
cases. <p>
<p>
Please note: GP-
NET
is not replacing the Participation Network, a list on our internal
e-
mail
directory of USAID staff who wish to receive summaries of the Participation
Forum sessions and related notices and materials.  GP-
NET,
on the other hand, makes use of "listproc"
software on the Internet, to enable the messages that you send automatically to
be received by all other GP-
NET
subscribers. Another important difference is that GP-
NET
includes development
practitioners from outside USAID: other donors, PVOs, universities and-
-
with
your help-
-
host
country NGOs and other institutions.  Like the Participation Network and the
Participation Forum, GP-
NET
is an effort of USAID's Participation Initiative.  <p>
<p>
If you would like to subscribe to GP-
NET,
or if you have questions about it, please contact Wendy Kapustin via e-
mail <A HREF="mailto:WKAPUSTIN@USAID.GOV"> WKAPUSTIN@USAID.GOV </A>.
To subscribe you, she will need to know your
Internet address. <p>
<p>
	<h3>
 From the CG Secretariat:</h3>
<b>
POLICY......POLICY......POLICY......POLICY......POLICY......POLICY.....POLICY</b>
<p>
Early Childhood Care and Development is on national agendas!<p>
<p>
<i>Policymakers are responding</i> to calls to address the needs of young
children and their families by creating policies that support healthy growth
and development<p>
	<p>
<i>You are an important resource to policy-makers</i>.  The more you know about
the policies in the country where you are working, the more effective you will
be in meeting the needs of young children and their families.<p>
<p>
	The Consultative Group on Early Childhood Care and Development invites you to
collaborate in a project that will provide information on the kinds of policies
that currently exist, what is being developed, and the policy-making process.
From this project we will write a manual that will be distributed to help
others work with their governments to develop appropriate policy. <p>
<p>
We are asking that you:<br>
	Review current government documents in the country where you work to identify
policies that provide support to young children and their families.  (One
source may be the National Plans of Action in relation to the Convention on the
Rights of the Child. Another is policies that may have been developed in
response to the Education for All (EFA) Initiative.)<br>
	Some of the questions that we would like you to answer include:<br>
<ul>	
	--What is the specific wording of the policy?<br>
		--What Ministries are involved in ECCD activities?<br>
</ul>
(Those we have come across so far include: education, health, social services,
women and youth, local government, community development, national development.
There may be others!)<br>
	Try to find out what the process has been in the creation of policy.<br>
<ul>
		-- Who was involved?<br>
		-- How did the process evolve?<br>
		-- Was there an attempt at cross-ministerial collaboration?<br>
</ul>	
<br>
By gathering this information you will have a better understanding of what
currently exists within government policy to support the work that you are
doing.  You will also be able to identify gaps in policy that you may be able
to address through your programming.<br>
<br>
We are hoping to gather information on national policies as soon as possible,
by early 1996 at the latest.  Please let us know if you can contribute.   Many
Thanks!<br>
<p>
Send any information that you gather to: Judith L. Evans, Consultative Group on
ECCD,<p>
	6 The Lope, Haydenville, MA 01039 USA<p>
            <b>Tel:</b> 413-268-7272;<b> Fax</b>: 413-268-7279 <b> 
e-mail</b> -
<A HREF="mailto:info@ecdgroup.com">info@ecdgroup.com</A>




