<TITLE>General Resources for Information on the Regions, or on particular
countries</TITLE>
<h1>General Resources for Information on the Regions, or on particular
countries</h1>
<b>	</b>We will continue to search the World Wide Web and Internet for
resources and information relating to Early Childhood Care and Development, and
link those resources into the appropriate sections of this Web Site.  However,
you may wish to search for particular information (or general information)
through one of the following resources:<p>
<p>
<b><A HREF="http://childhouse.uio.no/index.html">
The Children&#146;s House</b></A><br>

	The Children&#146;s House is a good place to start for all international
child-related searches.  	Our ECCD site represents the &#147;early childhood
floor&#148; of the Children&#146;s House, which is a collaborative effort
spearheaded by Childwatch in Norway to link all international on-line efforts
that focus on children and international development/research/advocacy.  The
formal launching for the Children&#146;s House is in February, 1996, but it
already contains many useful resources, such as extensive information on the
Convention on the Rights of the Child, and on NGOs working to serve families.
It also contains links to many other resources.  We recommend you take some
time to become familiar with the House.  It is growing in leaps and bounds, and
will eventually contain or link to most of the significant data-bases of
information concerning children.<p>
<p>
	<b>
<A HREF="http://undcp.or.at/unlinks.html">
List of United Nations servers and On-line Resources</b><br>
</A>
	This list will connect you with most U.N. resources including UNICEF.  From
there you 	can  get to the Innocenti Centre on-line catalogue of publications,
as well as Web Pages or gophers for some of the regional offices.  In the
UNICEF Eastern and Southern Africa (ESARO) web page, for example, you can find
descriptions of projects and e-mail addresses for key people in the region.<p>
<b>	</b><p>
	<b><A HREF="http://naic.nasa.gov//nsi/survey/">
Survey of International Internet Servers and K-12 connectivity</b></A><br>
<b>	</b>This site set up by NASA, offers information on internet resources on a
country by 	country basis.  If you are trying to help local or regional
organizations to get on-line and participate in electronic networking, this
might be a useful starting point in identifying local computer experts and
internet servers.    <br><p> 
 
<b>	<A HREF="http://www.odci.gov/cia/publications/95fact/index.html">
World Fact Book</A></b><br>
	The World Fact book offers a whole range of demographic information on a
country by 	country basis, with information about the people, their government,
birth, death, infant mortality rates, etc.  It also lists ethnic groups by
percentage, languages spoken, major industries and resources and a wealth of
other details that give you a capsulated profile of each country.<b>	</b><p>
 
<b>UNICEF Situational Analysis Documents</b><br>
<b></b>(not yet available on line -- contact information needed)<p>
 
<b> <A HREF="http://firewall.unesco.org">
UNESCO Education Documentation Service</A></b>
  or 
<A HREF="http://www.education.unesco.org80//edusect/"> alternate source
</A> <br>
	UNESCO is working rapidly to make its mass resources of information available
on-line 	or for easy e-mail or fax ordering.  Among other useful tidbits, they
offer an on-line directory of all the Minsters of Education in the world.
<p>
