<h1> Program and Project Profiles in Early Childhood
Care and Development</h1> 
<b> </b>Descriptions of programmes and projects in ECCD in developing countries
or with at-risk populations.  Can be selected by: <br>
 <h2>Programme Approaches:</h2> 
 <h3>1. Deliver a Service</h3> 
 <b>	<i>Models</i>:</b> <br>
<b>	Home day care</b> <br>
<b>	Integrated child development centres</b> <br>
<b>	&#147;Add-on&#148; centres</b> <br>
<b>	Preschools - formal</b> <br>
<b>			non-formal</b> <br>
<b>	Religious schools</b> <br>
<b>	Child development as part of school curriculum</b> <br>
 <h3>2. Educate Caregivers</h3> 
 <b>	<i>Models</i>:</b> <br>
<b>	Home visiting</b> <br>
<b>	Parent- teacher education</b> <br>
<b>	Child-to-child programmes</b> <br>
<b>	Schools (and teacher training) at all levels</b> <br>
 <h3>3. Promote Community Development</h3> 
 <b>	<i>Models:</i></b> <br>
<b><i>	</i>Technical mobilization</b> <br>
<b>	Social Mobilization</b> <br>
<b>	School linkage (ECCD with primary school and older)</b> <br>
 <h3>4. Strengthen National Resources and Capabilities</h3>  
<b>	<i>Models</i>:</b> <br>
<b>	Training</b> <br>
<b>	Experimental, demonstration projects</b> <br>
<b>	Strengthening infrastructure</b> <br>
<b>	Action research</b> <br>
<b>	Partnerships with diverse sectors or between groups</b> <br>
 <h3>5. Strengthen Demand and Awareness</h3> 
<b>	<i></i></b> <br>
<b><i>	Models:</i></b> <br>
<b>	Social marketing</b> <br>
<b>	Ethos creation</b> <br>
<b>	Knowledge dissemination</b> <br>
<b>	Creating enabling environment</b> <br>
 <h3>6. Develop National Child Care and Family Policies</h3> 
 <b>	<i>Models</i>:</b> <br>
<b>	Innovative joint public/private arrangements</b> <br>
<b>	Tax incentives for formal, quasi-formal private enterprises	</b> <br>
<b></b>	<b>Participatory policy development </b> <br>
 <h3>7. Develop Supportive Legal and Regulatory Frameworks</h3> 
 <b>	<i>Models</i>:</b> <br>
<b>	Workplace</b> <br>
<b>	Daycare facilities</b> <br>
<b>	Protective environmental standards</b> <br>
<b>	Maternal leave and benefits</b> <br>
<b>	Support breastfeeding for working mothers</b> <br>
<b></b>	<b>Family legislation</b> <br>
 <h3>8. Strengthen International Collaboration</h3> 
 <b>	<i>Models:</i></b> <br>
<b><i></i>	The Consultative Group on ECCD</b> <br>
<b>	Regional Networks </b> <br>
<b>	World Wide Web  </b> <br>
  These programme and project descriptions have been collected over the last 10
years.  Some of them are more extensive case studies, others are programme
profiles taken from the Consultative Group publication, the<b>
Coordinators&#146; Notebook</b> , and others have
been extracted from reports, prepared for presentations, and cited from other
sources (please note citations for those that are quoted from publications).
Over time we hope all professionals in International ECCD and all CG
participants will help us to build a large library/data base of program and
project profiles.  The Secretarial will continue to develop, with CG feedback,
outlines detailing what kinds of information to include, so that this can
become an increasingly useful data base as it builds over time. <br>
 <br>
At present, all program descriptions include the following information: <br>
	Name of country in which project takes or took place <br>
	Age group of children served (or target group if not children) <br>
	Sponsoring agency (agencies) <br>
	Contact information (if available) <br>
<b>They will be sorted according to the outline above Programme Approach, and
within that category, the type of model they represent.</b> <br>
 <A HREF="e10n.html">Guidelines for Submitting Programme Profiles for the Coordinators' Notebook,
and to be included in this data base:</A> <br>
