<H1>ECCD Programming Principles</H1>

	Given the need to respond to the rapidly growing interest in high-quality,
affordable early childhood care and development programs that can reach a
significant number of children and families, an understanding of the
programming process is critical.  First, because of the breadth and scope of
early childhood projects -- in terms of the developmental differences between
children during the first eight years of life, and in terms of the range of
needs to be met physically, socially, emotionally, cognitively and spiritually,
there are a wide variety of activities that can legitimately be undertaken.
There is no single &#145;model&#146; that could be appropriately applied to all
settings.  However, there are some basic social principles, some principles of
child development and learning that should guide programming intended to
improve the welfare of children in their early years, and there are some
operational principles that should be respected when establishing such
programmes.  They are described below:<p>
<hr>
<CENTER><b>Social Principles</b></CENTER><p>
<p>
With respect to statements of social principle, the Consultative Group finds
that it is useful for each organization to take into account assertions
presented in the Convention on the Rights of the Child, the Declaration of the
World Conference, the Summit on Children, and others, but that these positions
must be viewed critically.   The CG does agree upon several statements, by way
of preamble to the discussion of principles and guidelines, that have their
roots in affirmations found in the outcomes of recent world conferences and
conventions.  These are:<BR>
<p>
   	<IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">Children, by reason of their physical and mental immaturity, need special
safeguards and care.  Children living in especially difficult circumstances
need special consideration.<BR>
<p>
   	<IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">All children, without distinction of gender, race, language, religion or of
any other kind, should have the opportunity to develop to their full
potential.<BR>
<p>
   	<IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">Parents and families (however defined) -- men as well as women -- have the
primary responsibility for the upbringing, development and education of their
children.<BR>
<p>
   	<IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">Governments should establish a policy environment which enables families
and communities to fulfill their responsibilities of child rearing and
protection.<BR>
 <p>
<hr>
<b><CENTER>Principles of Child Development and Learning</b></CENTER><p>
<p>
	The term used by the early childhood community to describe children's
development is <i>holistic</i>.  What this means is that the child's
development cannot be compartmentalized into health, nutrition, education,
social and emotional variables.  All are interwoven in a child's life. As a
result, early childhood experiences for children, at whatever age, should be
holistic and developed around the child's developmental abilities.  Support for
this position comes from international literature on how children develop and
learn.  Specifically:<p>
<p>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*"><b>Development begins pre-natally and learning is occurring at birth.</b> Too
often the assumption is made that learning begins when children enter the
formal school system.  In fact, significant learning takes place before the
child enters school. Therefore, attention to the developmental and learning
needs of children should begin with pre- and post-natal interventions and be
continued thereafter.<br>
<p>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*"><b>Development has several inter-related dimensions, and learning occurs in
each of these areas. </b> These include physical, cognitive, social, spiritual
and emotional development, each of which influence the other and all of which
are developing simultaneously.  Progress in one area affects progress in
others.  Likewise when something goes wrong in any one of those areas it
impacts all the other areas. For example, children who are malnourished are not
able to learn, children with learning problems frequently have low self-esteem,
etc.  Developing a programme based on an understanding of holistic development
means taking the whole child into consideration, providing attention to the
child's health, nutrition, cognitive, and socio-emotional needs.  Therefore
development and learning must be seen holistically and interventions should
provide integrated attention to the child, including attention to needs for
protection, food, health care, affection, interaction and stimulation, security
provided through consistency and predictability, and play allowing exploration.
All of these elements should be present to support the child's development.<br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*"> <b>Development proceeds in predictable steps and learning occurs in recognized
sequences, within which there is a great deal of individual and social
variability in children's rates of development and styles of learning. </b> It
is important for adults to use methods that fit with the child's growth
pattern, not only in the cognitive area, but also in the affective, perceptual
and motor areas. Activities should provide the child with a developmentally
appropriate challenge. There is no value in presenting concepts and tasks
before a child is developmentally ready to understand them. Integrated
interventions promoting social, emotional and spiritual development as well as
cognitive learning can take advantage of varied forms of learning, consistent
with the culture, even while taking into account that there are recognized
sequences and activities that facilitate learning.   <br>
<p>
<IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*"> <b>Development and learning occur continuously as a result of the child
interacting with people and objects in his or her environment.</b>  The role of
adults (at home and in other settings) in supporting children's learning is to
be emotionally responsive to and involved with children, to provide children
with opportunities to work with concrete objects, make choices, explore things
and ideas, experiment and discover.  Children also need opportunities to
interact with peers and adults in a safe environment that provides the child
with security and acceptance. <br>
<p>
Given the importance of the environment in promoting children's learning, it is
also possible to focus interventions on changing the child's environment.  For
example, increasing family income, upgrading health and sanitation in the
community, and enhancing the social and political milieu will affect children's
growth and development.<p>
<p>
<IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*"> <b>Children are active participants in their own development and learning.</b>
Learning and related development involves the child's construction of
knowledge, not an adult's imposition of information.  The skills which are the
basis for constructing knowledge improve with practice. It is important for
children to have opportunities to construct their own knowledge through
exploration, interaction with materials and imitation of role models. Therefore
interventions should include opportunities for children to learn by doing, to
be engaged in problem-solving, and to develop language and communication
skills. ECCD programmes should not put undue emphasis on rote memorisation and
learning the <i>3 Rs</i>. Opportunities for active involvement should abound,
whether at home in everyday chores or in more organised settings outside the
home.<br>
	<p>
	In sum, ECCD programmes building on a holistic understanding of children's
growth and development, suggest a broad conceptualisation of early childhood
development in terms of the whole child within the context of the family and
community.  The early childhood years are perceived as the basis for learning
life-long skills and attitudes.  Activities and programmes planned for parents
and young children should not focus solely on providing children with school
survival skills, but should emphasize the development of the child's sense of
intellectual, motor and moral autonomy, initiative and self-esteem.  Emphasis
should be on <b>how to learn</b> (i.e. positive attitudes toward learning and
thinking skills) rather than <b>what to learn.</b><p>
<hr>
<center><b>Operational Principles</b></center><p>
<p>
	Some of the following operational principles are directly related to the
principles of development and learning.  Others are general principles that
apply to ECCD programmes as well as other social development programmes.<p>
<p>
<b>Identify Those Who Should be Involved in the Programme Development
Process</b> <b>: Foster participation by individuals, families and communities
who are to be the primary beneficiaries</b>.<p>
<p>
	Before one begins the programme development process it is important to
identify the people and organizations that should be a part of the process.
Historically programmes were developed by people from outside the community.
&#145;Experts&#146; got together and determined what it was that a community
needed and designed a programme for the community.  The programme was then
introduced and it may or may not have been successful based on how &#145;in
touch&#146; the experts were with the needs and resources within the community.
Today there is much greater emphasis on developing programmes with the
community, based on community-defined needs and building on community
strengths.  What this means is that communities are involved right from the
beginning.  They are part of the needs-definition process.  They are the key
actors in determining what the goals and objectives ought to be.  They plan the
activities to be undertaken. They are the primary implementors of the project.
They assist in the development of appropriate resources, and they are active in
the monitoring and evaluation process.  In other words, it is the
community&#146;s programme; the process has developed the community&#146;s
&#145;ownership&#146; of the effort.<p>
<p>
	The community is the primary &#145;stakeholder&#146; in the effort.  But there
are other groups that are also stakeholders.  A major one is the government.
In the majority of instances the expectation is that if the programme is to be
sustained over time it is necessary for the government to take some
responsibility for its continuation.  This responsibility may be in the form of
policy, laws and regulations that provide support for and recognition of the
programme, and/or the allocation of resources -- financial and human -- to
sustain the effort.<p>
<p>
	Other stakeholders include the research community. They can assist in
providing basic research which can be drawn on to help shape the ECCD
initiative.  In addition, researchers can be involved in developing the
monitoring and evaluation processes that provide necessary feedback to
implementors on the effectiveness of their programme.  Another potential
stakeholder is the private sector that may be able to provide some of the
resources to sustain the programme over time.<p>
<p>
	The more the various stakeholders are involved from the beginning, the greater
&#145;ownership&#146; they will have for the effort and the more they will be
committed to seeing that the programme is successful.<p>
<p>
 <b>Determine the Needs</b><p>
<p>
	There are several dimensions that have to be taken into consideration in
determining whether or not there is a need for an early childhood care and
development programme.  These can be divided into two groups -- those that are
related to the context within which the child lives, and those directly
associated with the child or group of children.  As assessment of both is
required before it is possible to create an ECCD programme that is appropriate,
cost effective and sustainable.<p>
<p>
	<b>Assessment of the Context</b><p>
<p>
	In assessing the context, it is worthwhile to seek answers to the following
questions:<p>
<p>
	- <i>What is happening in terms of changes in the social fabric and what are
some of the possible consequences of those changes for young children and their
families?  </i>There are a variety of forces that are impacting the family.
Today there is extensive migration.  In some parts of the world this involves
men leaving their homes and sometimes countries to seek work elsewhere.  In
other parts of the world women are the ones who are migrating.  The long
absence of either (or both) parents makes a difference in the lives of young
children.  <p>
<p>
	Other common social changes involve the movement of people from rural to urban
areas; from subsistence agriculture to paid labor, from reliance on the
extended family for a range of supports to living within a nuclear family.  The
practices in relation to childrearing that were in place before these shifts
have necessarily changed.  Sometimes there is a conscious awareness of shifts
in practice as a result of these changes; at other times new practices are
adopted without much thought.  These changes in the social system may have left
families without adequate child care, children may be living in environments
where they are at risk physically, they may lack appropriate places to play,
they may be cautioned against contact with &#145;strangers&#146;, there may be
new expectations of them in terms of their independence and ability to bring
money into the family. <p>
<p>
	There are some situations that put children at great risk in terms of
physical, social and emotional development.  These are situations of war,
violence, homelessness, and abuse.  In all these situations children learn to
fear rather than trust; they expect the unexpected instead of living in a
relatively predictable world; they live only for today with no expectations in
terms of what will be there for them tomorrow.  This social context presents
programme planners with a set of needs that must be addressed if ECCD
programmes are to be effective.<p>
<p>
	<i>- What is the economic context within which families are living?</i>  The
need to provide even the basics for a family can put a great deal of stress on
the family if there is no land to cultivate, if there are no jobs within the
formal sector and if there are few ways to earn money through the informal
sector.  Children living in the poorest families are at greatest risk of
debilitated and delayed development.  <p>
<p>
	<i>- What is the political milieu</i>?  The answer to this question is sought
through making an assessment of how individuals and communities relate to and
are served by the government.  In some societies there is a great deal of
individual freedom and autonomy.  Communities are encouraged to develop their
own programmes, with some degree of support from either local, regional or
national government.  In other contexts all decisions regarding social
programming are made by central government, leaving communities with little
flexibility in terms of the creation and implementation of programmes.  In
designing an ECCD programme it is essential to know how to position oneself in
relation to government, what resources are available and what regulations will
guide the implementation of ECCD efforts.<p>
<p>
	<i>- What is the government&#146;s social policy in relation to the family,
children, health, social services and education?  </i>Governments define their
role quite differently in terms of how much responsibility they think it is
appropriate for the family to take in terms of raising children and what they
view as the role of government in that context.  Where there are policies in
place to support the family, then these can be drawn on in creating programmes.
Where the government seeks to play a minimalist role in supporting families,
fewer resources are available for the implementation of programmes.  In this
case it may be necessary to engage in awareness raising activities in order to
facilitate the development of a more supportive policy environment.<p>
<p>
	<i>- What is current government expenditure on social programmes, and within
which ministries/departments is the spending administered?  </i>This question
is tied closely to the question of social policy. At times there are policies
in place that suggest a strong government commitment to social programmes, but
resources have not been allocated for implementation of the policy.  The
government budget should be analysed in terms of: 1) the percentage of the
national budget that is allocated to ECCD-related programmes; and 2) what that
means in real terms.  Other questions relate to where those monies are located
within the government and who controls their allocation.  In addition, it is
important to learn what the process is for obtaining the funds. <p>
<p>
	- <i>What is the role of non-governmental organizations (NGOs) within the
country?</i>  In some countries there is a long tradition of NGO involvement in
the development of social sector programmes.  In other countries NGOs are a
relatively new phenomenon.  Where they have existed they have been the ones to
develop innovative ECCD programmes that are designed to reach the poorest.  The
models they have developed and the lessons they have learned in the process can
be built on to expand coverage and use in the development of new programmes.
In countries without a strong NGO tradition, one strategy might be to help
strengthen the ability of the NGOs to work with communities to develop
appropriate ECCD programmes.<p>
<p>
	<i>- To what extent and in what ways is the private sector involved in ECCD
programmes? </i> Private industry has a great deal it can contribute to the
well-being of young children and their families.  The most direct route is
through the creation of jobs.  Beyond that the private sector can fund
programmes directly, they can provide child care, they can participate in
social marketing efforts, they can be influential in terms of policy
development.  They can be active partners in the development of social
programmes.  In order to do that, however, there needs to be legislation and
laws in place that encourage private businesses to become involved.  This can
be accomplished through tax incentives and appropriate legislation. <p>
<p>
<p>
	<b>Assessment of the Situation of Children</b><p>
	<p>
	In addition to doing an analysis of the context within which children are
being raised, it is critical to gain an understanding of the specific situation
of children.  There are some statistical data that can be gathered regarding
the number of children within a given age group.  These include the absolute
number of children at different ages, the percentage of the population that
young children represent, their urban/rural and geographic distribution, the
infant mortality rate, the under-five mortality rate, immunization rates, rates
and degree of malnutrition, etc.  In addition there are a series of questions
that need to be answered in order to target ECCD programmes to those most in
need. <p>
<p>
	<i>- What types of out-of-home care are children already receiving?  </i>This
includes the kinds of services that children are already receiving-- in terms
of health care, nutrition inputs, support for social, cognitive and spiritual
development.  This analysis should be done by social class, geographic
distribution, urban/rural residency, etc.   By looking at family income data
and/or socio-economic status it is also possible to identify those populations
of children that are the most &#145;at risk&#146; of not doing well
developmentally.  It is highly likely that these children are not included
among those children currently receiving the full range of  ECCD support.  <p>
<p>
	Once data are gathered it is possible to begin to identify children with
particular needs.  These might include children at risk of abuse, children with
special needs, children living in the poorest families, children living in
especially difficult circumstances due to war, violence and migration.   With
limited resources it is suggested that ECCD programmes for these children be
given priority. <p>
<p>
	<i>-  Who is caring for the children?</i> What are the current child care
arrangements?  Who cares for the child?  Is it only the mother?  To what extent
are other extended family members involved?  In most developing countries older
children, particularly girls, have responsibility for the care of young
siblings.  This phenomenon has led to the development of Child-to-Child
programmes where older children are provided with knowledge and skills that
assist them in their caretaking task, providing a safer and more stimulating
environment for the young child and providing the older child with skills and
knowledge that they will carry into their adult life.  When the current
caregivers are identified then it is possible to assess the knowledge and
skills and develop programmes that will enhance the ability of these
individuals to support the young child&#146;s development.<p>
<p>
	- <i>What are the current childrearing beliefs and practices?</i> It is
important to try to identify current belief systems and child rearing practices
that are guiding adult&#146;s interactions with young children.  Many
traditional beliefs and practices are very positive in promoting
children&#146;s overall development.  These should be identified and built upon
in the creation of new programmes.  Those practices which are harmful can be
replaced by alternatives that are more supportive of positive growth.<p>
<p>
	Not all of these questions can be answered by national survey or by the
standard methods used to obtain data.  Nonetheless, national statistical
bureaus are a good place to start.  Additional data can be obtained through
independent studies that can be drawn on or commissioned as required.  It is
important to involve key individuals and institutions in the process so that
they can help interpret the finding, become more aware of the situation of
young children, and develop a greater degree of commitment through their
participation.<p>
<p>
	In sum, an analysis of the context and the situation analysis for the child,
makes it possible to define the population to be served by the ECCD programme.
In general, priority should be given to families and communities in which
children are &#145;at risk&#146; of delayed or debilitated development.  The
criteria used to define &#145;at risk&#146; includes the condition of children
(birth weight, infant mortality rates, nutritional and health status,
immunization rates); the condition of women (educational levels, maternal
mortality rates, health and nutritional status, age at first pregnancy, work
demands and control of family income); family and support systems (size and
composition, employments and income, the availability of adequate support to
care for young children); childrearing practices and beliefs (feeding, health
habits, nurturance, communication); the general social conditions (access to
potable water, sanitation, literacy rates, access to social services); and the
political climate (degree of government control, stability, political will in
relation to support for families and young children).   There is no formula for
weighing these dimensions to come up with a <i>score </i>to indicate those
children who should be given first priority in an ECCD programme.  The
political realities combined with social conscience, technical competence,
resources and experience are likely to act as strong forces in determining who
is to benefit from ECCD programmes. <p>

<hr>
<b>Define the Goals and Objectives of ECCD Programming</b><p>
		<p>
 	Once the needs are clearly defined then it is important to determine how the
needs might  be addressed through an ECCD programme.  That is, what can one
hope to accomplish by providing an ECCD programme?  What are the goals and
objectives of ECCD programmes?<p>
<p>
	An overarching goal for child development programmes is <i>to assure the right
of each child to realize his or her potential.   </i>The child&#146;s potential
is likely to be defined differently across cultures.  Thus what this means is
that the specific objectives derived from the general one will be
culture-specific.  For example, in some cultures there is greater emphasis on
independence.  In other cultures what is most important is for the child to
find his or her place within an inter-dependent social group.  Expectations in
terms of how children relate to their elders are different; the value of
convergent versus divergent thinking is different.  Thus the specific
objectives of ECCD programmes will differ.<p>
<p>
	As has been noted in the section on <b>Program Strategies</b>, children are
not the only beneficiaries of ECCD programmes.  What follows is a listing of
the possible goals and objectives that can be accomplished through ECCD
programmes, for children, families, communities and the society at large.<p>
<p>

<pre>
Potential Benefits of ECCD Programmes*

Children	Psycho-social Development	Improved cognitive development(thinking, reasoning)
						Improved Social development (relation to others)
						Improved emotional development (self-image, security)
						Improved language skills

		Health and Nutrition		Increased chances of survival; Reduced morbidity;
						Improved hygiene; Improved weight/height for age;
						Improved micronutrient balance

		Progress and Performance	High chance of entering school; Less chance of repeating;
						Higher learning and better performance

Caregivers   (Parents, ECCD programme staff, older children)
		General Knowledge		Health and Hygiene; Nutrition (related to own status);
						Leadership skills

		Attitudes and Practice    	Health and hygiene; Preventive medical monitoring/
						Attention; Opportune treatment; Nutrition; Improved diet; 
						Improved self-esteem

		Relationships			Husband-wife; Parents-older children; Among children

		Employment			Caregivers freed to seek or improve employment; New 
						Employment opportunities created by programme; Increased
						Market for programme-related goods

Communities	Physical Environment		Sanitation, Access to potable water; Spaces for play;
						New multi-purpose facilities
		
		Social				Greater participation in life of community; Solidarity;
						Development of problem-solving and decision-making
						Skills; Empowerment

Institutions	Efficiency			Improved delivery of service (health, education, social);
						Greater coverage; 
		Effectiveness			Improved outcomes (higher immunization rates, lower
						under-five mortality; decreased morbidity; reduced
						drop-out and repetition
		Capacity			Changes in skills, competence, confidence
		Content				Improved curriculum, methodology

Society		Quality of Life			A healthier population; A more literate population;
						Greater social participation; An improved labor force;
						Reduced delinquency; Reduced fertility and early births;
						Reduced social inequalities
						
* Adapted from: R.G. Myers, 1995. Early Childhood Care and Development Programmes in Latin America and the Caribbean: A Review of Experience, SDS/WID Work Paper Series No. 1, Inter-American Development Bank, Washington D.C., pg. 51

</pre>



<hr>
<p>
<b>ECCD Programmes Should be Developed within a Broad Conceptual Framework and
Form a Part of a Comprehensive, Multi-faceted Strategy: Programmes should not
be developed in isolation of other social services</b><p>
<p>
	There is unity in a child&#146;s needs.  Therefore, ECCD programmes should be
part of a broad conceptual effort that addresses the needs of children from
birth through the early primary years.  Integration of services should be
sought in the conceptualization, planning and implementation of services. This
principle derives in part from the holistic nature of child development in
which physical, mental, social and emotional dimensions of development affect
each other.  Hence, effectiveness requires integrated attention to children.
In addition, there is a maximization of resources when programmes are
multi-dimensional, combining health, nutrition, education and social actions.
<p>
<p>
	Attempting to adhere to this guideline does not mean that all components must
appear in all programmes of all those providing ECCD services.  Nevertheless,
an overall strategy that is comprehensive and multi-faceted should frame all
child development programme efforts.  Opportunities should be sought to blend
services, to encourage multi-sectoral collaboration, and to fit new components
into on-going programmes whenever it is opportune.<p>
<p>
	Further, complementary strategies should be developed and implemented to meet
ECCD goals.  Since the child's development is affected by the environment (the
home, the community, social institutions, legal frameworks, and a cultural
ethos) a comprehensive programme to improve child development should function
simultaneously at different levels, focusing respectively on the child,
caregivers and national institutions and policies.  <p>
<p>
	ECCD programmes should also take an inter-generational view, seeking ways to
take into account the needs of families as well as the needs of children, and
to involve children, youth and adults in ECCD programmes.  Programmes of early
childhood development can and should benefit parents, other caregivers and
community members as well as children.  Child care, for instance, is generally
the responsibility of various family members (older siblings and extended
family members in addition to fathers and mother). Thus ECCD programmes can
focus on supporting these individuals in their caregiving task.<p>
<p>
<b>Begin with What Exists and Build from There</b><p>
<p>
	This principle derives from a belief that programmes are sustainable when they
are built on the &#145;known&#146; in people&#146;s lives.  Programmes that
introduce ideas and practices that are too &#145;foreign&#146; seldom take
hold.  Thus ECCD programme models should build on the strengths of communities.
These include: traditional family units and social structures that can be
mobilised; rich traditional practices that are supportive of children's growth
and development;  parents' strong desire to provide the best for their
children; people's desire for education and knowledge; and the networks that
have been created as a result of the fact that many people belong to churches
and religious organisations.  When people feel that their current practices and
beliefs are respected and recognized it gives them confidence to entertain
other ways of doing things.<p>
<p>
	This principle also applies to current social programmes that are in place.
It suggests that it is possible to expand the mandate of current social
programmes to provide a more holistic range of services.  For example:
education components can be added to nutrition programmes; child development
information can be provided by the health care profession when they work with
families; parenting information can be included as modules within literacy
programmes; current children&#146;s T.V. programmes can be modified to
encourage better health and nutrition.  And the list goes on.<p>
<p>
	Building on what exists within the community and the larger cultural ethos
provides a maximization of resources and reinforces a holistic view of
children&#146;s development.<p>
<p>
<b>Identify Partners at all Levels to Support the Creation, Implementation and
Sustainability of ECCD Programmes</b><p>
<p>
	ECCD provision should be created and expanded through partnerships at all
levels -- from the community to local, regional and national government, to
non-governmental partners. The principle of developing partnerships between
government, non-governmental agencies, the private sector and the community
arises from social as well as financial needs. Neither government nor
communities, nor a wide range of non-governmental organisations, can easily
maintain an effective ECCD programme without help.    In most countries, the
development, management and funding of early childhood provision is the joint
responsibility of the state, regional and local governments, the private
sector, the community and parents. The notion of creating partnerships is
consistent with a holistic view of the child and it will: decrease duplication
of services in some areas with other areas being under-served; assure more
equitable access to ECCD programmes; and maximise the use of human and fiscal
resources.<p>
<p>
	Within many governments there is an increasing focus on the development of
community-based programmes and the strengthening of communities to define their
own needs and develop their own resources, thus decreasing their dependency on
the State.   Early Childhood Care and Development programmes should be
developed in collaboration with the community. A growing body of experience
shows that community participation increases the effectiveness of most
programmes.  Community participation also allows extension of the services
beyond what would be possible using only the budgets and resources of the
public sector. Specifically, community-based programmes: build local capacity
to identify needs and seek solutions; create ownership and accountability;
encourage unity and strength within the community; enhance the probability that
decisions will be implemented and that programmes will be maintained once
initial outside support is withdrawn; and empower people to make decisions in
relation to all aspects of their lives.<p>
<p>
	Other important partners are non-governmental organisations (NGOs), which, in
many countries, have made significant contributions to ECCD programmes.  In a
wide range of countries the NGO community has developed both appropriate ECCD
delivery systems and training. Their experiences, skills and knowledge should
be maintained and built upon. Capitalising on the experience of these agencies
enhances the provision of ECCD programmes.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>ECCD Programmes Should:</b><p>
<p>
<ul>
<b>	 Provide Equity in Access.</b> 
</ul>
<p>
	While the aim is to provide universal attention to young children, there is
special recognition of children living in conditions that put them at increased
risk of delayed or debilitated development.  This strategy recognizes the need
for all children to be supported as they grow and develop, while stressing the
urgency of attending to children living in poverty or those who are
discriminated against as a result of ethnicity.  The sustainability of
programmes, and in particular those in remote and isolated areas, is a critical
factor in determining a strategy that will increase and maintain access.<p>
<p>
<ul>
<b>Be Flexible and Reflect Diversity</b>  
</ul>
<p>
	This principle derives in part from the social and individual variation in
children's needs. It is not necessary nor appropriate for all children to
receive the same kind of early childhood services.    This principle is also
derived from a recognition of the cultural diversity which exists within a
given country. Nations, communities and cultures differ widely in the
particular needs of their children.  Unless programme planners can be
responsive to these differences they risk designing efforts that are irrelevant
to the population to be served. The actual form the programme takes will vary
depending on local and regional needs and resources. Out of respect for this
diversity ECCD programmes will necessarily differ. <p>
<p>
<ul>
	<b>Ensure Quality</b>  
</ul>
	It is essential that quality not be lost as a result of tyring to implement
&#145;low-cost&#146; models and/or increasing the coverage of proven models.
The argument that efforts should be aimed at increasing supply before
endeavouring to improve quality misses the essential point that without quality
costs will be incurred later on, in schooling and by society.  	Low quality
programmes are ineffective, deprive children of benefits, and represent a waste
of resources.  <p>
	A quality programme is one that is appropriate to the child's stage of
development and addresses the needs of the child, while respecting individual
differences.   In seeking quality, it should be recognized that quality is
affected by the motivation and training of programme personnel, the physical
environment, the materials used, the curriculum, and the supports available to
providers.  (See <A HREF="e15.html">Program Structure</A>)<p>
<p>
	It is also important to recognize that quality cannot be legislated.  Setting
norms and standards does not guarantee quality.  Neither is quality defined by
expenditure level. Nonetheless a process for establishing standards (in
relation to facilities, staffing, curriculum and programme quality) and for
effective monitoring needs to be established.  This should include a clear
definition of responsibility for standards at the central, the regional and
community levels. Standards should be complementary and consistent across the
health, welfare and education sectors.  What is important is that quality be
defined within the national context, and that it not be identified only with
high-cost pre-primary school models.<p>
<p>
<ul>
	<b>Be Cost-effective</b>
</ul>
<p>
	Clearly it must be possible to implement programmes within recognized
resource constraints, and they should be economically feasible over time.  The
economic feasibility of a programme is only partly a matter of available funds.
It is also a matter of priorities and how funds are allocated.  If a programme
is accorded a high priority, it can be implemented by giving up something that
has a lower priority. Thus public awareness and political will are important
dimensions in determining feasibility.<p>
<p>
	Even when ECCD programmes are seen as a priority, those involved in such
efforts are concerned about identifying and implementing cost-effective models.
Resources need to be used efficiently and effectively.  Thus there is a need to
create and promote the adoption of low-cost programmes to ensure maximum
coverage.  However, low-cost programmes are not necessarily the best.  Too
often low-cost means low quality. If programmes are of such a low cost that
they are ineffective they represent a waste of resources. There needs to be a
systematic evaluation of a programme to determine the balancing point between
cost and quality. In general, strategies that stress prevention are more
cost-effective than compensatory strategies.<p>
<p>
	Because the need is so great, programmers should give priority to those
programmes that offer the best prospect of reaching the most children who are
&#145;at risk&#146;.  That means looking beyond demonstration and pilot
projects to the possibility of expansion and replication of the programme
model.<p>
	<p>
<b>Determine the Appropriate Size for the Project/Programme; Coverage should be
achieved by combining a variety of approaches rather than developing a single
national model meant to apply to all.</b>  <p>
<p>
	One of the things that is very difficult in designing a project/programme is
to determine an appropriate size for the programme.  It needs to be large
enough that the per beneficiary costs are not exorbitant, creating a project
that it is neither possible to expand nor replicate.  On the other hand, the
initial effort needs to be realistic in coverage based on the human, technical
and financial resources available.  Political pressures sometimes result in
projects being designed that cannot be implemented in a way to assure programme
quality and impact.<p>
<p>
Thus it is important to begin with a pilot project that reaches a reasonable
percentage of the target beneficiaries, with an eye to what it would take to
expand the project, if it were successful.  Further, the timeline for project
implementation needs to be realistic, based on resources -- human and financial
-- that are available.<p>
<p>
	Attention to all the children should be sought through a series of different
programmes responding to distinct needs.  When projects are successful there is
a temptation to take the project to &#145;scale&#146; to reach desired
coverage.  In the early days, it was assumed that scale was best achieved by
taking an exemplary project and expanding it to achieve national coverage.  By
and large, experiences with such expansion efforts have not been successful.
This is the result of several factors.  For example, projects that are
appropriate in one geographical area are not necessarily what is required in
another part of the country; the NGO that created the initial project may not
have the capacity to expand its own staff and capability to support the
implementation of a large project; the dynamics in terms of the way the project
was created and developed are difficult to replicate in large-scale
expansion.<p>
<p>
	As a result, today &#147;scale&#148; is defined as the sum of varied programme
efforts rather than the expansion of a single model.  This allows for cultural
variation; it allows for differences in terms of needs and resources; it allows
for the development of a variety of approaches, based on what is required and
the skills and competencies of those working with a given population; it allows
for more specific targeting, rather than attempting a blanket coverage; and it
provides for the development of more local ownership rather than having the
programme established from a central point.<p>
<p>
	Myers (1995) argues that scale should be achieved through<i> association</i>
or <i>addition.</i>  Scale is achieved by combining several models, varying in
size and carried out with relative independence, addressing the needs in its
own way, but with a <b>common goal or framework</b>. Scale by association is
like a puzzle.  All the pieces need to fit within the framework and when all
the pieces are in place the puzzle is whole -- coverage is achieved.  Myers
cites Chile as a country which has achieved scale through the implementation of
at least three major models, with several minor ones also involved, which
together, add up to significant coverage. (Myers. IADB, 1995, p. 23)<p>
<p>
<b>Create Systems for Monitoring, Assessment and Evaluation of the Programme
from the Outset.  </b><p>
<b></b><p>
	Programmes are only effective and sustainable when they include the capacity
to analyse strengths and weaknesses and to adjust programmes accordingly.
Assessment/evaluation processes need to be an integral part of all programmes.
This should occur at several levels.  There should be an assessment of the
child's developmental progress.  There should be an evaluation of the impact of
the provision on the child's progress through school and in relation to
life-long learning.  As well as focusing on the child, there should be an
evaluation of the ECCD programme being provided and the formal primary school
system the child is entering.  An assessment of the teacher training and
support process is critical.  And there should be an assessment of the
effectiveness of linking parents, the community, NGOs and government for the
purposes of supporting children's development. <p>
<p>
	Few ECCD programmes have been adequately evaluated.  One of the primary
reasons is that programme evaluation and monitoring is seldom considered as the
programme is designed.  It is frequently tacked on at the end and conducted by
someone outside the system.  There is also a lack of expertise in programme
evaluation, a paucity of  widely accepted child development impact measures,
and little realization of the value of on-going feedback and monitoring in
terms of continuing to improve the programme.  Another difficulty is that
alternative approaches to ECCD programming require alternative monitoring and
evaluation systems.  As there is no one model of ECCD provision, so there is no
one evaluation model that can be applied across the board.  Innovative data
collection techniques must be created, techniques that capture both the
intended and unintended outcomes of programmes for children, families and the
community.<p>
<p>
	There are several arguments in support of strong well-developed evaluations.
First, documentation of success is a powerful tool in eliciting the attention
as well as sustaining the commitment of policy-makers and planners.  Second,
evaluations can identify the factors that are fundamental to achieving
programme goals and assuring quality.  Third, evaluations can provide the
information that planners need to determine the extent to which a model can be
expanded and/or replicated.  Fourth, evaluations allow for cross-programme
comparisons of the effectiveness of alternative programming strategies.<p>
<p>
	Evaluations need to be designed at several levels.  There are evaluation
processes that can be used by parents and other caregivers to monitor
children&#146;s development.  There also needs to be an evaluation system put
into place to assess the impact of the training and support systems provided
for caregivers and others who work in the programme.  Evaluations can also be
conducted at the institutional level to assess the effectiveness of the
management systems in place.  And programmes can be evaluated in terms of their
impact on the community and the nation.  Thus, in addition to monitoring
individual programmes, it is necessary to evaluate the extent to which national
goals have been achieved. <p>
<p>
In designing the evaluation/ monitoring system the following principles
should be considered:<p>
<p>
	<b>Demystify the evaluation process</b>.  Evaluation and monitoring are seen
as something that is <i>done to</i> a programme, not something that can help
those involved in the programme do their job better.  Work with those involved
in developing and implementing the programme to identify what they need to know
to do their jobs better and develop ways to gather that information.  As people
receive evaluation data that they can use immediately in their work, they will
become more involved in the process and help develop instruments that are the
most useful.<p>
<p>
	<b>Involve all stakeholders in the evaluation process</b>.  The
stakeholders--from parents to policy-makers--should be a part of defining the
desired outcomes and be a part of collecting the data.  The extent that the
various stakeholders are involved on a day-to-day basis will depend on  when
they need to have the information that the process produces.<p>
<p>
	<b>Determine what information will be needed at each phase of the project in
order to make sound decisions</b>.   Define the kinds of information that is
required in order to enable the programme to grow and become stronger, both in
relation to the programme&#146;s operation, and in terms of longitudinal
results that can affect policy makers and the programme&#146;s ability to be
expanded or replicated in other settings.  Decide what kind of information will
be needed: soon after the programme begins (e.g. the demographics of the
children who are being served by the programme; the extent and kinds of parent
response; the extent to which various institutions and organizations are
supporting the programme; if there are skills and competencies that caregivers
do not have); at a mid-point in the programme (e.g. the types of families
involved in the programme and the turnover since the programme has begun; the
capability of staff to operate the programme with their current level of
training and supervision; additional training needs; the costs of the programme
as compared to anticipated costs); end of programme evaluation (immediate
impact on beneficiaries; costs and how they are being funded; projection of
costs into the future and who will pay them; potential to continue at same
size; potential for expansion); longitudinally (e.g. as compared to
alternatives,  the lasting impact of the programme on beneficiaries, costs and
financing).<p>
<p>
<b>	Define the evaluation methods to be used that will provide useful ongoing
information to programme providers, as well as methods to be used for the
purpose of summative information for decision-makers. </b> Most evaluations
will require a mix of quantitative and qualitative evaluation methods.  There
are some data that can easily be gathered for quantitative evaluation purposes
(number of children, ages of children, malnutrition rates, height/weight,
characteristics of parents (education, employment), staff/beneficiary ratios,
staff characteristics, etc.  To acquire a more in-depth understanding of the
programme and what it is accomplishing, however, qualitative data are of more
value.  This involves gathering information about attitudes and beliefs.  There
are a variety of instruments and processes that have been developed for the
gathering of both quantitative and qualitative data.  <p>
<p>
	<hr>
<b>Develop Strategies from the Beginning that Assure</b> <b>Programme
Sustainability</b><p>
<p>
	This principle addresses the issue of planning from the beginning to see that
the programme, if successful, will be maintained after the initial investment
is made.  The following should be taken into consideration as the programme is
being conceptualized and developed.<p>
<p>
	<b>Develop stakeholder &#147;ownership&#148; of programmes</b>.   If the
programme is developed with the community, then it is based on their needs.
They have helped to develop what the programme will do and how it will be
implemented.  As a result of this involvement from the beginning, and if the
programme does in fact meet their needs, they will work to find ways for the
programme to continue.  If the programme is handed to them, fully designed and
funded, the community will make use of the programme to the extent that it
meets their needs, but when external financing ends,  the community is unlikely
to make an effort to see that the programme continues.<p>
	<b>Build the capacity of individuals, the community and institutions to
continue the programme</b>.   It takes more than just financial resources to
sustain a programme.  There must be the capacity within the institution
offering the programme to continue to provide quality services.  The building
of institutional capacity may involve creating an NGO if the programme was
started by an individual.  It may involve taking a relatively small NGO and
enlarging it.  This frequently involves shifts in functions and requires
training and other technical supports for those taking on new roles and
responsibilities.<p>
<p>
	<b>Create a financing system for the programme</b>.  Many ECCD programmes
begin as innovative pilot efforts that are funded by external sources --
foundations, donor agencies, bi-lateral agencies, UN organizations and
international NGOs.  Frequently the mandate of these organizations is to
provide funding in the initial stages of a programme&#146;s evolution.  There
is funding for 3-6 years of time.  The expectation is that at the end of that
time period, if the programme has been successful it will have developed
alternative funding sources that will help sustain the work.  Frequently there
is the expectation that the community will fund parts of the programme.  That
is possible in some communities.  But if the ECCD programme is truly reaching
the poorest of the poor, no matter how willing or committed, the community can
provide only a fraction of the real programme costs.  Other possible funders
include the government, non-governmental organizations, and the private sector.
Some programmes even begin their own income-generating activities to subsidize
the programme.  Regardless of the strategy employed, it is most likely to be
successful if planning for the long-term funding of the programme is a part of
the initial programme design process.  It takes time to develop alternative
funding sources.<p>
<p>
	<b>Develop public education and promotional work that supports social adoption
of a service or programme</b>.  Programmes have a much greater possibility of
being sustained if the general public is aware of the programme and what it is
accomplishing.  Thus documentation and evaluation of the effort is critical.
The more that is known about the programme and what it can do, the more likely
it will be continued.  The media and popular press should be provided with
information, they should be invited to visit and feature the programme.
Identify a public figure that believes in the effort and get them to promote
the programme.  We live in a world that is governed by media, so take advantage
of that.<p>
<p>
	<b>Work with policy-makers to ensure the development and implementation of
policy that will create an enabling environment for ECCD programming.</b>  In
many instances exemplary pilot programmes that were well developed and
evaluated have fallen by the wayside because there has not been the political
backing that is necessary to sustain efforts over time.  Appropriate
legislation and policy will help assure programme continuation.  Once again, as
the programme is being designed it should be done with an understanding of
current government policy and how that policy will either support or inhibit
the development of the effort.  If there need to be changes in government
policy then activities related to lobbying and policy development should be
included among programme activities.	<p>
<p>
<HR>
