<h1>Program Strategies in Early Childhood Care and
Development </h1><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>Programme Approaches</b>:<p>
<p>
	&#147;For too many people, a child development project or programme
immediately conjures up the image of 25 or 30 small children, ages 3 to 5,
playing with blocks or fitting triangles and squares into brightly colored
puzzle boards, supervised by a professional teacher in a &#145;preschool&#146;
classroom. Associating child development with this &#145;preschool&#146; model
is unfortunate because it focuses narrowly on a child&#146;s mental
development, is relatively expensive, and begins late in a child&#146;s life.
It also involves a direct, &#145;institutional&#146; approach, relying on the
creation of centres that &#145;compensate&#146; for missing elements in the
family and community members, while, too often, leaving parents and community
members out of the programme.  This image seldom provides the most appropriate
guide to programming for child care and development in Third World
locations.&#148;  (Myers, The Twelve Who Survive, 1995, pg. 83)<br>
<p>
	Early childhood care and development (ECCD) programmes are much broader than
that--in terms of their purposes, the forms they can take and the potential
beneficiaries.  Within this section a variety of approaches that can be taken
in relation to ECCD will be outlined.<br>
<p>
1. 	<b>Deliver a Service Directly to Children</b>.  This approach focuses
directly on the child from the time the child is born up until school entry age
(0-6/7).  The immediate goal of this approach is to enhance child development
by attending to the immediate needs of children in &#145;centres&#146; outside
the child&#146;s home.  The objectives of these programmes include: child
survival, child care, socialization, overall child development, programmes that
&#145;prepare&#146; children for school, and rehabilitation programmes. These
programmes can be offered in centres designed specifically as a pre-school or
child care centre, but they are also found in a neighbor home, in a community
centre, in the market place and under the trees.   In other words these
programmes can exist anywhere children are brought together in a group.  <br>
<p>
	There are advantages and disadvantages related to the direct provision of
service.  The benefits include:<br>
<p>
<ul>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">direct attention allows programme implementors to know what kinds of services
the child is actually receiving;<br>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">grouping children facilitates protection, health care and nutritional
monitoring;<br>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">for children 3-6/7 years of age it provides them with a chance to socialize
with their peers in ways not possible when they stay at home, preparing them
for socializing within the culture and preparing them for the school
environment;<br>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">it is possible to monitor children&#146;s physical, social, emotional and
cognitive development and plan activities accordingly and to identify children
with special needs;<br>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">centres provide visibility that can be useful politically, both to get
programmes going and to sustain them;<br>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">ECCD centre-based programmes can serve as an entry point into the community to
foster community development objectives.<br>
<p>
</ul>
There are also cautions associated with focusing only on the development and
implementation of programmes for children in centres/groups.  These include:<p>
<p>
<ul>
<IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">increasing the child&#146;s exposure to communicable diseases;<br>
<IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">the potential conflict that can occur between home and centre in terms of
language, values and beliefs;<br>
<IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">the fact that some parents then turn their children over to the
&#145;experts&#146;, abrogating their responsibility in terms of supporting
children&#146;s growth and development.<br>
</ul>
<p>
Models: Purpose-built centres for young children<br>
	  Family day care where children are provided for in a home in the
neighborhood<br>
	  &#145;Add-on&#146; programmes within community centres, women&#146;s
programmes, health centres,
	         Religious schools<br>
	   <p>
Programme examples: India - ICDS; Peru - PRONOEI; Colombia - Family Daycare
Homes - Homes of Well-Being; Nepal - Entry point project.<p>
<p>
<p>
2.	 <b>Support and Educate Caregivers.</b>  The focus of these programmes is on
those who care for and are responsible for the growth and development of young
children.  Included in these programmes are efforts to support and educate
parents, community members, care providers and/or older children.  The
objective is to create awareness of the importance of the caregivers&#146;s
role in relation to supporting children&#146;s growth and development, and to
change attitudes, beliefs and practices.  Ultimately these programmes empower
caregivers in ways that will improve their care of and interaction with young
children and enrich the immediate environment within which children live.<p>
<p>
	Once again there are benefits and cautions related to these programmes. The
benefits include:<p>
<ul>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">both caregivers and children can benefit from the programme;<p>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">when educating parents their roles and responsibility can be reinforced;<br>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">improvements in development are more likely to be sustained because activities
that promote the child&#146;s development are part of the child&#146;s everyday
life and not provided only for a few hours a day;<br>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">broad coverage can be achieved at relatively low costs;<br>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">ECCD components can be added to existing programmes, for example, literacy
programmes, health centre provision and women&#146;s groups.<br>
</ul>
<p>
In terms of cautions:<p>
<ul>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">to be effective the information provided to caregivers must be timely in
relation to the child&#146;s developmental stage;<br>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">information should be culturally appropriate, building on current beliefs and
practices while adding to caregivers&#146; knowledge;<br>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">the teaching/learning process must be participatory, allow for interpersonal
exchange and mutual support;<br>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">the education of caregivers is an on-going process; goals are unlikely to be
achieved through a &#145;one-shot&#146; training.<br>
</ul>
<p>
Models: Parent education classes<br>
	  Home Visiting<br>
	  Child-to-Child programmes<br>
	  Literacy programmes with child development content<br>
             Training programmes for those who work in ECCD programmes<br>
<p>
Programme Examples:   Indonesia: BKB; Jamaica - Child-to-Child; China - Parent
Schools; Thailand - Integrated Nutrition and Community Development Project;
Chile- The Parents and Children Programme<p>
<p>
<p>
3. 	<b>Promote Community Development</b>.  Emphasis in these programmes is on
changing conditions within the community that make a difference in terms of
children&#146;s ability to survive and thrive. There is emphasis on building on
community initiative and the empowerment of the community to define its needs
and to develop strategies for meeting those needs.  This can include water and
sanitation projects or other efforts that improve the physical environment and
have an impact on the child&#146;s health, nutrition and general development.
It also includes projects that increase the knowledge and skills base within
the community and the ability of the community to organize around a common
problem.<p>
<p>
	The benefits of such efforts include:<p>
<ul>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">the programme impacts on the whole community, enhancing the quality of life
for all community members;<br>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">the effects of the programme are likely to be sustainable;<br>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">the programme can provide the base for the development of a series of efforts
that will empower the community to act on its own behalf socially and
politically. <br>
</ul>
<p>
The cautions include:<p>
<ul>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">the benefits of the programmes may take a long time to or never
&#145;trickle-down&#146; to children;<br>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">the poorest of the poor may not benefit directly from the programme;<p>
 there is no way to monitor the services children actually receive, nor to
monitor the child&#146;s health, nutritional, and developmental status.<br>
</ul>
<p>
Models: Water and Sanitation Projects<br>
	   Micro-enterprise projects for women <p>
<p>
4. 	<b>Strengthen National Resources and Capabilities.</b> There are many
individuals and agencies/institutions involved in carrying out the approaches
listed above.  In order to do an adequate job, they need financial, material,
and training resources that provide them with the capacity to plan, organize,
implement and evaluate ECCD efforts.  Thus within this category are programmes
that develop institutional and human resource capability.  These include the
training of staff and administrative personnel, the provision of materials, the
upgrading of physical facilities and the introduction of new technologies.<p>
<p>
	The benefits and cautions connected with this strategy and those that follow
(numbers 5, 6, 7, 8,) are all similar.  Basically the strategy is designed to
make a difference in the child&#146;s environment and in the cultural and
political ethos that surrounds families as they raise their children.  It is
difficult to see the impact of these strategies on the lives of specific
children, but there is a strong belief that without these efforts direct
service provision and the work with parents and other caregivers is
unsustainable, and it is difficult for the child to maintain the gains made in
early childhood programmes.<p>
<p>
Models:   <br>
	Training of supervisors, managers and programme developers<br>
	Linkage programmes which upgrade the quality of the primary school and prepare
it to 		receive children with and without prior &#145;pre-school&#146;
experience.<br>
	Providing teachers and caregivers with appropriate materials<br>
	Providing a safe and secure environment within which programmes can be
offered<br>
	Development of  in-country research capability through national and
international training 		and exchanges.<br>
	<p>
5. 	<b>Strengthen Demand and Awareness</b>.  This programme approach
concentrates on getting information on the importance of the early years to a
broad audience, to both raise their awareness and increase the demand for ECCD
services, and create an &#145;enabling environment&#146; for young children and
their families.  The potential audience includes policy-makers and politicians
and the general public, as well as families and communities who could benefit
directly and immediately from ECCD programmes.<p>
<p>
Models: Social marketing<br>
	  Media exposure to concepts and projects (radio, T.V. videos and films)<br>
	  Coalition building/petitioning<br>
	  Linkage to national and international efforts to raise awareness (e.g
Education for All,
		Convention on the Rights of the Child)<br>
<p>
6. 	Develop National Child Care and Family Policies.  Ultimately to make ECCD
programmes sustainable over time it is necessary to have policies in place
which support the development and implementation of ECCD programmes.  Policies
need to be in place that encourage family-sensitive social service delivery
systems and employment.  Thus programmes within this category are focussed on
analyzing current policies and getting involved in the process for creating new
policies if that is required, and/or facilitating the implementation of current
policies that are supportive.<p>
<p>
Models: Participatory policy reviews (Malaysia, Namibia, South Africa)<p>
Creation of policies related to the Convention on the Rights of the Child and a
procedure      to monitor compliance (e.g. National Plans of Action - official
and unofficial)<p>
	Development of Government/NGO and private partnerships from a policy
perspective<p>
	Development of policies that are supportive of women&#146;s participation in
the home and 	     workplace<p>
<p>
7. 	<b>Develop Supportive Legal and Regulatory Frameworks</b>.  There needs to
be a legal framework which allows for the institutionalization of
non-governmental agencies and the private sector to engage in the provision of
programmes that support young children and their families.  Further regulations
need to be established which help govern the implementation of programmes,
serving as one aspect of quality assurance in terms of direct provision.
Programmes within this strategy are designed to increase people&#146;s
awareness of their rights and legal resources, increase the use of ILO
legislation, and increase monitoring of and compliance with international
conventions.<p>
  <p>
Models: Development of regulations/standards for ECCD centre-based programmes
<br>
	Development of creative mechanisms for funding ECCD programmes<br>
               ( Colombia - taxes earmarked for ECCD programmes; Mauritius -
Children&#146;s Fund)<br>
	Develop legal structures that support Government, NGO and private
partnerships<br>
	Development of employee benefits to support male and female responsibilities
within the 	    family (maternal/paternal leave, breast-feeding for working
mothers, child care)<br>
	Development of protective environmental standards<br>
<p>
8. 	<b>Strengthen International Collaboration</b>.  Currently most of the major
international and bilateral donor agencies are involved in funding the
provision of ECCD programmes.  To facilitate the exchange of lessons being
learned, collaborate in terms of programme development and mitigate against the
duplication of efforts, there are formal and informal mechanisms that have been
established that encourage collaboration.  The direct beneficiaries of this
strategy include donor agencies, UN agencies, international NGOs, foundations,
policy-makers and researchers.<p>
<p>
Models:<br>
 <A HREF="cgroup.html">The Consultative Group on Early Childhood Care and Development</A> <br>
	DAE: Development for African Education<br>
	<A HREF="reg.html">Regional Networks</A><br>
<HR>
