<html><head></head><body>
<title>Programme Structure</title>
<h1> Programme Structure</h1><p>
<p>
	This section defines the components that need to be considered in creating and
implementing an ECCD programme.  It describes what needs to be put into place
in order to serve the beneficiaries.  Essentially it answers the questions of
<b><i>what </i></b>(curriculum, activities and materials), <b><i>how
</i></b>(the organization of the services and the methodology used with
beneficiaries)<b><i> </i></b>,<b><i> where</i></b> (location and facilities
required), <b><i>when </i></b>(timing of programme activities, daily schedule),
<b><i>who </i></b>(the human resources required for the programme - staffing)
and <b><i>how much</i></b> (costs).  The <b><i>why</i></b> is described in
<A HREF="argu.html">
Arguments in Support of ECCD</A> and the<b><i> who</i></b> in terms
of beneficiaries is described in <A HREF="e13.html">ECCD Programming Principles.</A><p>
<p>
The <b><i>What</i></b> of ECCD Programming<p>
<p>
	The <b><i>What </i></b>of ECCD programming is the curriculum.  We define
curriculum as <i>the plan for providing learning opportunities for the
beneficiaries</i>.  The plan includes a specification of objectives and the
content to be conveyed, and a specification of activities to be undertaken. It
also provides a way to evaluate whether or not the objectives were reached.
This definition of curriculum allows us to talk about the kinds of ECCD
programme opportunities that are planned for parents, children and the
community within various Programme Strategies.<br>
<p>
	Different Programme Strategies require different kinds of curricula.  There
are a variety of curriculum models available for providing services for
children, particularly within the 3-6 age-group.  The best known
internationally are the <u>Montessori</u> and the<u> High/Scope Curriculum</u>
for centre-based programmes.  The <u>Hippy Program</u> is a model used
internationally for home visiting programmes.  All of these have been adapted
for implementation, based on the cultural context.<p>
Some countries provide national curriculum guidelines that can be adapted
locally.  <u>The Kenya Institute of Education Early Childhood Curriculum</u> is
a good example of this.<br>
<p>
	Parent education materials tend to be developed locally, drawing on
information from a wide variety of sources.  The most centralized parent
education curriculum is the Parent School curriculum in China. <br>
<p>
	The curriculum actually delivered through an ECCD programme is dependent on
the objectives of the programme.  For example, if there is a desire to work
with parents and provide them with additional parenting skills, then the
&#147;what&#148; has to do with the kinds of information that you wish parents
to receive.  This may include information on how children grow and develop.  It
might include information on health and nutrition; it might address
socialization issues; it might provide information on quality child care.  The
specific content will depend on the needs that parents have defined for
themselves and the information that professionals think it is important for
parents to receive.<br>
<p>
	There are several marks of a good curriculum.  They include*:<p>
<ul>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">Were data reflecting the characteristics of the learners, the social and
cultural milieu, the nature of knowledge and the learning process available to
those planning the curriculum?  How is this reflected in the curriculum?<br>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">Are the goals of the programme clearly stated and understood by all concerned?
Are the values and assumptions underlying the goals known?  Are the goals
sufficiently comprehensive, balanced and realistic?  Is there provision for
modifying, dropping and adding goals as needed?<br>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">Is the curriculum plan a part of a comprehensive community-wide plan?<br>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">Do the learning opportunities anticipate a progression from dependent,
other-directed learning to independent self-directed learning in accordance
with the level of the learner?<br>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">Do learners and<i> teachers/caregivers</i> mutually understand the specific
plans in the curriculum that affect them?  Do learners participate, as their
maturities permit, in making the plans?  Do they generally understand and agree
as to what is expected of them, and why?<br>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">Is there a clear relationship between the goals and learning activities?  Do
the learning opportunities seem to be the best possible activities for this
group of learners at this time to achieve the agreed-upon goals?  Are all
appropriate and feasible types of learning experiences used?<br>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">To what extent has the curriculum been tailor-made for the learners?  If an
external curriculum is being used has it been adapted to the setting and
characteristics of the learners?  Are the learning opportunities planned truly
relevant to the educational needs of the population and community?  Are
provisions made for the individual differences of learners?<br>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">Is the total curriculum plan comprehensive?  Does it define appropriate
teaching methodologies and evaluation as well as include goals and
activities?<br>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">Does the group planning the curriculum include all persons concerned,
including the learners, community members and professionals?<br>
 <IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">Does the curriculum plan allow for adequate provision for feedback from
learners and other concerned groups as well as the means for making
modifications as needed?<br>
<IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*"> Can the curriculum and each of its parts be explained clearly to learners and
others who are impacted by the programme?<br>
<IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*"> Is there a mechanism in place for identifying problems?  Is there a systematic
way of securing, monitoring and reporting action regarding suggestions for
change and innovation?<br>
<IMG SRC="blue.gif" ALT="*">Does the curriculum plan anticipate full use of the resources--within the
programme, community, local and regional government, and beyond--available to
the programme?<br>
</ul>
*Adapted from J.G. Saylor, W.M. Alexander &amp; A.J. Lewis. 1981. <b>Curriculum
Planning for Better Teaching and Learning.</b> New York: Holt, Rinehart and
Winston. (Pgs. 48-50)<p>
<p>
<p>
The<b><i> Where</i></b> (location and facilities required) of ECCD Programmes<p>
<p>
 	After determining what it is that will be delivered through the ECCD
Programme (i.e. the combination of health, nutrition, and stimulation for
children, or the kinds of information and experiences desired for parents, or
the activities to be undertaken with the community, etc.) Then the location of
the programme needs to be determined.  Will the programme for children be
offered to children in groups?  If so, where can the group meet?  It may be in
a purpose-built centre for children.  But this is a very expensive alternative.
ECCD programmes can be offered in existing centres or halls, including
community centres and religious centres.  They can be offered in the home of a
community member, in a corner of the market place, or any other place that
children can be gathered together safely, with access to water and sanitation
facilities.<p>
<p>
	Likewise programmes that work with parents and other caregivers can provide
services through a variety of mechanisms.  They can visit parents in their
homes, meet with women in a health centre, set up regular meetings in a
community hall, be affiliated with micro-enterprise projects, etc.  In other
words, these programmes need to be flexible and set up where it is convenient
for the beneficiaries, wherever that might be.<p>
<p>
The <b><i>When </i></b>(timing of programme activities) of ECCD Programmes<p>
<p>
	The when of ECCD programmes takes into consideration the timing of the
programme.  When will it be offered?  For how long?  Over what period of time?
For example, parent education programmes frequently meet over a period of
months, meeting once a week or once a months for 2-3 hours at a time.  The
scheduling of these time-blocks depends on the availability of parents,  the
intensity of the course being offered, the number of facilitators available to
work with the groups, the number of groups that a facilitator is able to lead,
the distance facilitators have to travel to meet with the group, etc.<p>
<p>
	The timing within home visiting programmes is dependent on the balance of a
number of dimensions.  Home visiting programmes may involve 1-2 hours per week
over a year&#146;s period of time.  Less intensive programmes may include home
visits only once a month, with more frequent visits being made for those
families who are in greater need.  The once-a-month visits may be extended over
a two-three year period of time.  The specific structure will be dependent on
the needs of the population being served, the objectives of the programme, the
number of families to be served, the number of families that an individual home
visitor is working with, the number of home visitors available to the programme
given the resources available, etc.<p>
<p>
	Programmes that involve young children directly can also be offered within a
variety of structures.  A common form is full-day child care programmes that
are offered from early in the morning until late in the afternoon/evening,
designed to accommodate the needs of working parents.  For the pre-school aged
child the most prevalent model is a half-day programme, offered five days a
week.  Or the child may attend a programme only two or three times a week.  The
focus of these programmes is generally on socialization and the development of
cognitive and learning skills.  <p>
<p>
The <b><i>How </i></b>(the organization of the services)<b><i> </i></b>of ECCD
Programmes<p>
<p>
	This speaks to the way in which organizations and institutions are organized
to deliver the service.  In some instances new organizations are created,
designed specifically to provide ECCD programmes.  This is a costly
alternative. An effective way to offer ECCD services is to build on what
already exists.  For example, if there is a health centre where women come
regularly to monitor the growth of their child, it is relatively easy to
provide mothers with parenting information during the visits.  This does not
require setting up a separate organization or institution or place to deliver
the service.  It requires working with current programme staff and providing
them with additional skills, knowledge and competencies to enhance what they
are able to provide when they work with parents.<p>
<p>
	In some countries where there is a decreasing population, one consequence is
that there are frequently empty rooms in the primary school, and teachers are
unemployed.  This might be an opportunity to introduce a pre-school programme,
housed in the primary school.  The teachers can be re-trained to work with
younger children.  This option takes advantages of under-utilized resources.
The danger in this situation, however, is that the pre-school can easily become
a scaled-down version of what happens in Primary 1, with inappropriate
activities and teaching methodologies being employed with the young children.<p>
<p>
	While building on existing efforts is a viable alternative, there is a danger
of over-loading the local worker.  An example comes from the Integrated Child
Development Service (ICDS) in India, where, over time, the responsibilities of
Anganwadi Worker, the local woman trained to deliver the services of the
programme, has been increased exponentially.  Every time a new component is
added to the programme the Anganwadi Worker receives additional training and
has to add a new service to the list of things she already does.  She meets
with pregnant women, she provides support in breast feeding, she monitors the
child&#146;s growth and development, she provides the nutritional programme for
the children, she operates the Anganwadi Centre attended by the children...and
she fills out forms and forms and more forms.  She also receives little pay.
Thus the danger of building on current efforts is the exploitation of the local
worker and the dilution of her work to the point where none of the services is
delivered well.<p>
<p>
	Thus there are clearly trade-offs in terms of the value of building on already
existing programmes.  These must be weighed against the costs of creating new
programme structures.<p>
<p>
The <b><i>Who </i></b>(the human resources required for the programme -
staffing) of ECCD Programmes<p>
<p>
	One of the most critical features of ECCD programmes is the people who are
expected to deliver the service--whether that be working directly with
children, working with parents and/or the community, working with the media, or
undertaking advocacy work with the general public and politicians.  Each of
these tasks requires a different set of skills.  Even more than that, they
require different kinds of personalities.  Thus in putting together the
programme, planners need to be clear on the knowledge, skills and the personal
characteristics that will be required to undertake a given set of activities
and seek individuals who fit the right &#145;profile&#146;.   For example, not
every woman is interested in nor has the ability to work with young children,
although that is a common assumption.  <p>
<p>
	In thinking about staffing of programmes there are several dimensions.  First
there is the set of skills and personal characteristics that people bring with
them in relation to the tasks to be undertaken. The profile will be determined
by the roles and responsibilities that individuals will be taking on in
relation to the beneficiaries.  Thus in seeking staff the specific skills,
knowledge and competencies that are desired should be spelled out.  Academic
credentials will give you some information about the person, but hiring should
not be done based on degrees alone.   For example, if one of the objectives of
the programme is to support the development of self-directed learning, then the
candidates one hires must be self-directed learners themselves.  If people are
expected to do advocacy work and work with policy-makers then they must be
people who have the ability to relate to policy-makers in a positive way.  If
awareness-raising is one of the programme objectives then people who have
skills as communicators should be among those hired.<p>
<p>
	 Second, there is a need to plan for the kinds of additional training that
people will require to undertake the task.  On-going staff training is an
important feature of any ECCD programme.  Staff need to be renewed; they need
to be provided with current information; they need to learn new techniques.
But the training should be tailored to the programme and done is a way that
reinforces programme objectives. For example, if staff are given lectures on
methodologies that can be used to foster interaction and group work with
children or adult learners, they will continue to lecture those they work with.
We teach the way we were taught.  So, if you want those working with children
and adults to use more participatory methods in their work, then they must be
trained through participatory methods.<p>
<p>
	Third, there is a need to think about the complementarity of skills, knowledge
and competencies among staff.  The emphasis in ECCD programming is on
participatory development.  The participatory model encourages team work and a
sharing of tasks. Thus one of the things that planners should strive toward, in
hiring staff, is the creation of a team that can work together to accomplish
programme objectives. <p>
<p>
	The team will include those who work with the beneficiaries -- children and/or
adults -- those that provide on-going supervision and support for the
direct-line workers, administrative staff, financial and accounting services,
and consultant services that are required periodically.<p>
<p>
The <b><i>How Much</i></b> (costs and financial resources required) of ECCD
Programmes<p>
<p>
	All of above have implications in terms of costs.  There is a cost to having a
facility within which to operate the programme, there is a cost for each and
every staff person, there are costs associated with the materials that are
needed for use in the programme and for use by those administering the
programme, there are maintenance costs (electricity, water, petrol).  All of
these have to be factored in when determining the costs of a programme.<p>
<p>
	Costs can be divided into two general categories: start-up costs and recurrent
costs.  As the name implies the start-up costs include all those things that
need to happen to get the programme going.  It may include the building or
refurbishing of facilities, the buying of equipment and initial supplies, the
purchase of a vehicle.  These are one-time costs, or at least they are costs
that are not incurred every year.<p>
	Recurrent costs are those costs that are on-going.  You always have to pay
them.  These include staff salaries and benefits, maintenance of the facilities
(heat, water, electricity, taxes), the replenishing of supplies.  In addition
an allocation should be made for on-going training if the programme is going to
continue to develop and not stagnate.  <p>
<p>
	The initial and on-going costs must then be matched with resources--those that
currently exist and those that need to be gathered.  In addition, the costs
should be examined in relation to the benefits that are expected from the
programme.  By taking the total cost of the programme and dividing it by the
number of intended beneficiaries it is possible to derive a cost/beneficiary
figure for the programme.  This calculation should be made in relation to
recurrent costs, since the initial costs of establishing programmes can be
high.  The inclusion of start-up costs in the calculation will produce a much
higher costs-per-child figure and not accurately reflect what is required to
sustain the programme over time.  <p>
<p>
	The actual costs per beneficiary will vary across and within countries based
on the population being served, the cost of living in the area, the type of
staffing required, and the actual services being provided. (For example, a
nutrition component can account for half the per-child costs in a programme.)
<p>
<HR>
