<title>CASE STUDY 2 - CHILD CARE AND WOMAN'S WORK IN RURAL NIGERIA</title></head>
<body>
<center><b><u>CASE STUDY 2</u></b><p>
CHILD CARE AND WOMAN&#146;S WORK<p>
IN RURAL NIGERIA<p>
<p>
Margaret Akinware<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<u>DOCUMENT NO. 4</u><p>
 <p>
(Thursday Morning, July 20)<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Prepared for:<br>
The Fourth Meeting of<br>
The Consultative Group on<br>
Early Childhood Care and Development<br>
Ottawa, Canada:  IDRC<br>
July 20-22, 1988<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
CHILD CARE AND WOMAN&#146;S WORK<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
FINDINGS IN RURAL SOUTHWESTERN NIGERIA AND<br>
IMPLICATIONS FOR UNICEF&#146;S PROGRAMME PLANNING<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
By<p>
<p>
M. A. Akinware<br>
<p>
<p>
UNICEF, NIGERIA<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Paper Presented at the Fourth meeting of the Consultative Group on Early
Childhood Care and Development at Ottawa, Canada	July 1988<p>
<p>
</center>
<p>
<p>
CHILD CARE AND WOMAN&#146;S WORK<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
FINDINGS IN RURAL SOUTHWESTERN NIGERIA AND<p>
IMPLICATIONS FOR UNICEF&#146;S PROGRAMME PLANNING<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
BY<p>
<p>
M. A. AKINWARE<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<center><img src=nigeria.gif alt="[map of Nigeria]"></center>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<u>CHILD CARE AND WOMAN&#146;S WORK</u><p>
 <p>
 <p>
 <p>
<u>FINDINGS IN RURAL SOUTHWESTERN NIGERIA AND</u><p>
<u>IMPLICATIONS FOR UNICEF&#146;S PROGRAMME PLANNING</u><p>
<u>SUMMARY</u><p>
 <p>
<p>
This paper highlights the pattern of childcare and women&#146;s work within the
Yoruba traditional rural settlements of Oyo and Owo Local Government Areas in
Southwestern Nigeria.  The division of labour and task allocation within the
Yoruba patrilinear system are highlighted.<p>
<p>
It is emphasized that the majority of woman face the task of incorporating the
requirements of work with high child care loads of 2 under 6 years old
siblings, on average.  In a situation of high fertility of 6-8 pregnancies per
woman, low socio-economic status and insufficient food intake in the presence
of a biting economic recession, these woman present with maternal depletion;
low nutritional and health status which readily saps their energy.<p>
<p>
The mothers&#146; income generating activities tent to dictate needs for child
care and the place where community based child care centres can evolve.<p>
<p>
Market based villages/neighborhood models and women cooperative models ate
being tried out on an experimental basis.  In addition, the feasibility of a
&#147;child to child&#148; care programme and a greater involvement of fathers
and grandmothers with young children are other alternatives to be considered.<p>
<p>
The Early Childhood Programme is implemented within the UNICEF assisted
programme which takes a comprehensive and multisectoral approach to primary
health care with additional sub-components of household food security,
nutrition and woman&#146;s training programmes during the present 5 year plan
period.<p>
<p>
The programme intends to strengthen and upgrade the present skills of
professional, para-professional as well as community members on early childcare
and development.  Health, Nutrition, Sanitation and Early Childhood stimulation
messages are being incorporated into the national Woman and Adult Education
Movement and as part of primary school curricula.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
CHILD CARE AND WOMAN&#146;S WORK<p>
<p>
<u>FINDINGS IN RURAL SOUTHWESTERN NIGERIA AND IMPLICATIONS FOR UNICEF&#146;S
PROGRAMME PLANNING</u><p>
<p>
<p>
Introduction:<p>
<p>
The social structure in Western Nigeria is primarily patrilinear with a strong
orientation for male authority and dominance.  Culturally, the Yoruba rural
society is based on a polygamous family system where husbands and wives, to
some extent are economically dependent.<p>
<p>
The woman-folk form a single productive unit with their husbands who are the
heads of the unit.  The predominant occupation is farming with a re-orientation
from subsistence to &#147;consumption&#148; economic patterns.  The husband
usually owns the land and labour-supply is lineage-based or hired.  Other
economic pursuits for women include trading, home crafts such as weaving,
dyeing, pottery, soap making, food processing and food vending.  In addition,
the woman are responsible for the following domestic chores:<p>
<p>
- the fetching of water from streams/ponds,<p>
- the fetching and chopping of firewood for food preparation and<p>
- the environments sanitation within their communities.<p>
<p>
Therefore, the combination of income generating activities with household
chores and child care arrangements has been culturally accepted as an integral
part of a woman&#146;s life in the rural setting.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<u>Role allocation within the Polygamous setting:</u><p>
 <p>
Given this setting, child care is a collective responsibility of the family and
the community members and &#147;there is less stress upon the individual
mothers role in the socialization of the child&#148; (Ellis 1978)<p>
<p>
The younger wives stay at home to take care of the family children, theirs and
those of other wives.  This living pattern also accords them the opportunity to
engage in food processing and petty trading.<p>
<p>
The tradition of male authority or dominance allocates to the man the
supreme-headship of the household.  His tasks are the provisions of
accommodation, food maintenance allowance and protection.  He is not
traditionally expected to assist the wife with household chores rather he is to
be served by the womenfolk and the children.  In a polygamous setting, each
wife and her children constitute an economic unit.  The mother is usually
responsible for her own and her children&#146;s clothing, medical/ceremonial
expenses, food as well as taking care of her own parents (Akintoye 1981).<p>
<p>
A study from Oyo LGA indicated that mothers had to provide most of their
children&#146;s foods, 50% of the family health care and that on the whole
women contribute 42% of all the household expenditures. (Adekanye 1987) (Table
1 presents the Division of Household Expenditure (monthly))<p>
<p>
<u>WOMAN&#146;S WORK: A review of Literature</u><p>
<p>
From the review on woman&#146;s work in the traditional Yoruba society, Awe
(1975) declared that Yoruba woman as a rule do not go through the ordeal of
tilling the ground.  Women are however assigned the following task:<p>
<p>
- caring yam tubers before the husband who plants each in the prepared yam
mounds.<p>
- harvesting, and processing of crops such as cassava, palm oil, etc.<p>
- preservation of the harvest crops from vermin, insects and natural
elements,<p>
- shelling of maize, beans and melon seeds.<p>
<p>
According to Makinwa-Adebusove (1985), the Yoruba woman regard work as part of
their roles as wives and mothers.  She posits that <p>
- women process food and non-food commodities such as soap, palm oil and cooked
food,<p>
- sell processed and non-processed farm commodities mainly produced from their
husbands farms.<p>
<p>
Favi (1977) in a study of Oyo villages discovered that women assist with
planting, harvesting, processing and transportation of farm products such as
yam, maize, cassava, etc.<p>
<p>
Osuntogun (1976) in a study of farmers&#146; wives in Oyo State declare that
trading constitutes the most important occupation of the farmers&#146; wives in
addition to harvesting, processing and marketing.<p>
<p>
<u>WOMAN&#146;S INCOME GENERATING ACTIVITIES:</u><p>
 <p>
The prevalent income generating activities in the rural communities include
cassava and palm oil processing in addition to farming.  Cassava processing for
gari, fufu and (lafun) cassava flower is a tedious, woman&#146;s income
generating venture.  The data from the Oyo LGA show that a total of 2,253
unconverted work hours needed for all stages of cassava development, may
contribute only 29%, women 46% and children 25%.  Women and children contribute
100% of the total labour for processing and 94% of that for marketing.  The
processing involves the peeling of cassava, the grating manually or with
machine, the fermentation and dehydration method of applying weight, the
sieving of the grated cassava, the frying cooling, preserving and marketing of
the finished product.<p>
<p>
A rapid assessment study of the rural cassava in household food security among
the Yorubas revealed that cassava is the major crop for household food
security.  Cassava is nearly always intercropped and provides the bulk of the
family&#146;s energy requirements during the lean ,months of the year (April -
June).  This is true in the rural areas and increasingly in the urban areas
where it is the survival food among the urban poor.<p>
<p>
The processing of palm oil involves the women standing in the processing pit to
separate the palm kernel from the oil which collects at the top.  The
processing entails rigorous boiling of the palm nuts in containers made of clay
or tin drums.  Fire making is tedious, using firewood and locally produced
tinders.  Processing is non-hygienic, laborious and time-consuming.  Women,
employing child-labour are often seen cracking the palm kernels before the
shells are sold to trading companies for soap making and also used locally for
processing blacksoap: a low cost, locally acceptable and available commodity in
the Yoruba communities.<p>
<p>
Women also perform 60 - 80 percent of all agricultural labour and 95 percent of
all domestic tasks.  They help with weeding the farm,<p>
- carry out most of the farm work during harvest period as well as<p>
- carry home the harvest products before processing and marketing
respectively.<p>
<p>
<u>The Problem:</u><p>
 <p>
Women&#146;s income generating and domestic chores are labour intense, energy
consuming and physically tasking.  The majority of women face the task of
incorporating a heavy work load with high childcare load of 2 under 6 year old
siblings, on average.  Given a situation of high fertility of 6-8 pregnancies
per women, low socio-economic status, insufficient food intake in the mist of a
biting economic recession and food taboos which effect mainly the women and
their children, the majority of mothers present with maternal depletion of low
nutritional and health status which readily sap their energy.<p>
The also suffer from physical exhaustion as a result of hard labour.
consequently these gender roles as primary care givers, wives, cook and
housekeepers are adversely affected.  Their children also present with poor
nutritional health status.  Childcare arrangement that becomes the
responsibility of the olds siblings, grandmothers where available, neighbors
and relations if still resident in rural communities.  The search for job
opportunities had taken a sizable proportion of family members into the urban
centres.  <p>
<p>
Besides, the rural areas have not witnessed the off shoots of daycare centres
as these are urban oriented and urban based.<p>
<p>
<u>Government&#146;s Policy on Early Childcare and Development</u><p>
 <p>
Where as some women groups such as the National Council of Women&#146;s
Societies and the Women in Development have been vocal and active at getting
the government to institutionalize early child care arrangements, their
activities have been focused mainly in the urban centres.<p>
<p>
The National Policy on Education: Guidelines on Pre-Primary Education (1987)
has enlisted certain objectives of preprimary education as:<p>
<ol>
<li>effecting a smooth transition from the home to school;
<li>preparing the child for the primary level of education:
<li>providing adequate care and supervision for the children while their parents are at work (on the farm, in the markets, offices, etc.);
<li>inculcating in the child the spirit of enquiry and creativity through the exploration of nature and the local environment, playing with harmless, educative materials and toys, artistic and musical activities.
<li>teaching cooperation and team spirits;
<li>teaching the rudiments of numbers, letters, colors, shapes, forms, etc. through play and
<li>teaching good habits, especially good health habits.</ol>

<p>
The Ministry of Education will effect the requirements for preprimary
institutions in multisectoral/ministerial approach with the ministries of
Health, Works, etc.  The Ministry of Education (1987) has also commended these
guidelines to both Nursery Schools and Day Care Centres for use as a reference
point.  National Child Welfare Policy for Nigeria (1987) has emphasized
Government&#146;s awareness that adequate attention tot he education and
intellectual development of the Nigerian Child is an invaluable insurance for
the future well being of the nation.  The government will therefore implement
faithfully the provisions of the National Policy on Education particularly on
the objectives of preprimary education whether the Child resides in the urban
or rural areas.<p>
<p>
It is worth mentioning however that the conventional institutional, urban based
approaches to Early Childhood Care and Development programme have failed to
provide adequate services for the escalating needs of preschool children.<p>
Given such a background at the rural area and in Nigeria as a whole, UNICEF
Nigeria in collaboration with the Bernard Van Leer Foundation has initiated an
informal community based Child Care and Development Programme in Oyo, Owo and
Oyun LGAs which are predominantly Yoruba speaking.<p>
<p>
From 1987 until 1989, Early Child Care and Development Programme will focus
it&#146;s activities within these three LGAs in the order to develop models
that will be adequate Yoruba children in the 0-6 year age group, under
different but comparable conditions.  The ECCD programme is implemented with
the UNICEF assisted Integrated Community Health and Development programme which
takes a multisectoral and holistic approach to primary health care with
additional sub-components such as household food security, nutrition and
women&#146;s training.  These activities involve various Ministries of Local
Government and Community Development, Health, Education, Agricultural and
Women&#146;s Organizations.<p>
<p>
The remanding two LGAs of Akko in Bauchi State, Calbar in Cross River State
will require more systematic planning since fairly little is known about the
traditional childcare patterns and modern needs for alternative arrangements in
comparison with the Yoruba speaking LGAs.<p>
<p>
<u>THE OBJECTIVES OF THE PROGRAMME</u><p>
<h3>

 <li>To demonstrate and apply low cost, community based approached to childhood care and education which respond to the needs of women and children in rural areas.       <br>
<li>To develop a system of training for young women in rural areas which will enable them to function as workers in community based early childhood centres.       <br>

<li>To reinforce the development of creativity and thinking in children at the informative age.       <br>

<li>To develop a system which based on early childhood centres could address the wider needs of women at community level in preparing them for motherhood, improving their child rearing skills and their understanding of their children&#146;s growth and development needs.       <br>

<li>To improve the process of transmission of social and cultural skills, enhancing the child&#146;s self-image and identity and        <br>

<li>To promote, through the growth of alternative early childhood services employment opportunities for young women, halting the drift to the city.       <br>
</h3>
	
<p>
<u>The Target Audience of the Base Studies for Programme Development</u><p>
 <p>
Oyo Local Government Area is located in the northern part of Oyo State and
shares a common boundary with Kwara State.  It&#146;s headquarters:  Oyo town
with a population of under 200,000 people, is a traditional town and the
capital of the old Yoruba kingdom.<p>
<p>
Oyo LGA consist of a conglomeration of three urban centres Oyo, Awe, Ilora and
hundreds of small villages and temporary farm camps and their farmsteads.  It
has an estimated population of 544,047 people in 1986 and is one of 24 local
government areas of Oyo State.<p>
<p>
Owo Local Government Area is a merger of three, previously autonomous district
councils with it&#146;s headquarters at Owo town.  Owo LGA consist of 6 towns,
their farmsteads, camps and hamlets with an estimated population of 353,000
people.  It is located in the north-east of Ondo State and shares common
boundaries with Bendel and Kwara states.  Owo town is the largest with a
population of about 150,000 people.<p>
<p>
Some 40 percent of the population in Oyo and Owo LGAs reside at Oyo and Owo
towns respectively.  The population of the children under 6 amounts to 18
percent and 20 percent of Oyo and Owo LGAs respectively.<p>
<p>
Oyun LGA though the smallest LGA within Kwara State, has the highest population
density with more then 300 people per square kilometer of an estimated
population of 234,000.  About 70 percent of it&#146;s population lives in Offa,
the headquarters of the LGA.  Oyun LGA though close to Oyo, is within the dry
savannah region with fewer cash crops than the richer forest zones.<p>
<p>
<p>
<u>Terms of Reference for the Baseline Study:</u><p>
 
<h3>
	<li>To estimate the extend to which motherhood responsibility has been effected by mothers other activities.       
<li>To ascertain how children adapt to and develop in their mothers&#146; existing economic activities as regards:       
</h3>

       
- health status and socialization pattern<p>
- nutritional practices, taboos and status of rural and urban women and
children<p>
- play facilities as related to motor stimulation and transfer of linguistic
skills.<p>

<h3>
	<li>To find out what childcare arrangement obtained in the communities and thus encourage the settlers to improve along the line.       

       </h3>
<p>
<u>Development of Research Instruments</u><p>
 <p>
For the purpose of data collection, a three part questionnaire focused on care
and development was constructed.  It comprises of -<p>

<h3>
	<li>The Household Questionnaire which solicits the information on household record and series of items on infrastructural facilities in the community.       
<li>Mother Questionnaire which combined both the child birth and the child fostering record.       



       </h3>
	The Child Development Questionnaire which focused on the child&#146;s health
and nutritional, current health and nutritional status and the socialization
practices.<p>
<p>
The 98 item questionnaire also solicited information on material assessment
strategies and childcare arrangements among working mothers.<p>
<p>
To standardize the questionnaire, a pre-test was conducted on a rural
population in Oyo State.  The same questionnaire was used in the local
government areas of Oyo and Owo through slight modifications and corrections
were made before the second survey.<p>
<p>
It is necessary to mention here that the survey on childcare and development
for Oyun LGA is currently in progress.<p>
<p>
<u>The Conduct of the Baseline Survey/Observational Assessment:</u><p>
 <p>
Two surveys have been completed in two LGA&#146;s of Oyo and Owo.  In each LGA,
thirteen interviewers were selected from their performance on a related
aptitude test and interviews.  One hundred mothers were interviewed in Oyo and
Owo town respectively while 150 and 175 were selected from the rural areas of
Oyo and Owo LGAs respectively.  Selection of hamlets, small villages and
rural/urban settlements were based on size category.  For the observational
assessment, Time Series Analysis was adopted for each child between two and six
years.  This was conducted on a 10 percent of the sample interviewed.  Every
child was observed for an hour at different periods of the day.  Pictorial
documents were also obtained.  The collected data was computerized.  The
socio-economic and educational data were analyzed using simple tabulations and
percentages.  Attempts are being made to correlate Oyo and Owo data.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Table I					Division of Household Expenditure (monthly)<p>


<pre>
          Items              Average      Part paid     Part paid     Part paid     Percent by    Percent by    Percent by   
                           total costs     by men #     by women #   by others #      men %        women %       others %    
