<p>
* To estimate the average costs of accommodations it was assumed that living in
own houses (126 families) had half of the average rent as cost for
maintenance.<p>
** Based on yearly expenses.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<u>Statistical Findings and Implications for UNICEF&#146;s Interventions:</u><p>
 <p>
<u>The socio-economic Characteristics of Mother</u><p>
 <p>
<p>
Generally, there are more monogamous marriage in Owo rural communities than at
Oyo: approximately 66 percent to 53 percent of the sample.  Twenty-two females
in Owo completed the Primary School education as against only 9 percent on Oyo
rural communities.  Over one-third females in Owo (39%) are literate, about 18
percent are literate in Yoruba and English, 12 percent in Yoruba (only) at Oyo
rural communities.  However, 86 percent and 57 percent females at Oyo and Owo
rural communities have had no formal education.  Access to primary education is
the same for boys and girls in LGAs.<p>
<p>
Adekanye (1987) reported a high school drop out rate for both boys and girls of
20 to 30 percent especially after primary four.  This is due particularly
academic inaptitude and to some extent parental financial constraints at
keeping all children in school during the present economic recession.<p>
<p>
<p>
<u>Religion:</u><p>
 <p>
The predominant religion among the household in Oyo rural communities is Islam
while the rural population in Owo is almost 100 percent Christian.  The
implication of religion is that polygamy tends to be more prevalent among the
Moslems than the Christian orthodox denominations.  Greater parental
involvement has been attributed to monogamous family than the polygamy setting
where each mother is expected to shoulder certain responsibilities of her
children.  The mean age at marriage in Owo rural communities is about 20.4
which is probably high than for Oyo which is predominately Moslem and with
lower lever of education.<p>
<p>
The general trend is that early marriage, low level of education and high child
mortality are correlated factors in child survival and development.<p>
<p>
<u>Economic Activities:</u><p>
 <p>
Over 60 percent of adult female in Oyo indicate that they process and trade in
various farm product particularly in palm oil and cassava.  Over 21 percent
report that their primary economic activity is farming.  However, most of them
also trade and process farm products on a secondary basis.  The pattern is
different at Owo rural communities.  Twenty-six percent of females are farmers,
43 percent engage in farming and trading activities while 13 percent describe
themselves as traders.  Two women regard themselves as housewives.<p>
<p>
Owo is one of the few Nigerian areas still covered with dense tropical rain
forest and about half of the LGA is kept as forest reserve.  Therefore, most of
male adults are hunters.  Owo is heterogeneous because of the long settled
groups of immigrates from the neighboring ethnic groups.  On the other hand,
Oyo is midway between the woody and the grass savannah zones in a homogeneous
race.  Farming is more important to women in Owo than Oyo:<p>

<h3>
	<li>because Owo women readily have access to farm lands through their families of origin under customary law.       
<li>farming in Owo is more profitable due to it being a dense rain forest area.  It has several cash crops such as cocoa, rubber, colanuts in addition to the main staple food crops.       
<li>the services of farm labourers are more readily available in Owo than in Oyo due to influx of other ethnic groups.  This often leads women to return to their families of origin after their child bearing years.  Food processing and storage are almost exclusively in the hands of women in Oyo and Owo.       

       </h3>
<p>
<u>Household Size and Child Dependency:</u><p>
 <p>
The average household size in Oyo rural settlements is 8.5 persons and 7.7
persons in Owo.  These figures are considerably higher than the recent estimate
for rural populations in Southwestern Nigeria of a mean household size of 4.66
(Willson Oyelaran and Ladipo 1987).  The majority of households are male
headed.<p>
<p>
In Oyo about 9 percent of under 5 and 12 percent of 5 to 14 ear old children
are in traditional fostering, being raised in households where their primary
caretaker in not a biological parent.  In more than 46 percent of the cases,
the primary caretaker is the grandmother while in approximately 22 percent of
the cases, older sisters assume parental responsibilities.<p>
<p>
In Owo, 15 percent of the women surveyed are involved in traditional fostering
situations.  Slightly more than 13 percent of the fostered children are below
preschool age.<p>
<p>
The figures in Table 2 shoe evidence of high fertility and mortality.  Oyelaran
and Ladipo (1997) reported a great deal of under reporting thus indicating the
tendency for these figures to be higher.<p>
<p>
Table 2 presents <u>Mean number of children under 5 born, Alive and Dead</u><p>


<pre>
                                        Oyo Rural           Owo Rural           
Mean number of children born Alive      4.69                4.61                
Mean number of children Living          4.05                4.27                
Mean number of children Dead            0.63                0.34                
Percentage of children Dead             29 %                8%                  
Child Mortality                         129/1000            40/1000             

</pre>
<p>
These figures are confirmed by Adekanye&#146;s (1987) findings showing that
fertility is higher in rural areas.  The desire for large families is also
expressed by approximately 76 percent of the women responding in the
affirmative when asked if they want more children.  Significantly, this is
spelled out 13 percent of the surveyed children were twins amounting to 54 sets
of twins.  Spelled out 59 sets of twin pregnancies were also reported by the
surveyed women.<p>
<p>
The high incident of twining among the Yoruba women is common knowledge and has
been well documented by researchers.  There is no correlation between twining
and morbidity/mortality.  This could have resulted from inaccurate/under
reporting of morbidity/mortality correlates by the respondents.  There is a
relatively high incident of neonatal and child aged 1-5 year deaths in Owo
while the most at risk period is that of infancy as well as the 1-5 age
category in Oyo.  The age categories of reported child deaths are presented in
Table 3 below:<p>
<p>
<u>Table 3:  Age of Reported Child Deaths:</u><p>
 

<pre>
                                                          Oyo                      Owo        
                                               No         %             No         %          
