</pre>
<p>
<p>
The cause of child deaths are presented in Table 4.  While fever is reported as
the most common cause of death in Oyo, the &#147;illness&#148; category is
prevalent at Owo.<p>
<p>
The implication of these findings is that child survival components ORT, EPI,
Growth Monitoring and Nutrition be intensified during the high risk age period.
Incidentally, no respondent from Oyo and Owo attributed any child&#146;s death
to diarrhea.  Diarrhoeal diseases are often regarded as necessary and
inevitable as an &#147;internal cleansing mechanism&#148;.  The importance of
diarrhoeal knowledge is therefore critical to child survival in the rural
areas.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<u>Table 4:   Causes of Child Deaths:</u><p>
 <p>


<pre>
                                                          Oyo                      Owo        
                                               No         %             No         %          
 Convulsions                                    7          22.6           9        14.75      
Fever                                          8          25.8           6          9.84      
Measles/Smallpox                               4          12.9           9         14.75      
Malaria                                        3           9.7           2          3.28      
Illness                                        1           3.2          24         39.38      
Cough                                          1           3.2           2          3.28      
Other                                          3           9.7           2          3.28      
Abiku                                          1           3.2           -             -      
Unknown                                        3          9.7            7         11.47      
  Total                                  =     31         100           61         99.99      

</pre>
<p>
<p>
<u>The Nutritional Status of Children:</u><p>
 <p>
In the baseline study at Oyo rural settlements (1987), age discrepancies were
found during data collection, therefore the survey relied on age independent
parameters of nutritional status using age only in a cautious way to explore
the possibility of trends.<p>
<p>
Using the Height for Weight as percent of standard, the children of Olorunda in
Oyo rural community, of mean age 2 years had moderate PEM and severe PEM for
children of mean age 4.  On the whole anthopometric measurements, the children
of Olorunda 0-18 months did not meet the standard, a reflection of inadequate
breast feeding from malnourished mothers, as well as poor weaning diets.<p>
<p>
The weight for Height revealed a severe PEM for 4 year olds in Oloruda probably
due to inadequate food intake.  using Weight for Height percentiles, 41 percent
of the children in the survey fell at or above 100 percentile, 37 percent fell
below 95 percentile whilst 19 percent were below 90 percentile.  Only 2 percent
was below 80 percentile *.<p>
<p>
Generally, the nutritional status of children is considered unsatisfactory in
terms of micro-nutrients and possibly protein intakes.  In the survey, it was
shown that the shortest group of children are ass of satisfactory weight whilst
in the tallest category using Weight for Height, scores show the oldest group
of children to be the least well nourished, quite possible the children
reported to be the oldest are not the tallest.  These findings suggest that
many of the children are maintaining adequate Weight for Height ratios at the
expense of height and that in an on-going programme, it would be worthwhile to
register births so that height for age and long term nutritional status could
be evaluated.<p>
<p>
Recent rapid nutritional assessments conducted by the Nutritional Unit FMOH
revealed that 30 percent of children in Oyo LGA are malnourished between the
ages of 12-36 months while and average of 30 percent of children in the sample
are regarded as malnourished considering all the parameters (Height for Weight,
Weight for Age and Height for Age).  using the Height for Weight as percent of
standard:  about 4q percent in the sample were normal, almost 30 percent had
mild PEM, about 10 percent had moderate PEM (acute) while 2 of the children
suffered from severe PEM.  Weaning food is often low in energy density because
it consist mainly is watery corn porridge.  Even where mothers sell fruits such
as oranges, children so not readily get them.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<p>
<p>
* (Reference values for Weight and Length/Heights Table 31 in Cameron and
Hofvander, <u>Manual on Feeding Infants and Young Children</u>, Oxford 1983)<p>
<p>
<p>
A similar survey conducted at Owo showed that 30 percent of children age 0-5
are moderately to severely malnourished according to Weight for Age and 25
percent moderately to severely stunted by Height for Age standards.
Malnutrition tends to be more common among girls than boys and increases with
age, especially in the 4-5 age group where moderately/severely malnutrition is
twice as common among girls as compared to boys (40% against 20%) respectively.
Two-thirds of all infants 0-1 year are relatively well-nourished due to the
wide spread and prolonged breast feeding practices.  Malnutrition among this
age group is mainly due to a late introduction of solid food after the first
4-6 months of exclusive breast feeding.  According to the survey, 15 percent of
all mothers did not introduce additional weaning until the child was over 12
months old and believe that &#147;children should not be fed on any other food
besides breast milk and pap until the children are two tears old&#148;.
(Balogun 1987)<p>
<p>
From the UNICEF/IITA/UI (1986) field survey it was discovered that the 0-5 year
old children at Olorunda do not consume an appreciable amount of red palm oil,
protein, carbohydrates and vitamins. Researches have shown that palm oil does
not only increase the food density for young children but also adds the much
needed minerals to the diet in it&#146;s freshest state.  The baseline survey
in Oyo also revealed that most of the children in the low weight group eat with
siblings while more of the high weight eat with adults.  More of the children
in the low weight category have mothers who do not think that milk or legumes
are particularly good for children.  There is the indication that the higher
the number of undesirable foods, the more likely the child is to be in the
lower weight group.<p>
<p>
<u>The Health Status:</u><p>
 <p>
The health status of the children at Olorunda showed the correlation between
the nutritional and health indices.  General physical examination conducted
during the UNICEF/IITA/UI survey (1986) revealed that 51 percent had angular
stomatitis, 37 percent had splenomegaly while a large portion of the children
at Olorunda presented with umbilical hernie.<p>
<p>
From the blood films, packed cell volume (PCV) and stool specimens examined,
about 27 percent of the surveyed villagers including children were anaemic with
PCV less than 40 percent, 81 percent had ascaris infection with a high
proportion of people infected with hookworm.  These findings were confirmed by
the clinical examinations which were conducted at the inception of the Child
Care project in August, 1987.<p>
<p>
The most prevalent health problems are fever, anemia, nasal discharge and
inflammation with lymphadenitis.  Umbilical hernia, hepatomegaly, wounds and
boils were also detected.  Other rampant health problems such as excess wax in
the ears causing hearing impediment, scabies, poor dental hygiene and
unawareness on the part of the parent.<p>
<p>
The baseline survey revealed that fever, chicken pox and diarrhoea were
reported as prevalent among the pre-school children in Oyo.  Both surveys
(1986, 1987) in Oyo have shown the immunological status of children to be low
at 20 percent (1986) and less than 28 percent in 1987.<p>
<p>
In Owo, the most prevalent, identified health problems include fever, diarrhoea
and measles/  The immunological status of children is good with 87 percent
haven completed triple antigen.<p>
<p>
<u>Ethnicity and Child rearing patterns:</u><p>
 <p>
The population is Oyo is predominately (95 percent) Yoruba.  Ojomo (1987)
reported that Edo-like language with increasing pigeon English repertoire to
the South of Owo reflects a gradual transition to Bendel State.  The
implication is that this section of Owo population tends to eat a substantial
amount of red palm oil, yam and vegetables just like Bendelites with whom they
have contact.<p>
<p>
Unlike the parents in rural settlements of Oyo who rely mainly on their
children for farm works, parents in Owo LGA hire labour from outside the state
to work on their farmsteads.<p>
<p>
<u>Mother&#146;s Perception on the Development of a Child&#146;s Skills:</u><p>
 <p>
<u>Table 5 presents the age expectation for Task Achievement:</u><p>


<pre>
Task                                     Mean in Years Oyo Rural             Owo Rural          
Stop bedwetting                                    2.85                        2.63             
Know where to defecate                             2.85                        2.55             
Talk clearly                                       3.36                        3.31             
Dress without assistance                           4.70                        4.73             
Heed himself                                       3.16                        2.49             
Care for himself alone for 2 hours                 5.17                        5.86             
Run errands                                        4.44                        4.35             
Care for younger siblings                          6.31                        6.73             
Greet elders properly                              5.58                        4.96             
Obey elders at all times                           5.73                        5.33             
Think for himself                                  7.08                        7.21             
Assist with trading                                6.62                        7.73             
Assist with farming                                6.78                        7.51             
Assist with housework                              6.09                        5.92             

</pre>
<p>
<p>
Generally speaking there is a slight later age where children are expected to
do certain task in Owo.  Physical control of children is expected earlier in
Owo than in Oyo: a more westernized concept which in indicative of maternal
level of education.  Self reliance and responsibility are heaped at an early
age on children in Oyo rural settlements.  Children in Oyo are judged by their
ability to run errands at an early age.  Foe example, children are given money
to buy food for themselves at Oyo whereas Owo women tend to prepare food and
are more protective towards the children.<p>
<p>
Relatively early autonomy and competence are expected of the Oyo rural children
with respect especially to assistance with trading, farming as well as care for
themselves alone for 2 hours indicative of activities which help to enhance
income generating activities of mothers.  More emphasis is placed on Owo on the
acquisition of skills to have control of certain bodily functions and good
manners (etiquette) for example, feeding and dressing self.  These are
important for programme planning in each LGA.<p>
<p>
<u>Stimulation and Development:</u><p>
 <p>
Whereas pre-reading exposure to books and other materials is unavailable to
most preschool children in Oyo rural settlements, over half the population in
Owo have access quite often to these materials.  Despite the absence of books
and toys in Oyelaran and Ladipo (1987) declared that this environment can
hardly be viewed as intellectually impoverished.  For them, the everyday
experiences of the preschool child provide many opportunities for the
development of psycho-motor, perceptual and linguistic skills.  Perceptual
motor skills particularly of eye-hand coordination, apprehensions and a sense
of balance are reflected in many of the preschoolers actions such as palm
kernel cracking/shelling and cassava peeling and grating.<p>
<p>
Of particular concern from the point of view of the development of pre-literacy
skills the relatively high percentage of children who are not being exposed to
stories and riddles.  These oral literature experiences which were quite common
in the past provide a powerful source of linguistic stimulation.  The riddles
in particular challenge both the child&#146;s imagination and his reasoning
process.  While these activities appear to be dying out, there is no evidence
that they have been replaced by their counterpart in literate societies, the
bed time story (Wilson Oyearan 1987).<p>
<p>
Less than one-third of the mothers play or sing with their preschoolers with
any regularity.  In Owo mothers believe that play is important for keeping the
child busy and for development of body as mind.  They also indicate that play
teaches social skills and body control.<p>
<p>
Motoric development is influenced in the rural catchments of both LGAs by the
spatial and architectural designs of the camps, the attitude of adults to
children&#146;s mastery of the spacious environment, children&#146;s imitation
of the older siblings and the innate capacity to walk early in this part of the
world.  Besides mothers&#146; aspirations for these children are high and are
independent of maternal level of education, occupation, residence, child&#146;s
ranking order, sex and the number of children in the family.  Approximately 77
percent and 70 percent in Oyo and Owo respectively wan their children to be
doctors, lawyers, engineers and nurses.  The expectation of rural women is that
their children should eventually move out of the rural areas.<p>
<p>
Mothers stress intellectual skills so that their children could be economically
viable, build houses, provide financial and moral support for them during old
age periods.  Parents further expressed the desire for their children to live
abroad, or wherever God directs them.  In Owo, parents are so anxious that some
children are sent to school as early as two tears of age.  Programmes should
take into consideration these parental expectations and goals.<p>
<p>
<p>
<u>Child Care Load and the Demands of Work:</u><p>
 <p>
The majority of women:  47 and 51 percent carte for at least two children
between the ages of 1 day and 6 years in rural Owo and Oyo respectively.  In
Owo, 20 percent are responsible for these young children as against 10 percent
in Oyo.  The majority of Oyo rural women: (53 percent) however look after one
preschooler as compared with approximately 31 percent in Owo.  While about 31
percent indicated that they are fostering children (not their natural
off-springs), small but relevant number of children (2 percent) under 5 years
are cared for by other relatives.  The fostering responsibility seems to be
reciprocal, at time.<p>
<p>
On average the child care load is 1.66 and 2 preschool children at Oyo and Owo
respectively.  When asked how many hours they spend away from home during the
day, the mean number of hours for all care takers is 4.7 and 5 hours at Oyo and
Owo respectively.<p>
<p>
While the majority of farmers (39 percent) are away for three to five hours, a
sizable percentage (24 percent) are away for more than eight hours a day in
Oyo.  Over a third of the sample was absent for more than 6 hours in Owo rural
areas.<p>
<p>
<u>Child Care Arrangements:</u><p>
 <p>
The Owo data revealed a weak correlation between the mothers&#146; occupation
and the methods of child care arrangement.  Children are more likely to
accompany the mother if she is a farmer or farmer/trader.  Although the
assistance of grandmothers is common irrespective of occupation, fathers are
more likely to assist with child care is the mother is a trader.  On the whole,
less than 10 percent of the fathers assume child care responsibilities on a
regular basis and over three-quarters of these men reside in the rural
settlements.  Settlements and place of residence are therefore significantly
associated with the pattern of child care.<p>
<p>
<p>
The majority of children accompany mothers who work (43 percent), about 25
percent remain with grandmothers, while nearly 8 percent remain with older
siblings in Owo.  The picture is slightly different at Oyo.<p>
The most common child care arrangement is that children remain at home with
grandmothers (24 percent).  Other common arrangements involve the child
accompanying the mother to work, (18 percent) or remaining with a sibling (16
percent).<p>
<p>
<u>Table 6 presents Child Care Arrangements:</u><p>
 

<pre>
                                                Oyo Rural                   Owo Rural           
Accompanies me                                     18.2                       43.35             
=                                                                                               
With husband                                       13.1                        9.25             
=                                                                                               
Grandmother                                        24.1                       24.86             
=                                                                                               
Older sibling                                      16.1                        7.51             
=                                                                                               
Other relative                                      5.1                        1.73             
=                                                                                               
Neighbour                                          13.9                        8.67             
=                                                                                               
Alone                                               5.1                        2.31             
=                                                                                               
Others                                              4.4                        0.58             
=                                                                                               
No Response                                         - -                        1.73             
                         Total       =             100                         100              

</pre>
<p>
<p>
The overwhelming majority of women, 96 percent, were satisfied with the child
care arrangements employed at the time of field work.<p>
<p>
<u>Child Care Options:</u><p>
 <p>
When confronted with child care options, each mother taking care of her own
child was the overwhelming choice (73 percent and 67 percent) in Oyo and Owo
respectively.  At Owo, about 23 percent opted for a group care arrangement
under the supervision of a trained care giver while the preference is for a
cooperative daycare arrangement at Oyo.  In Owo, 17 percent indicated their
willingness to pay cash for such services while only 7 percent at Oyo would pay
in cash or kind.<p>
<p>
The majority of women in Oyo (54 percent) and 30 percent in Owo would be
willing to reciprocate child care arraignments.<p>
<p>
In both studies, child care arrangements are regarded as everybody&#146;s
responsibility and not something for which they should pay.  This is because
mothers perceive child care arrangement as a child minding rather than as a
stimulating activity.  This cultural idea has implications for program
sustainability in both areas.  Some mothers in urban economy are however
prepared to pay a high premium on getting their children the right
stimulation.<p>
<p>
The following models of self help, community based child care arrangements have
been decided in collaboration with the mothers at Oyo LGA -<p>

<h3>
	<li>Rural community-based using existing centre and organized by women&#146;s cooperative society.  Olorunda, a homogenous village north of Oyo town has been chosen for model building.       
<li>Rural market based periodic group using a given space.  this will operate only on the 5 day market system.  Omooba/Olanite of Oyo LGA is to be established as a model.       
<li>Urban market based full-time group using Akesan market in Oyo town       

	
       </h3>
<p>
The rational for the choice of the market based models is to reach the high
risk groups from hamlets, villages and urban poor areas who would not have
otherwise benefited from this programme.<p>
<p>
The following model would be built later in Owo LGA:<p>

<h3>
	<li>Establishment of a preschool annex at Owo to cater for the needs of preschoolers who attend schools with other siblings.       
<li>Development of child care arrangements at the church premise using the church as the focal entry point since Owo LDA is predominately Christian.       
<li>A market based model will also be considered.       



       </h3>
<p>
An educational component for all age categories would be developed as
follows:<p>


<pre>
Age Category                             Programme                                
0-2 years                                Emphasis on child care, nutrition and    
                                         stimulation                              
2 1/2 - 4 years                          Child development, stimulation and       
                                         nutrition                                
4 1/2 - 6 years                          Preschool education and child            
                                         development                              

</pre>
<p>
In all these categories, there would be opportunities for cognitive and
psycho-social stimulation using play in all its ramifications.  Based on
UNICEF&#146;s programme approaches, the following activities would be integral
to the child care project.<p>
<p>
1. <u>Delivering a service</u>:	The project is seeking to meet the identified
needs of children at the project sites.  Health/Nutrition components have been
built into the programme to improve and promote the health/nutritional status
of the children in Olorunda.  Nutrition surveillance is an integral part of the
project.  As part of the nutrition strategies, food production among the
poorest farmers, particularly the women will be increased to cope with the
family protein-energy needs.  For these reasons, improved varieties of cassava
and soybeans have been introduced to rural primary schools, groups of communal
farmers at Owo LGA in 1986 and Oyo in 1987.  Fast growing and high yielding oil
palm seedlings would be introduces at Oyo and Owo to combat the high incident
of energy malnutrition.<p>
<p>
2. <u>Educating Adults:</u>	Adult literacy classes have commenced at Olorunda
since May 1988 by the Directorate for Social Mobilization.  Women in particular
are to be empowered to participate along side their husbands who have imbibed
the value of literacy.<p>
<p>
Training courses have been organized and schedules for community members, LGA
staff, school masters, women leaders etc. on multiplication of root crops and
soybeans as well as on cultivation, processing and utilization.  This is a
collaborative programme between UNICEF, IITA and the LGA Agricultural/Extension
staff.  Adult male and female and in general, all care-givers including older
siblings are to be instructed on breast feeding technique, family planning,
ORP, EPI, personal and communal hygiene, child care and development with
emphasis on the use of low cost toys, traditional stories, games, songs in
their lingua franca to stimulate the child&#146;s psycho-social and cognitive
development.  Women are being taught to monitor child and maternal growth and
nutrition.  A curriculum will be developed to train women/parents, older
siblings as care givers in the various child care models.  There would be
emphasis on cultural transmission through the process of socialization.<p>
<p>
In addition, The Can Leer Nigerian Educational Trust in collaboration with
UNICEF will develop &#147;First Readers&#148;, designed to convey health care,
nutritional, social and developmental messages to educate and improve the
quality of lives of rural women.<p>
<p>
<u>3. Promoting Community Development:</u><p>
 <p>
UNICEF in collaboration with consultants in appropriate technologies from ITDG,
England, RAIDS and FIIRO would pursue a project of upgrading household
technologies for women in food storage, processing and preparation for their
families.  There would be additional input on water-storage with filtering,
improved cooking stoves for firewood and less labour intensive methods on the
preparation of cash crops such as palm oil, melon and fried cassava (gari) for
local markets.  A low cost food processing centre has been constructed at
Olorunda in February through the efforts of COWAD members, the community, RAIDS
and UNICEF with a fund from the Dutch Government.  The centre was declared open
in February by the wife of the Oyo State Governor.<p>
<p>
The technical skills of the women groups have been upgraded to operate the
mechanized processing centre and cope with the child care project.  The skills
of local artisans would also be upgraded to produce appropriate toys and
educational equipment for use within the child care models and to make low cost
toys readily available.<p>
<p>
4. <u>Strengthen National Resources and Capacities:</u><p>
 <p>
UNICEF would implement the child care in collaboration with
National/State/Local women&#146;s organizations, OMEP, Nigerian Educational
Research Council (NERC), various related Ministries, specialist in early
childhood education etc. to effect policy making and evaluation strategies.
The capability of COWAD would be strengthened through training and supervision
by qualified early childhood teachers who have been identified at Oyo LGA.
OMEP Nigeria would be encouraged to carry its preschool activities to the rural
communities.  Steering Committees would be established at National/State/LGA
levels.  These would be inter-organizational and interministeria.<p>
<p>
5. <u>Social Marketing and Advocacy:</u><p>
 <p>
Community mobilization and training strategies will be integral tot he
programme to create awareness and disseminate knowledge on early childhood
education at all levels.  Education materials would be produced by UNICEF to
strengthen the primary school system and teaching force into effective
participation in child survival and development activities.<p>
<p>
The following programme activities are also complementary to the child care and
development project -<p>
<p>
1. An assessment of women&#146;s development needs has just been completed at
Oyo and Owo LGAs.  Women Development Programme would be institutes at ICHDs
unit later this year.<p>
<p>
2. The training of TBAs (Traditional Birth Attendants), the baseline surveys on
API, malaria, diarrhoea, knowledge of ORT and Nutrition are ongoing
processes.<p>
<p>
3. In order to prepare for adequate nutritional interventions for children
under two years of age most at risk, UNICEF intends to sponsor an in-depth
study into the positive deviance in child feeding patterns and their
development among Yoruba.  This will be carried out by the Tufts University in
collaboration with the University of Lagos.<p>
<p>
4. <u>Water and Sanitation Project</u> - UNICEF implements a low cost
generation of drinking water supply and sanitation in the deprived rural
communities.  Thus, water and sanitation are used as focal entry to mobilize
communities particularly women so they could meet the minimum requirements and
needs of child survival and development.  Availability of water also acts as a
time/energy saving device for women and their children who otherwise spend long
hours fetching water.  These facilities have been provided at Olorunda.<p>
<p>
<p>
<u>The Role of OAU on the African child.</u><p>
 <p>
At the OAU summit in July 1987, the year 1988 has been declared for the
Protection, Survival and Development of the African child using immunization
programme as a vehicle for achieving other wider goals.  This was brought about
because of the  deteriorating condition of children under the Structure
Adjustment Programme in Africa generally.  Child development is stressed by OAU
as a human right for the African child.<p>
<p>
The challenges of early childhood education programme is to reach the children
who are most at risk.  This is the problem to which the ECCD programme will be
addressed.<p>
<p>
<p>
