<html><head></head><title>ENHANCING EARLY CHILD DEVELOPMENT</title><body><p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<center><b>ENHANCING EARLY CHILD DEVELOPMENT:</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>ALTERNATIVE PROGRAMME STRATEGIES</b><p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
A briefing note presented to the<br>
Workshop on Early Child Development<p>
<p>
UNICEF, Cairo<p>
October 9, 1990<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Cassie Landers<p>
Consultative Group on Early Childhood Care and Development<p>
UNICEF, New York</center><p>
<p>
<p>
<b>I.	Introduction</b><p>
<p>
It is a privilege and a challenge to be here this morning and I thank UNICEF,
Cairo for this invitation. As so often with UNICEF invitations, I hope I am
able to fulfill their expectations. It is particularly exciting, as this is my
first visit to Egypt and to this part of the world. <p>
<p>
In my brief presentation this morning, I hope to accomplish the following
objectives:<p>
<p>
a. Provide a rationale for supporting child development programmes.<p>
<p>
b. Review some of our experiences from around the world which have generated a
range of programme strategies. In particular, I will try to highlight parental
education, as an important strategy.<p>
<p>
c. Present a framework for early child development proposed for Egypt.<p>
<p>
d. Describe in more detail a proposed community-based parent education project.
<p>
It is this particular project that will be the topic of discussion for our
working group. <p>
<p>
<b></b><p>
<b>A.	Early Child Development: A Definition</b><p>
<p>
Although there is a tremendous knowledge base about how children develop, it is
not always made available to practitioners who care for children or to
policy-makers who make decisions about programmes for children. In fact, there
seems to be a growing confusion about the terms survival, growth, development,
and care. These terms mean different things to different people and are often
used interchangeably. In our discussion today, I will try to provide an
intentionally simple working definition.<p>
<p>
Child development is not the same as growth. While growth is described by
changes in size, development is characterized by changes in complexity and
function. Child development encompasses the unfolding of behaviors from
immature to mature; from patterns of behavior that are simple to those that are
complex; and the evolution of a human being from dependency to autonomous
adulthood. More simply, child development is a process of change in which the
child learns to handle more complex levels of moving, thinking, feeling, and
interacting with people and objects in the environment.<p>
<p>
A child development programme or activity is one that looks beyond a child's
growth and survival needs and focuses on issues related to its needs for
attachment to consistent primary care-givers, its need to explore and
manipulate increasingly complex environments and its need to be praised and
valued for its accomplishments. <p>
By attending to a child's health, nutrition and psychosocial needs, survival
and development are simultaneously enhanced.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>B.	Rationale for Investing in Early Child Development Activities</b><p>
<p>
Over the past decade a growing body of scientific, political programming data
emphasize why governments and NGOs should focus attention on comprehensive
child development programmes. As indicated in your handout the arguments are
vast and varied. Let me simply highlight <p>
<p>
<b>Programme Efficacy Argument</b>  The effectiveness of health, nutrition,
education, and income-generating programmes can be improved through their
integration with programmes of child development. Thus, taking advantage of the
interactive effects of these. Child development programmes are often an
important entry point for community development activities.<p>
<p>
<b>Social/Economic Argument</b>  Society benefits through increased
productivity and cost savings which can result from high quality child
development activities. These preventive programmes can produce savings by
reducing the need for curative health service, by improving the efficacy of
education systems, by reducing the number of dropouts and repetition.<p>
<p>
<b>Scientific Argument</b>  The research evidence demonstrates that the early
years are critical in the development of intelligence, personality, and social
behavior and that there are long term effects associated with a variety of
early intervention programmes.<p>
<p>
Other arguments include:<p>
<p>
<b>A human rights argument:</b>  Children have a right to live and to develop to
their full potential.<p>
<p>
<b>A moral and social values argument:</b>  Through children humanity transmits
its values. That transmission begins with infants. To preserve desirable moral
and social values in the future, one must begin with children.<p>
<p>
<b>A social equity argument:</b>  By providing a "fair start", it is possible to
modify distressing socio-economic and gender-related inequities.<p>
<p>
<b>A political argument:</b>  Children provide a rallying point for social and
political actions that build consensus and solidarity.<p>
<p>
<b>Changing social and demographic circumstances:</b>  The increasing survival
of vulnerable children, changing family structures, country to city migration,
women in the labour force, and other changes require increased attention to
early child care and development.<p>
<p>
Taken collectively we have a compelling and powerful rationale for investing in
ECD. From this rationale we should be capable of eliciting the necessary
support and commitment to these programmes whether they are organized by
individuals, families, communities, non-governmental organizations,
governments, or international funders.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>II. 	Programme Responses</b><p>
<p>
<b>A.	A Typology</b><p>
<p>
As one looks at ECD programmes from around the world, there is an impressive
body of accumulated knowledge and experience. As indicated in the attached
table the wide range of economic, social and political circumstances in which
children live has created a mosaic of different approaches. These can include,
for example:<p>
<p><ul>
Attending to children in centers.<p>
Supporting and educating parents and families.<p>
Promoting community development.<p>
Strengthening institutional resources and capabilities,<p>
Strengthening demand and awareness.</ul><p>
<p>
Although all five approaches are aimed at enhancing early child development,
each has different specific objectives and is directed towards a different
audience or group of participants. The selection of a particular programme
approach is dependent upon a range of factors and circumstances including for
example, cultural patterns and practices, availability of resources both human
and financial, and the range and the intensity of problems confronting
children, mothers, and families. It is hoped that a national policy in favor of
children will simultaneously support the range of alternative strategies, each,
with its attendant strengths and weakness.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<b><center>TABLE </b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>PROGRAMMING FOR CHILD DEVELOPMENT:</b><br>
<b>COMPLEMENTARY APPROACHES AND MODELS</center></b><p>
<pre>
<b>Programme	Participants/	  Objectives		Models</b>
<b>Approach	Beneficiaries</b><p>
<b></b><p>
Deliver 	The Child	 Survival		Home day care
a service	0-2 years	 Comprehensive	  	Integrated child
		3-6 years	 development		development centers
		0-6 years	 Socialization      	"Add-on" centers
				 Rehabilitation	 	Work-place
				 Improvement of	 	Preschools: formal/
				 child care		   non-formal
<p>
Educate 	Parent, family	 Create awareness	Home visiting
caregivers	Sibling(s)	 Change attitudes	Parental education
		Public		 Improve/change	 	Child-to-Child
				 practices		programmes
							Mass Media<p>
Promote 	Community	 Create awareness	Technical
community	Leaders		 Mobilize for action	mobilization
