		Para-professionals			projects
							Strengthening
							infrastructure
	
<p>
Advocate child	Policy-makers	 Create awareness	Social marketing
development	Public		 Build political will	Ethos creation
programmes	Professionals	 Increase demand	Knowledge
				 Change attitudes  	dissemination<p>
</pre>						  
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>B.	Parent Education Models</b> <p>
<p>
Since a major objective of our workshop is to discuss the potential for a
parent education programme in Cairo, I will highlight several examples of this
approach. The main purpose of programmes to educate parents, families and
communities in child development is to strengthen self-confidence, impart
knowledge and enhance parents' existing ability to foster the physical, mental,
social, and emotional development of their young children. Parental education
for ECD can occur in the home or outside, on an individual basis or in groups.
It may be realized through face to face interaction or through distance
education emphasizing the use of mass media. It may be didactic or based on
observation, imitation, and demonstration.<p>
<p>
Several existing parental education projects have been implemented in
Indonesia, China, and Colombia. For example, in Indonesia together with the
periodic weighing of young children and distribution of food, mothers
participate in group discussion sharing experiences and making toys out of
wooden materials. In China, the All China Women's Federation has established
200,000 parent schools. Most of these schools are attached to hospitals and or
primary schools. Lectures are given by trained community residents and focus on
family child rearing issues. Started by the Associate Ministry for the role of
Women, the project aims to enhance the knowledge, awareness, and skills of
mothers of children under 5. Women from the local community are trained in
child development and adult education. They hold workshops at nutrition centers
and emphasize what mothers can do with their children at home.<p>
<p>
In a marginal area of Bogota, Colombia, a parent education programme was
developed. In this project, mothers or primary care-givers met once a week in a
community center where they were provided information on psychosocial as well
as health and nutrition questions. An innovative feature of this project
building on local practice was the creation of a baby book containing messages
from the baby to the mother. The book covering the first two years of life
provides a personal record for the child, at the same time, educating
care-givers and serving as a basis for discussion.<p>
<p>
All of these programmes recognize that parental education is not simply
"outside" experts transmitting pre-determined messages to parents who are
assumed to lack knowledge. Rather, they support common wisdom and local
practices as well as incorporating how information about development that has
not yet found its way into the sphere of common knowledge.<p>
<p>
In summary the enthusiasm surrounding parenting education is recognized by the
following factors;<p>
<p><ul>
  Both children and parents can benefit.<p>
  Reinforces family stability and responsibility as opposed to giving this to
        educational institutions.<p>
  Adds continuity and reinforces what may occur in other programmes.<p>
  Improvements in CD are more likely to be sustained.<p>
  Broad coverage can be maintained at lower costs.<p>
</ul>
<p>
It must be kept in mind however that parent education programmes are timely,
and that the process of transferring knowledge must provide for through
interpersonal exchange. It is suggested that parental education should be one
of several strategies that should be pursued simultaneously.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>C.	Guiding Principles</b><p>
<p>
Through the implementation of child development programmes from around the
world several principles or guidelines have evolved that should be considered.
These include:<p>
<p>
<p><ul>  Priority should be given to families and communities in which children are at
risk of delayed development.<p>
<p>
  Programmes should form part of a complementary multifaceted strategy, build
upon existing infrastructures, and develop partnerships with established
institutions and organizations.<p>
<p>
  Programmes should be community-based and community residents should play a
major role in all aspects of the programme's design and implementation.<p>
<p>
  Programmes should be able to adjust to different socio-cultural contexts, and
the materials and methods should incorporate a range of techniques.<p>
<p>
  Programmes should recognize and strengthen the local child-rearing patterns
and practices that have been devised to cope with problems of child care and
development.<p>
<p>
  Programmes should be financially feasible and cost-effective, and find ways
to address issues related to long term sustainability.<p>
<p>
  Programmes should try to reach the largest possible number of children and
families in need of services.</ul><p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>III.	Strategies</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>A.	Goal</b><p>
<p>
Based upon these principles, UNICEF/Cairo in collaboration with its
non-governmental and governmental partners is planning to design, implement,
and evaluate a range of complementary Early Child Development (ECD) activities.
The overall goal of these activities is to empower those who care for young
children including health professionals, teachers, families, and parents with
the knowledge, attitudes, and skills necessary to enhance the development of
Egyptian children from birth through the first six years of life. <p>
In order to enhance the development of young children in greatest need of
services, the proposed National Early Child Development Programme requires a
multi-staged, multi-channeled complementary approach. The following section
outlines four specific projects comprising this approach.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>B.	Multi-Faceted Complementary Approach</b><p>
<p>
Over the next several years UNICEF will develop a National Early Child
Development Programme consisting of several interrelated projects. At the
present time, four projects comprise this strategy and include:<p>
<p>
a. Community-based parent education activities in collaboration with NGOs and
  other community service providers.<p>
b. Enhancing child development through mass media efforts.<p>
c. Integrating child development issues into existing health and nutrition
services.<p>
d. Strengthening existing formal preschools.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>Enhancing Early Child Development: A Complementary Strategy</b><p>
<p>
<p><pre>
	Community-Based				Mass Media
	Parent Education			Partnerships
<p>
<p>
			Enhancing Early Child
			   Development<p>
<p>
	Child Development and			Strengthening
	Health and/Nutrition			Existing Preschools <p>
</pre>
As shown in the above Figure, the overall goal of each of these four projects
is to enhance the development of young children from birth through the first
six years through the training of existing service providers including
community workers, media personnel, pediatricians, preschool educators, and
parents. <p>
<p>
The specific objectives of each of these four projects are as follows:<p>
<p>
1. <b>Community-Based Parent Education Programmes</b>   The objective of this
project is to work with existing non-governmental organizations (NGOs) and
other community groups in the design, implementation and evaluation of a
parenting education programme. Working with small groups of parents and other
caregivers, trained community facilitators will discuss issues related to the
developmental needs of young children from birth through the first six years of
life.<p>
<p>
2. <b>Mass Media Activities</b>   The objective of this project is to work with
representatives from the mass media to develop a series of television, radio
and print materials on themes related to child development. These programmes
will be targeted to audiences of parents and other caregivers. In addition,
these methods could also be utilized in the design of programmes and materials
for children in the first six years of life.<p>
<p>
<p>
3. <b>Integrating Child Development with Health and Nutrition</b>
Capitalizing on the success of Egypt's child survival efforts, the goal of this
project is to increase the knowledge, attitudes and skills of pediatricians and
other health care providers regarding the developmental needs of young
children. Understanding the relationship between psychosocial, nutrition and
health needs of the young child will result in the delivery of a comprehensive
approach to child health. Thus, young children as well as parents will benefit
from the activities of this project.<p>
<p>
4. <b>Preschool Education</b>   The objective of this project is to strengthen
Egypt's existing preschool education facilities and programmes. Through a
series of training activities and workshops, preschool education teachers will
be exposed to different approaches to early child education. In addition these
activities will improve the ability of preschool educators to work with and
understand the needs of families and parents of young children.<p>
<p>
The success of the proposed National Strategy is dependent upon the close
collaboration of each of the four projects. No one approach is sufficient. The
skills, expertise and commitment of educators, community workers, media, and
health professionals must work together with families and parents to enable the
Egyptian children to reach their full potential. The content of materials and
methods used to accomplish the project objectives should recognize and build
upon the values and strengths of parents in caring for their children combined
with new information on development. To foster and guide this collaboration,
between each of these initiatives it is suggested that an Advisory Committee
comprised of representatives from each of the four project areas be
established.<p>
<p>
I will now discuss in more detail the conceptual underpinnings of the
Community-Based Parent Education Project which will be the subject of the
afternoon working groups.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>IV.	Project Description: Community-Based Parent Education Programme</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>A.	Introduction</b><p>
<p>
The goal of this project is to collaborate with NGOs and other existing
community services to provide parents and families with information and skills
about the importance of the early child development period (birth - 6 years).
Through participation in this project parents will gain knowledge and skills
enabling them to enhance their child's cognitive, emotional, social development
as well as to foster their learning skills.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>B.	Programme Planning</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b>Although there is a tremendous amount of material on "how to parent" it
will be important to tailor this information to meet the needs of Egyptian
parents. Thus, the content of the material presented in the programme must
address early child development issues that are important to Egyptian parents.
It is necessary to build upon and recognize the strengths of existing patterns
and practices. New information can then be integrated into this framework.<p>
<p>
Recognizing this need, the first step in the development of this project is to
work with parents and communities in the identification of existing patterns
and practices, problems and concerns regarding early child development, and
factors that inhibit parents from changing their behavior. Using informal data
collection techniques including interviews, observations, and small group
discussion sessions, the needs of parents on topics such as feeding,
discipline, language, development, social and emotional development and early
learning skills will be explored. Information about what parents want for their
young children as well as their current practices will also be obtained.<p>
<p>
The knowledge gained from this research will be used to guide the development
of the content of the parent education curriculum. A joint working group
consisting of members of NGOs, community representatives and technical experts
in the field of early child development will work collaboratively to design and
pre-test the programme content. For example, the parent education programme
could include age-appropriate (infancy, toddlerhood, preschool) information on
various themes including:<p>
<p><ul>
	<li>  Patterns of parent-child interaction
	<li>  Discipline
	<li>  Language and communication
	<li>  The role of play
	<li>  Safety and health
	<li>  Feeding and nutrition
	<li>  Learning, problem-solving and sensory capabilities
	<li>  Self-esteem and social development
	<li>  Gender differences in early development</ul>
<p>
In addition to those cross cutting themes, parents could be provided with
critical information on the timing and sequence of tasks in the normal process
of child development.<p>
<p>
It is also necessary to identify the set of materials and methods to be used in
transferring this information to parents. For example, various formats could be
explored including posters, videos, cartoons, flash cards, story-books. The
methodology for working with parents and families needs to be developed such as
small groups, home visiting and linkages to existing programmes such as
literacy and women's income generating activities.<p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>C.	Programme Implementation</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b>Working with NGOs, the community-based parent-education facilitators
will be identified and trained. At the same time, efforts to mobilize parents
of young children about the importance of this programme will be implemented.<p>
<p>
The parent-education facilitator will implement the curriculum working with
small groups of parents with children of similar ages. For example, it would be
necessary to form groups of parents with children of infants, toddlers, or
preschool age. In this way, parents could discuss issues of development which
are most relevant to them.<p>
<p>
It will also be important to closely supervise and co-ordinate the programme
both within and between communities. Thus, a coordinating body should be
established to identify problems, provide immediate solutions and make
necessary adjustments in the content of the curriculum as well as the training
and implementation strategies.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>D.	Evaluation</b><p>
<p>
In addition to monitoring the process of the programme, efforts to evaluate the
ability of the project to improve the parents' knowledge and beliefs as well as
increase their parenting and child rearing skills will be evaluated. It is
expected that children will also benefit from their parents' participation in
the programmes. Thus, changes in the child's development will also be
evaluated.<p>
<p>
<b></b><p>
<b>E.	Expansion and Sustainability</b><p>
<p>
Based on the results of the evaluation combined with the acceptance of the
programme at the community level, issues of programme expansion will be
discussed. Factors relevant to a discussion of programme expansion and
sustainability includes, for example, financing, training facilities,
availability of personnel, materials development, monitoring and supervision.
Of critical importance will be how to maintain quality as the programme seeks
to reach higher numbers of families in need of the services.<p>
<p>
<p>
I look forward to our group discussion this afternoon and to your reactions to
this community-based parent education project. Again, I thank you for the
privilege of being a part of your work. I would like to close with a statement made at a public
lecture recently delivered at a UNESCO Seminar, Urie Bronfenbrenner, a great
friend of children, underlined the importance of our common responsibility when
he stated "the most potent dynamic that will bring success to our effort is the
new hope to families and nations across the world of seeing children, seemingly
fated to a life of failure and pain, bloom into competent and caring human
beings".
