<HTML>
<TITLE>INTERNATIONAL EARLY CHILDHOOD CARE AND DEVELOPMENT:
WHERE WE STAND AND THE CHALLENGES WE FACE</TITLE>
<H3>INTERNATIONAL EARLY CHILDHOOD CARE AND DEVELOPMENT:
WHERE WE STAND AND THE CHALLENGES WE FACE</H3><BR>
by Judith L. Evans,  Secretariat, Consultative Group on Early Childhood Care and
Development<BR>
Paper presented at the National Consultation on ECCD organized by the                
National Inter-agency Committee on Early Childhood Care and                     
Development.  November 11-12, 1994, Quezon City, Philippines<BR>
<p>
<CENTER><I>                   The real voyage of discovery consists not in seeking
new landscapes but in having new eyes.</I><BR> 
                                   Marcel Proust</CENTER><BR>
<P>  


     The focus of the world's attention has begun to shift to the 21st century.  Every major
international agency has set goals to be achieved as we head into the Year 2000 and beyond.  It is
important to have a long-term vision of what should happen to support children's development in
the next decades.  But in order to do that we need to have a clear understanding of where we are
now and what can be accomplished during what remains of this century.  In the next five years the
base for the work in the 21st century can be strengthened in much the same way that early
childhood care and development programmes seek to strengthen young children's base for all later
learning.<BR><P>  
     What I would like to do in this presentation is to highlight some of the major
accomplishments internationally during the last 15 years, raise some of the questions that have
arisen in relation to these accomplishments, and present some of the challenges before
us.<BR><P>  
<B>Accomplishment A: Many people have been "sold" on the importance of early childhood care
and development (ECCD), based on an understanding of the economic benefits of the
investment.</B><BR><P>  
     Early childhood care and development (ECCD) has been promoted actively by
practitioners for decades. Those who have taught young children are very much aware of the
value of the experience for the child. Educational psychologists have also been advocates of
attention to children's developmental needs during the early years. But neither the practitioners
nor the theorists have been able to command national or international attention. What finally made
a difference was being able to discuss the benefits of quality early childhood programming in
terms of cost savings and rate of return on investment. <BR><P>  
     The most striking example of these data have come from the High/Scope Perry Preschool
Project.  In that project a group of children from a small community in the USA have been
followed over the past 22 years.  Some of these children experienced a quality pre-school
programme; the other group had no preschool experience.  The experiences of these children have
been recorded as they progressed through school and have moved into adulthood.  The most
recent data were collected when the children reached age 27.  The differences between the groups
are dramatic, not only in terms of school achievement, but more importantly in terms of a variety
of social dimensions.  Those with the pre-school experience as compared with their peers who did
not attend preschool, did better in school, continued their education longer, have better paying
jobs, have more stable families, and are much less likely to require public assistance or have
criminal records.  These characteristics can be assigned economic value.  When this is done, the
study indicates that the public is receiving an estimated $7.16 for every dollar invested in
preschool. (Schweinhart et al., 1993) Data such as these have captured the attention of policy
makers, and national policy in relation to programmes for young children and their families has
changed as a result.<BR><P>  

     Early childhood care and education is also beginning to find its place on the agenda of
major donor agencies. A major boost to the early childhood field came as a result of events that
took place at the World Conference on Education for All (WCEFA) held in March 1990 in
Jomtien, Thailand.  During the conference the vision of "basic education" was expanded to
include meeting basic learning needs in the earliest years. This expanded definition reflected a
recognition that early development provides the foundation for learning in primary school and for
productive social contributions in later life.  Within the Framework for Action adopted at the
Conference it was noted that <I>learning begins at birth</I>. Further it stated: <BR><P>  


<CENTER>  "The preconditions for educational quality, equity and efficiency are set in the early
childhood years, making attention to early childhood care and development essential to the
achievement of basic educational goals."  (Paragraph 20)</CENTER><BR>
<P>
The Framework for Action included some dimensions of basic education that countries might
include in their own Action Plans for the 1990s. Among these was:<BR><P>  
<CENTER>  "Expansion of early childhood care and developmental activities, including family
and community interventions, especially for poor disadvantaged and disabled children" (Paragraph
8)</CENTER><BR><P>  


     The endorsement given at WCEFA for early childhood programming was in response to
overwhelming evidence that it is a sound social investment to provide appropriate support for
children's growth and development during the first years of life.  WCEFA spurred new interest
among many governments and some international organizations in creating and strengthening
programmes for the early childhood years.  The ratification of the Convention on the Rights of the
Child (November 1989), and the Summit for Children (September 1991) also brought increased
recognition to the needs of young children.  <BR><P>  


     This international climate in support of programmes addressing the needs of the young
child has opened up new funding.  For instance, the World Bank, which had virtually no loans in
this area five years ago has responded to country requests with at least a dozen loans over the last
5 years.  These loans support such diverse initiatives as programmes of parental education, formal
and non-formal pre-school programmes, home day care, and nutrition programmes that include an
educational component.  And today the majority of UNICEF offices throughout the world have
devoted significant resources to the support of early childhood programmes. The number of such
programmes is increasing.<BR><P>  
     Thus, it is safe to say that political will has improved in response to demand and in
growing recognition of the benefits that come from investments in the early years. 
<B><I>Indeed, it is probably fair to say that attention to children during the pre-school years is
now the fastest growing part of the educational sector.</B></I><BR><P>  
<B>Questions that arise:</B><BR><P>  
     There are essentially two questions that come to mind immediately.  The first is related to
programme quality.  Those programmes that have shown a clear impact are of high quality.  Thus
a primary question is, what is the real value of investment in early childhood programming when
low-cost models of pre-school provision are being implemented?  What level of quality must be
obtained before we can see positive results? <BR><P>  
     We know that the indicators of quality can be divided into two categories.  There are the
static dimensions -- the physical structure, the availability of water and sanitary facilities, the
amount of square footage per child, the kinds of materials the children have to work with -- all the
dimensions that are easily measured.  <BR><P>  
     The other indicators are the dynamic ones.  These include the kind of interaction that the
teacher has with the children, the way children relate to one another in the programme, the type of
supervision the teacher receives, the relationship of the parents and the community to the
programme.  These are the indicators that make a difference, but they are seldom used because
they are difficult to measure.<BR><P>  
     A great deal of work needs to be done to come up with indicators of quality that people
are comfortable using. We need to identify indicators that will allow us to make decisions about
the kinds of programmes that we should be supporting and ones where we can anticipate positive
results from our investment.<BR><P>  

     A related issue is the relationship between cost and outcomes.  We know that there is not
a causal relationship between the cost of a programme and its quality.  However there is a
relationship.  There are data to suggest that increased investment in quality early childhood
interventions is economically valid. That is, the rate of return for investment in the early years is
higher than rates of return at any other level of the education system. Thus it is argued that
governments should increase their spending for such programmes. <BR><P>  
     When policy makers become convinced that investment in ECCD is a sound investment,
they begin to look around for programmes to implement.  They see that early childhood advocates
promote the adoption of "low-cost" models -- implemented by paraprofessionals (hopefully with
some training), paid less than minimal wages or expected to provide volunteer service, using
locally made materials almost exclusively, and operating in makeshift space. Can it really be
expected that these low-cost efforts will allow the same yield on investment as higher-cost higher-
quality programming? Although one would not argue that high dollar investment is sufficient to
guarantee quality, it can well be imagined that there is a minimum investment necessary to yield
positive results.  The question is, what is the minimal investment that should be made in an early
childhood programme so that we can be assured of a positive outcome?<BR><P>  
     Another question is, how do we take current government interest in early childhood
programmes and turn that into policy which will provide sustained support for such programmes?
It is one thing for a government to be 'sold' on the importance of early childhood provision.  It is
quite another to have policies in place from which appropriate programmes can be developed.
<BR><P>  
     Some interesting initiatives along these lines are taking place.  For example, currently the
government of Malaysia is involved in a policy review.  A study has been commissioned to look at
the various programmes that the government is offering that impact on young children. <BR><P> 

     The study was initiated because currently there are six government departments
responsible for the provision of care and/or education to children before they enter the primary
school. These include the Ministry of Education, The Ministry of Land and Rural Development,
The Ministry of Health, the Ministry of Social Development and National Unity and the Ministry
of Human Resources.  There are also several quasi-governmental organizations providing early
childhood programmes. Each has a slightly different mandate and/or population that it serves. 
Yet there is an overlap of services in some communities and no one serving children and their
families in other parts of the country.  The government wants to create greater coherence within
the system.<BR><P>  
     It is anticipated that the main outcome of the study will be a set of essential data and a
"menu" of policy, strategy and financial options which will allow decision-makers to formulate a
comprehensive and cost-effective Malaysian policy for ECD for the next decade. Further, it is
anticipated that the review will lead to proposals regarding arrangements for effective
implementation, monitoring, management and coordination of the programme, and subsequent
identification of broad policy and strategy options for strengthening ECD's contribution to
national development.<BR><P>  
     This type of review of current early childhood provision, leading to a set of policy
recommendations was also undertaken in South Africa, in anticipation of the installation of the
new government.  Increasingly as governments are asking questions about how best to invest in
early childhood programming, groups like UNICEF are in a position to facilitate this type of
linkage between current programming and policy.<BR><P>  

<B>Challenges:</B><BR><P>  
 
     As there were two questions, there are two challenges.  One
challenge is to better understand the economics of creating, implementing and sustaining early
childhood programmes and to be bolder in our statements about the level of resources required if
the investment is going to pay off. The other challenge is for early childhood educators to work
more closely with government to see that appropriate policies are established that will support the
development of programmes for young children and their families.<BR><P>  

<B>Accomplishment B:  This is an abundance of strategies for the provision of Pre-school for
children 3-6 years of age.</B><BR><P>  
     In all corners of the world one can find pre-school programmes for the 3-6 year age
group. Some of these have strong theoretical foundations; others are based on the model for
primary schooling which prevails in the country. Some are well known, documented and
promoted; others are known only to those whom they serve. Many include high levels of parent
involvement and/or are community-based. Almost all attempt to be culturally appropriate,
particularly in terms of curriculum and materials used by and with children. Some have even
successfully integrated traditional religious and cultural activities with more secular learning. Be
cause of the variety of options currently available to a group or community that wants to create a
pre-school programme, it is hard to imagine that someone could come up with a truly
"innovative" approach to pre-school education, at least within the limits of our beliefs, values and
assumptions about learning and the purpose of education.<BR><P>  
<B>Questions that arise:</B><BR><P>  
     One of the reasons new approaches are funded is that we do not know enough about what
can be achieved by the programmes that currently exist.  There are a wide variety of programmes
that claim to support the growth and development of young children.  Most programme
descriptions state that they are child-centered, or activity-based, or some phrase to that effect. But
when you step inside the centre you find the children's attention focussed on the teacher; children
are not actively involved in learning. Thus we need to get  inside programmes to understand the
relationship between the goals of the programme and what is actually happening on a day-to-day
basis, and what that means in terms of child outcomes.<BR><P>  
     We argue for increasing the number of places available in daycare, yet the research would
clearly indicate that not all programmes produce long term positive results for children. 
Kagitcibasi (in press) conducted a comparative study of children who participated in daycare
where little attention was paid to children's overall development, a pre-school with a well-rounded
programme, and children whose mothers participated in a "Mother Training" programme.  She
found that the children who did best were those in the Mother Training group. Those in the pre-
school did almost as well.  However, those in the daycare setting lost ground developmentally as a
result of being in the programme.  Thus, it is important that those programmes that exist are
evaluated systematically and that we make clear choices about the kinds of programmes that
governments should and should not fund.  <BR><P>  
     At this point in time there is a lack of comparative knowledge about what has worked and
what has not.  So rather than trying to identify 'innovative' approaches, attention might more
profitably be focused on testing the efficacy of various strategies.  It would be useful to identify
effective strategies that might be combined to create an integrated programme, creating new, or at
least more clearly defined, models that can usefully be disseminated.<BR><P>  
     In the process, one of the questions that needs to be answered is, what constitutes a
<I>model?</I> A dictionary definition of the word suggests it is "a preliminary pattern
representing an item not yet constructed and serving as the plan from which the finished work,
usually larger, will be produced, or, a tentative ideational structure used as a testing device."
(American Heritage Dictionary of English Language, 1969). From that definition an early
childhood intervention model can be seen as a framework (plan) that provides the theoretical
underpinnings for the creation of a programme that is built upon locally and tested in context for
appropriateness.<BR><P>  
     If this definition is applied to the various early childhood activities available, it is soon
evident that most are not models. Rather, they are a set of strategies that may or may not be part
of a larger whole that could be called a model. For example, in India the Cognitively Oriented
Preschool Programme for Children (COPPC) has been developed. It is seen by some as a pre-
school curriculum. In fact, it consists of a set of games and activities which teachers can use to
engage children in the learning process. During COPPC training teachers are actively engaged in
learning as they construct games and activities to be used with the children. Having experienced
active learning themselves, they are better able to understand its value. And that is the primary
learning they take into the classroom. <BR><P>  
     Even though the COPPC approach is neither a model nor a total curriculum, it is valuable
in that it is able to stimulate a teacher's thinking and behavior, which, in turn, makes a difference
in terms of how children learn. So, in putting together a programme, one would want to include
some of the dimensions of the COPPC effort.<BR><P>  
<B>The challenges:</B><BR><P>  
     One challenge is to make sense of the rapidly expanding set of approaches, techniques and
methodologies designed to affect children's development in their early years, and then determine
what should be disseminated, based on its effectiveness. <BR><P>  
     A further challenge has to do with the age group currently being reached.  As noted, most
early childhood programmes have been created for the 3-6 year old child. Little programme
development has been done for the child from the point of "survival" to the age of 3. Children
within this age group are relatively invisible. Yet, as research to be discussed later indicates, it is a
critical period in terms of health, nutrition and cognitive stimulation. Thus there is a gap in our
experience in developing effective programmes for the youngest children and their families. 
<BR><P>  
<B>Accomplishment C:  There is increasing recognition of the importance of
 the linkage between what happens in early childhood programmes and children's experience in the
early years of the primary school.</B><BR><P>  
 In recent seminars, workshops and international fora one of the main topics of interest has
  been the interface/linkage between pre-and primary schools. Part of the impetus for this came
  from the WCEFA activities where the early years were linked with basic education.  This was
  built on an understanding of the continuity of children's development from birth through the
early  primary years. Carrying this thinking through, policy-makers and programmers are seeing
the
  relationship between children's early childhood experiences and their school attainment and
  performance.<BR><P> 
  
     There is increasing concern about the high drop-out and repetition rates in many Majority
  World countries.  These rates are particularly high during the first three years of primary school. 
  The predominant response is that children are not ready for school, so "readiness" programmes
  have been created.  For example, there is a "Bridging Programme" in South Africa, where
children
  essentially have a year of schooling within the formal school system before they are admitted into
  the first primary grade.  Another example is Promoting Primary and Elementary Education
  (PROPEL), a program which has been developed in India.  Through it children ages 3-6 spend 2
  hours a day in centres designed to help prepare them to enter school. <BR><P> 
  
     These particular readiness programmes make the assumption that children will perform
  better and stay in school longer if the child is better prepared for the school.  However, it needs
to
  be recognized that the child does not stand alone.  
Children's school experiences are based on the

 interaction between the child and the school.  Therefore, another part of the readiness equation
is
  the degree to which the school is ready to receive the child.  For example, many schools operate
  from the assumption that children are empty vessels to be filled.  There is a lack of awareness
  regarding children's developmental differences and the kinds of experiences they bring with them
  as they enter school.<BR><P> 
  
     The importance of the school's readiness is illustrated by the experience that non-
  governmental agencies have had implementing high quality pre-schools and then discovering that
  despite the fact that children are well prepared for learning, they have very negative primary
  school experiences.  This has caused people to question the value of investing in an early
  childhood program if the benefits of that programme are lost when children enter a primary
school
  of questionable quality.<BR><P>   
  
     Within India there is an interesting example of what can happen when a high investment in
  early childhood programming was made without adequate attention to the total context. In
  Gujarat, a state in Western India, the Aga Khan Education Services (AKES) operates a cluster
of
  50 day care centres which are half-day pre-schools providing children with education, health
  services and nutritional supplementation. Further, there is a high degree of emphasis on parent
  education and community control of centres. Over the years these pre- schools have provided
  children with a solid base intellectually, physically and socially as they enter the local government
  primary school. In the late 1980's AKES began tracking what happens for the children as they
  enter primary school.<BR><P> 
  
     While the expectation was that primary school teachers would respond positively to the
  fact that children entering from the pre- schools were well prepared for school, and would
  perhaps be motivated to teach better, that has not been the outcome. In some instances it was
  reported that the children were immediately advanced to primary 2 or 3, even though the
children
  were not prepared to succeed intellectually or socially at that level. In other instances they were
  segregated from the other children and neglected until those without the pre-school experience
  had caught up. In neither instance is this an appropriate response. The strength of the pre-school
  experience is not being built upon; it is being set aside. Unless there are ways of working with
the
  primary school teachers and providing continuity between the pre-school and primary school
  experience, the argument could quite legitimately be made that it is not worth investing in the
pre-
  school.<BR><P> 
  
     While not going to the extreme and arguing that investments not be made in preschool if
  the primary school is not adequately prepared to receive the children, Myers (1988) in a review
of
  the research on the relationship between pre-schools and primary school performance,
concludes:<BR><P> 
  
  <CENTER>   Enrollment, progress and performance in school are influenced both by the
cognitive and
       social characteristics a child brings to the school and by the availability and quality of
       schooling. Either or both of these sets of variables can favor or present obstacles to
       successful school enrollment, adjustment, progress, and achievement... Programme
       decisions about early childhood intervention and about improvements in primary schooling
       should be considered together, not separately. (p.2-3)</CENTER><BR><P> 
  
     Thus, even as programming for child survival cannot be completely successful in isolation,
  focusing on programming for the needs of children from 3-6 cannot be done in isolation. There
is
  an interdependency between what happens in the pre-school and what happens at the primary
  level.<BR><P>  
  
     While fewer in number, some programs have been developed which address both
  children's readiness for school and the school's readiness to receive children (Subaran, in press). 
  One example is the Joint Innovative Project (JIP) sponsored by UNESCO in China.  Four major
  lines of action have been taken within the project. One was to increase pre-school provision, a
  second was to focus on improving teaching methods and teaching materials at the primary level,
  third, teacher training was improved and fourth, there was an attempt to increase parent and
  community involvement.<BR><P>  
  
     Another example of a programme designed to bridge the gap between the child and the
  school comes from South Africa where within the Bophuthatswana school system a pre-school
  programme was developed as part of a larger school reform effort.  As in the China project, the
  focus is on increased pre-school provision, curriculum continuity, teacher training, and
community
  involvement. Thus in both instances the readiness issue is being addressed by focussing on all the
  essential elements in the child's environment -- the family, the community, and the school as well
  as the child.<BR><P> 
  
  <B>Questions that arise:</B><BR><P> 
  
     The primary question is, how do we know when interventions with young children and/or
  interventions in schools make a difference?  The difficulty in answering this question has been
that
  there are no agreed-upon indicators of either children's readiness for school or the schools
  readiness for the child.  <BR><P> 
   To try to fill this void the Secretariat of the Consultative Group on Early Childhood Care
  and Development (known as the CG) is coordinating a project within four countries (Kenya,
  Jamaica, Jordan and Colombia). Within each country a group of researchers is attempting to
  create a profile of what children are like when they enter the primary school, and what the school
  is like that is receiving them.  <BR><P> 
  
     The Child Status Profile is intended to reflect a holistic view of the child, to be relevant to
  the particular location in which it is to be used, and to be relatively simple.  It will provide a
  description that can be used to monitor the changing status of a population, to help identify
  groups of children (not individuals) most in need of support, and to provide measures of early
  intervention program effects as well as baseline data for the condition of children as they enter
  schools. <BR><P> 
  
     As noted, there is another side of the equation and that is the ability of schools to respond
  to the children. Because development and learning occur as a child interacts with his or her
  environment, the ability of a child to learn in any learning environment (including school)
depends
  not only on what the child brings to the environment but also on what the environment offers the
  child. Therefore, it is crucial to balance indicators of a child's status with indicators of the
  environment in which a child develops and learns. By creating a "Profile of the Learning
  Environment in Schools", it is possible to monitor the environment's (or school's) part in this
  interactive process.  Thus within the project, a profile for schools will also be created. 
<BR><P> 
  
  <B>The Challenges:</B><BR><P> 
  
     The challenge here is not to be satisfied with a <I>quick fix</I>.  It will not work to simply
  provide children with a 'crash course' to make them school ready.  Neither will the linkage
happen
  through osmosis.  (Some people think they have solved the problem by moving the pre-school
  onto the school compound to make the primary school more sensitive to the population about to
  enter the primary school.)  Concerted effort will have to be made to introduce curricula that
  provides a continuity of experience for children, to provide upgraded and on-going teacher
  training that prepares teachers to work with children from 3 to 8 years of age, and to get the
  community more involved in children's education from the very beginning and continuing on
  through.<BR><P> 
  
  <B>Accomplishment D:  A range of training and dissemination systems has been created in
  order to make early childhood programming available to a wider audience.</B><BR><P> 
  
     For every early intervention strategy developed, there is an accompanying training system.
  The multitude of training schemes can be compared by placing them on a grid (See Figure
1).<BR><P> 
  
  <CENTER>
  
                                Figure 1<BR><P> 
  
                       Mapping of Training Schemes<BR><P> 
  
                                 Theory<BR><P> 
  
                                          I                     II<BR><P> 
  
                    Pre-service ---------------------------------- In-service<BR><P> 
  
                                          IV                    III<BR><P> 
  
                                Practice<BR><P> 
  
  </CENTER>                        
                                              
     On one axis is pre- versus in-service training. One end represents pre- service training
  only; at the other end is on-the-job training of untrained teachers. In between is every imaginable
  combination. The other axis represents theory versus practice. The predominant model of
training
  being offered today is pre-service training, with a highly theoretical focus (Quadrant I). But this
  does not begin to meet the needs or realities in most Majority World countries. Since the late
80's,
  the movement has been to Quadrant III, where there is greater focus on the practical skills
  provided through in-service training.<BR><P> 
  
     Training falling in Quadrant III is well illustrated by the District Centres for Early
  Childhood Education, DICECESs, developed by the Kenya Institute of Education (KIE). Over
  the last 20 years there has been a boom in the creation of community-based pre-schools in
Kenya.
  The pressures of rapid population growth have meant that there are not enough places in
Primary
  I for all the children who are age-eligible. Recognizing that pre-school education would give
  children a better chance of obtaining scarce places, parents have created their own pre-schools.
  Within the harambee tradition, these schools are built by the community, staffed by untrained
  parent-paid teachers, and operated with sparse equipment and materials.<BR><P> 
  
     KIE began to address the issue of how to provide trained teachers for these community-
  based pre-schools in the late 70s when they created district training centres where local teachers
  receive intensive training over a two-year period during school holidays. In addition, during the
  school year they receive on-the-job training through periodic visits by training centre staff. At
the
  end of training, teachers receive a certificate in early childhood education. After having been
  involved in the district training process since the early 80's, KIE is experiencing two demands.
  One is for additional practical courses for those teachers unable to attend the two-year course
  because of lack of space or lack of minimal academic requirements. And, from those who have
  completed the course, there is a demand for additional theoretical input. In essence, KIE
designed
  a training system to meet a very specific set of needs, and the system is solidly in place.
<BR><P> 
  
  <B>Questions which arise:</B><BR><P> 
  
     From KIE and related training experiences it is clear that when training systems are
  designed to meet the needs of those to be trained and the systems they will serve, it is possible to
  create effective training. When there are too many constraints, the effectiveness of the training is
  more in question. Still other experiences have stimulated questions about the appropriate mix of
  theory and practice, and the limits of in-service training if teachers lack minimal skills.<BR><P> 
  
  <B>The Challenges:</B><BR><P> 
  
     One challenge is to continue to experiment with the more flexible in- service training
  models, the substance and form of which should be developed from needs and sound educational
  practice. Another challenge is to try to establish the threshold between theory and practice that
  gives teachers the practical skills they need to get children actively involved in the learning
  process, while at the same time giving teachers a solid enough theoretical base from which they
  can invent new activities that support children's learning.<BR><P> 
  
     Another challenge is to take those training programmes that have proven to be effective
  and create cadres of trainers who are able to disseminate those programmes to a wider audience. 
     One approach to this is being experimented with by the Bernard van Leer Foundation in
  Africa.  Within this effort master trainers are being identified in a given country. They will
receive
  additional training and then take on the responsibility for training other trainers in their country
  and possibly region.<BR><P> 
  
  <B>Accomplishment E. It has been demonstrated that the most effective programmes are those
  which "integrate" health, education, nutrition, social and economic development
  programmes, and that the younger child benefits from such interventions more than older
  children.</B><BR><P> 
  
     The latest research on the relationship between health, nutrition and stimulation argues
  convincingly that an adequate food supply is not enough to assure a child's survival, neither is
  access to micro-nutrients, neither is education, nor absence of disease.  Children's growth and
  development is fostered when all these variables are present, within a caring environment. 
<BR><P> 
  
     Within the past decade there has been a marked increase in our understanding of the
  interactive relationship between health, nutrition and education. For example, in a review of
  research looking at nutrition and educational achievement, Pollitt (1984) concludes that
  "malnutrition in infants and children is a potent contributor to school wastage." (p.7). He then
  examines a series of studies designed to provide nutritional supplementation. The results of these
  studies were disappointing. Pollitt concludes, "the remedial or preventive effects of monofocal
  nutrition supplementation intervention programmes during early life on the intellectual deficits
  associated with early chronic malnutrition are questionable." (1984, p. 31)<BR><P> 
  
     If that conclusion is valid, then what kind of intervention is appropriate? Research data
  would suggest that a multifocal approach is most effective. An elaborate intervention research
  project was conducted in Cali, Colombia in the early 70s. Children's experience in the
programme
  differed in relation to the age at which they entered and the type of interventions they received.
  The interventions included supplementary foods for the family, regular health monitoring, a full-
  day child care and education programme, and some parent education. This multifocal effort
  yielded positive results in terms of children's health and nutritional status as well as academic
  achievement. Pollitt concludes, "It is apparent... that nutrition interventions per se, as monofocal
  programmes, are not as successful as those multifocal interventions which add educational and
  health services to a good diet." (1984, p.26)<BR><P> 
  
     Another finding highlighted was that the younger the children were when they entered the
  programme, and the longer they were involved, the greater the total benefit to the child. The Cali
  Colombia study, and others reviewed by Pollitt, suggested to him that "there is strong evidence
of
  the plasticity of the organism among young children. The course of their growth and
development
  was heavily determined by the nature of the experiences that the children had." (1984, p. 25)
  Thus, there would appear to be a strong argument for looking at the multiple needs of young
  children and programming accordingly, rather than focusing on only one aspect of development.
  Further, there is a strong argument for providing an enriching environment for children at an
early
  age.<BR><P> 
  
  <B>Questions that arise:</B><BR><P> 
  
     The research cited is but one example of the range of studies currently suggesting both the
  efficacy of integrated programming and intervening early in a child's life in order to make a
  significant difference. The questions that arise are in relation to the nature of integration and
what
  is meant by "early" intervention.<BR><P> 
  
     What does integrated programming mean?  Integrated services  is the buzz-word today.
  For many,  integrated services  is seen as a panacea. Commonly heard phrases include: We could
  use day care centres as a vehicle for offering integrated services to the family... Programmes
  would be more cost-effective if they could provide integrated health and education services...
  Children are already getting an education, why can't we add a health component?... We should
  develop a child care programme in conjunction with the women's income generating activities...,
  etc. In various ways people have been attempting to stimulate cross-sectoral discussion, with the
  goal of creating integrated service programmes.<BR><P> 
  
     One of the problems has been that no one has defined what "integration" means. The
  dictionary sheds some light. According to the Oxford Concise Dictionary, (1987), the word
  "integrate" has two meanings. (1) complete by addition of parts; combine parts into a whole, and
  (2) bring or come into equal membership. If we were to take the first definition, integrated
  programming might be accomplished with relative ease. What tends to happen, however, is that
  people assume that the second definition obtains; there is the implication of "equal" partnership,
  and no one is quite willing to be equal with another. In the final analysis, it comes down to who
  will really be in charge, be responsible, have decision- making power, be held accountable?
  Perhaps a less threatening term should be used. The word, <I>coordinate</I>, for example,
which means
  to bring parts into proper relation, cause to function together. Perhaps <I>coordination</I> is
more
easily
  accomplished.<BR><P> 
  
     However, rather than struggling for a definition of integration or looking for a word to
  replace it, it makes more sense to look at the nature of the relationships that actually occur as
two
  or more sectors attempt to work together. Doing that, it is evident that a variety of words are
  needed. For example, <I>liaison</I> (connection) could be used when groups are at least
meeting
  together to learn more about what the other can provide. <I>Cooperation</I> (working together
toward
  the same end, mutual reinforcement of messages and practices) would describe instances where
  sectors work together to reduce duplication of services, perhaps jointly identifying gaps in
  services that need to be filled and deciding who might best address the gap. <I>Coalition</I>
(temporary
  combination of parties that retain distinctive principles), a stronger word, could be used when
two
  or more sectors actually work together toward some common goal, but the coming together is
  goal specific and/or time-limited. A <I>federation</I> (forming a unity but remaining
independent in
  internal affairs) suggests that separate sectors actually accept each other's goals and together
  focus on the best way to meet community needs. Federation appears to be necessary to
formulate
  national policy guidelines. The ultimate in integration is <I>unification</I> (reduce to unity or
  uniformity), which occurs when there is a single administrative system for the delivery of all
  services. <BR><P> 
  
     At this point there are guidelines for how child care and education programmes might
  <I>cooperate</I> with the health sector to introduce material and child health components
(Evans, 1985
  a), and questions have been raised about how a <I>federation</I> can be created which links the
  intersecting needs of women and children (Evans, 1985).  Further, there are examples of
  <I>unification</I>, where child care is used as an entry point for community development
(Macy, 1985).
  However, it is quite evident that the potential of truly integrated programming has not been
  adequately or significantly explored.<BR><P> 
  
     The second question is, what is the optimal age at which to introduce integrated interven-
  
  tions? As cited above, Pollitt noted that in the studies he reviewed, children who were receiving
  services from a "younger" age benefited more from them than older children involved in the
same  programme. However, the children in the studies he reviewed were no younger than 3. One
of
the  problems is that little longitudinal research has been undertaken to look at the impact of
multifocal  programmes for children 0-3. Thus there remain questions such as, should services be
offered
  earlier than age 3? Would there be an even greater impact if they were? What are the relative
  costs and benefits of such programmes?<BR><P> 
  
  <B>The Challenges:</B><BR><P> 
  
     It is unrealistic to expect that there is going to be one model of "integration"; in different
  situations it is going to mean different things. Thus, as we look toward the creation of integrated
  projects, the challenge is for all actors involved to agree upon a definition of the term as it is to
be  used in that context. Perhaps over time we can create clusters of programmes that exemplify
the
  various ways sectors can work together and have a clearer understanding of the impact of dif-
  
  ferent models of linkage.<BR><P> 
  
     Further, the challenge is to address the potential and nature of interventions appropriate
  for children below the age of 3, in terms of the sectors that should be involved, and the range of
  provision that can and should be provided. <BR><P> 
  
     Most specifically this speaks to the need for much closer work with parents. While
  programmes that educate and enable parents have grown dramatically in some countries, they
are
  virtually non-existent in others, particularly with respect to the psychosocial components of early
  development. <BR><P> 
  
  <B>Accomplishment F.  There is a significant movement toward greater collaboration between
  government, donor agencies and non-governmental organizations (NGOs).</B><BR><P> 
  
     Not only are attempts being made to create programmes which are cross-disciplinary, but
  there are moves for greater collaboration between governmental ministries, bilateral donor
  agencies, and local non-governmental organizations (NGOs).  In particular, bilateral donor
  agencies and international funding organizations are increasingly turning toward NGOs to create
  and implement programmes.  It is only within recent years that we have begun to see examples
of  collaborative arrangements which bring together and build on the strengths of 
 the participating  organizations.<BR><P> 
  
     This move toward greater collaboration has come about for a multitude of reasons. 
  Among them are the fact that: (1) The global economic crisis has put increasing burdens on
  governments.  They lack the resources to provide the range of supports and services required. 
(2)   There has been a serious questioning about the ways in which foreign aid has been provided. 
  There is a realization that traditional forms of aid have not been very effective. Thus new ways
of  working with countries are being sought.  (3) There is a belief that non-governmental
organizations are more in touch with what is going on at the grassroots level and thus have a
wealth of
  insight and experience that would be helpful in national programming.  Further, NGOs have
  greater administrative flexibility and can implement new initiatives more rapidly than
  governmental agencies.   <BR><P> 
  
     There are several trends evident even in these early days of co-operation and
  collaboration.  One is the expansion of successful NGOs to work on a much larger scale.  The
  primary example here is BRAC (Bangladesh Rural Advancement Committee) in Bangladesh. 
  With donor support, BRAC has now created rural development and education programmes that
  rival government programmes in scale and effectiveness. <BR><P> 
  
     The second is for NGOs to be much more sophisticated in their approach to and work
  with donors.  Again, BRAC is a good example. For years BRAC has been receiving funds from
  donor agencies to implement a full range of economic development and education programmes.
  For each agency BRAC has had to generate proposals and write reports (all with different
formats
  and timelines).  Rather than continuing to respond to all these demands, BRAC became
pro-active
  and created a consortium of donors with whom it works as a group, greatly simplifying
  administrative procedures while assuring results for donors.<BR><P> 
  
     Third, a hierarchy of NGOs is developing.  Some NGOs, BRAC among them, have
  become very powerful.  They have attained such a prominence internationally based on their
work
  that it is difficult for the national government to ignore them.  While some have questioned
  whether sizeable funds should be committed to one NGO, others have argued that given there is
  already a proliferation of groups, it is more valuable to provide adequate backing to those which
  are working well than to support numerous small, untried NGOs (Smillie, 1988).<BR><P> 
  
     An important role that the established NGOs are playing is provide technical support to
  other NGOs in terms of capacity/ institution building, dissemination of experience, networking
  and educating the funders in relation to effective programmes and policies.  This work has
  resulted in the strengthening of many of the smaller NGOs.<BR><P> 
  
     A fourth trend is the development of coalitions. NGOs are realizing that they can be more
  effective in working with government and with donors if they can present a united front. 
  Umbrella organizations of NGOs have developed in Asia (ANGOC) and Africa (FOVAD) to
  advocate for greater understanding of and support for NGOs.<BR><P> 
  
     Along with greater collaboration among NGOs, there is also greater co-operation among
  donors.  A notable example is the Consultative Group on Early Childhood Care and
Development  which was a pioneer in this effort to create collaboration among donors.  
A more recent example
is the Donors for African Education, a group which includes both donors and governments
  seeking ways to work together effectively in Africa.<BR><P>
  
     Thus there is considerable attention to the issue of how non-governmental agencies,
  governments and donors can work together to share experiences and resources to better meet
the
  needs of young children and their families.<BR><P>
  
  <B> Questions that arise:</B><BR><P>
  
     Primarily under question is the nature of the relationship that can and should be established
  between government, NGOs and funders/donors. Answers to the question will come partly from
a
  better understanding of NGOs. While the general belief has been that the more NGOs there are
  working in a given area the better, the validity of that belief is currently under discussion.
  Significant questions about the proliferation of, need for, appropriate size and role of NGOs
have
  been raised in several development sectors. These concerns are reflected in World Bank,
  UNICEF, UNDP and USAID documents developed during the past five years. Some of the
  concerns are as follows:<BR><P>
  
     First, how do we differentiate meaningfully among NGOs?  The term NGO is used to refer
  to any and all non-governmental organizations.  Yet NGOs differ greatly in some of the
following
  ways: <BR><P>
  
    <B> Purpose</B> - some are service-oriented, others provide technical support; some focus on
  charity while more and more are shifting to <I>development</I> as the basis of their approach. 
Still
  others are quasi-governmental and have been established as a way for government to conduct its
  work more efficiently.<BR><P>
  
   <B> Size</B> - some are very large, such a BRAC, others may consist of no more than a
handful of
  individuals.<BR><P>
  
     <B>Philosophy/approach</B> - some derive their activities from a grassroots approach to
  working with communities; others provide services to a community based on the NGO's
  assessment of what is needed.<BR><P>
  
     <B>Experience</B> - some are well established with a wealth of experience to back up their
work;
  others have been newly formed and are struggling to find and/or maintain an identify.<BR><P>
  
     <B>Resources</B> - some are well endowed and can devote their energies to their purpose
with
  minimal regard to fund raising, but most operate from year to year.  A poster seen on the wall of
  an NGO read  "We are tackling problems it will take 20 years to solve.  To do that we have five
  year plans, personnel who have been with us less than two years and one year of funding."  That
is
  not an unusual picture.<BR><P>
  
     <B>Scope</B> - some operate locally, working only within a single community; some are
regional
  or national in their focus; still others operate internationally.<BR><P>
  
     Thus it is as meaningless to talk about NGOs as a group as it is to talk about Majority
  World countries as a group.  One needs to know more about the comparative advantages of a
  given NGO in order to determine whether or not it is appropriate to explore collaborative
  arrangements.  <BR><P>
  
     Second, to what extent does NGO strength, often derived from its small size and
  homogeneity, get lost when the NGO tries to expand to reach a larger number of
people?<BR><P>
  
     There are examples of creative people who have needed to create NGOs in order to
  receive funding. Because of this they have been shifted from creative workers and trainers to
  administrators of organizations. This has not always been a successful shift. Unless the individual
  is willing to give up some measure of control (i.e. let someone else run the organization while
  they continue to do what they do best), there is likely to be a struggle between further
developing
  the ideas which were funded and devoting time to the maintenance of an organization which
may,
  in fact, get in the way of the message. It is important to be sensitive to the needs of individuals
  involved in NGOs. The issue is knowing when people should be supported to do what they are
  currently doing best, and when they are ready to take on new challenges. It is not always
obvious.<BR><P>
  
     Third, to what extent do NGOs see each other and the public sector as competitors for
  scarce donor funding and what does that mean in terms of collaboration and the ability of NGOs
  to learn from one another?<BR><P> 
  
     An illustration of the problem comes from an experience of the Aga Khan Foundation
  (AKF).  In the early 80s, AKF began funding a number of early childhood initiatives in India, all
  of which were focused on developing curricula for children 3-6 years of age. From the donor
  perspective it was possible to see ways in which the models being created came from a similar
  theoretical base, and what the various grantees could learn from one another if they would come
  together and share their thinking. However, despite various attempts, it was not until each of the
  projects was near completion that there was some interest in meeting together. In essence, each
  grantee wanted to maintain its own innovative approach until it chose to "go public".
Foundations
  and donors need to be in a position to assess what can be shared, with whom, and
when.<BR><P>
  
  
     There is clearly the potential for clashes between NGOs and governments as large donor
  agencies with bilateral funds are attempting to channel some of these monies to NGOs.
  Governments that have been in control of how these monies are spent are understandably
  reluctant to lose access to these funds and, in response, are establishing governmental
committees
  to control how and to whom these funds are allocated.  Such a process has been established in
  Kenya, where all grants made to the country must be reviewed by a national body before they
can
  be received by the NGO.  The review process consumes both time and financial resources. 
  Actions such as these will not make it easy for donors to provide grants directly to
NGOs.<BR><P>
  
     Fifth, although NGO projects may have small budgets in comparison to the public sector,
  their costs per beneficiary are often high. Does this mean that successful small-scale projects are
  not necessarily feasible as models for serving large populations?<BR><P>
  
     Some of the issues are addressed by looking at the experience of the Centre for Learning
  Resources (CLR) in Pune, India which produced excellent curriculum materials for use by pre-
  school teachers. A complete set of materials adequate for a teacher's use for one year, with
  minimal replacement in subsequent years, was mass produced at what appeared to be a relatively
  low cost ($16/set).  While all who reviewed the materials agreed on their high quality, it was
clear
  that if the materials were to be adopted on a large scale, (i.e. within the ICDS system which
  served 130 million children by the 1990s), the costs to the government would be prohibitive. So,
a
  compromise was made. CLR produced another set of materials at about half the original cost.
  This brought the costs within a manageable range, and they have now been made available to
  government training centres. However, even that compromise does not get the materials directly
  to teachers.<BR><P>
    
     The COPPC project, described earlier, also includes a set of materials, known as the
  COPPC kit. The kit, made from locally available materials, is created by teachers and/or
  supervisors during their training. The basic cost of the set is about $3. This is about as low cost a
  kit as can be produced. Once costs get to this level there is a real question about the durability of
  the "kit". Games made from newspaper, cardboard, etc; do not last long if they are used as
  teachers are trained to use them.<BR><P>
  
     A legitimate question being asked is, how low can the cost per beneficiary be and still have
  a project that is worthwhile?  A related issue is that of "scale". Not all projects have to be
adopted
  nationally, particularly in a country like India. We might better ask, what is the appropriate
"scale"
  to which a project can legitimately be taken?<BR><P>
  
  <B>The challenge:</B><BR><P>
  
     The primary challenge is to continue to explore ways in which partnerships can be
  developed among and between governments, non-governmental agencies and donors.  To do
this
  there is a need to shift from competition to co-operation.  This is not easy for organizations
which
  historically have been competitive.  But the more the organizations work together and break
  down the barriers, the greater potential there is for advancement on all fronts.  <BR><P>
  
  
  
     In sum, over the past 15 years there has been tremendous growth in understanding the
  needs of young children and their families. Persuasive arguments on the economic benefits of
early
  childhood programming have convinced many policy makers of the importance and necessity of
  early childhood provision.  There are a variety of programme models available to meet the needs
  of the 3-6 year age group, yet few for the 0-3 year old. Further, there have been real inroads in
  terms of understanding the inter-relationship of children's health, socio-emotional and cognitive
  needs and there have begun to be examples of appropriate programming.<BR><P>
  
     As in many other aspects of our lives, the more we achieve and learn, the more we see the
  need for greater achievement and learning. The temptation as we look toward the 21st century is
  to envisage a new <I>landscape</I> -- a radical change in the ways that children's needs are
being met --
  while our real understanding of what can happen for young children and their families will come
  from casting a new eye on what exists today.    <BR><P>
  
     We are poised to make a major improvement in the lives of young children around the
  world.  What is needed now is an extra push that will capture, sustain and add to the momentum. 
  We need to support the social and political will to act.  We need to collaborate in new ways to
  marshall additional resources.  We need to put knowledge and experience to work so as to
  improve programme coverage and quality.  In so doing, coming generations of children will be
  provided with what they need as they grow and develop.  <BR><P>
  
