<title>SUMMARY REPORT</title>
<body>
<center>
<b><u>SUMMARY REPORT</u></b><p>
<p>
of<p>
<p>
The Third Inter-

Agency
Meeting of<p>
The Consultative Group on Early Childhood Care and Development<p>
January 12-

14,
1987<p>

 Washington, D.C.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b><u>Theme:</u></b><p>
<p>
"Combining Health, Nutrition, and Psycho-

Social
Components<p>
in Programming for Early Childhood Survival and Development"<p>
<p>
<p>
</center>
This summary has been prepared by Robert Myers, Coordinator of<br>
The Consultative Group. Requests for copies of this summary (and those of<br>
previous meetings) may be directed to him c/o UNICEF/PD/A-6M,
866 United<br>
Nations Plaza, New York, New York 10017 USA.<br>
<p>
<p>
<b>THE THIRD INTER-

AGENCY
MEETING OF THE CONSULTATIVE</b><br>
<b>GROUP ON EARLY CHILDHOOD CARE AND DEVELOPMENT</b><br>
<b>January 12-

14,
1987</b><br>
<p>
<p>
<b><u>Background</u></b><p>
<p>
	In May 1983, staff from six organizations (Ford, UNICEF, USAID, Carnegie, WHO,
and IDRC) convened at the Ford Foundation in New York to discuss their mutual
interest in community-

based
programmes designed to promote early childhood care and development. After
sharing information about programmes and approaches being supported by each
organization, the group suggested that the informal exchanges continue on a
periodic basis. Accordingly, a second meeting was held at UNICEF's Headquarters
in New York, from October 29-

31,1984,
where special attention was given to the topic, "Going-

to-
Scale
with Programmes of Early Childhood Development." (Full summaries of these
previous two meetings are available from the Coordinating Unit of the
Consultative Group.) A third meeting, hosted by the Agency for International
Development, was held in Washington, D.C. from January 12 to 14, and is
reported upon in the following pages.<p>
<p>
<b><u>Purposes</u></b><p>
<p>
	The third inter-

agency
meeting of the Consultative Group on Early Childhood Care and Development had
three major objectives:<p>
	1. <u>To exchange programme information about current child care and
development activities</u> supported by each participating organization.<p>
<p>
	2. <u>To discuss the topic, "Combining Health, Nutrition, and Psycho-

Social
Components in Programming for Early Childhood Care and Development</u>."<p>
<p>
	3. <u>To review activities of the Consultative Group</u> and to think
collectively about its future.<p>
<p>
<b><u>The Agenda</u></b><p>
<p>
	 In the three-

day
meeting, most of the first day was devoted to information exchange. The
remainder of that day and all of day two focussed on the main theme. Working
groups were set up on the afternoon of day two. Day three was spent reviewing
activities and looking ahead. For details of the agenda and alist of documents,
see Attachment A.<p>
<p>
<b><u>Participants</u></b><p>
<p>
	 Among the 27 participants were staff from ten organizations participating in
the Consultative Group (USAID, UNICEF, Ford, IDRC, Carnegie, Aga Khan, The
World Bank, UNESCO, WHO/PAHO, and Rockefeller) as well as individuals from the
Commonwealth Secretariat, a major private voluntary organization (Save the
Children/USA), two research centres (High/Scope, The International Center for
Research on Women), and three universities (Maihdal/Thailand, Bogazici/Turkey,
and The National Teacher Training College/Lesotho). Reflecting the many-

sided
nature of early childhood development, participants came from the fields of
education, medicine, sociology, nutrition, psychology, economics, and social
psychology. Included in the group were present (or former) policy makers and
planners, practitioners and programme implementors, researchers, and funders.
This unusual diversity enriched discussion. For a list of participants, see
Attachment B.<p>
<p>
<b><u>Opening Remarks</u></b><p>
<p>
	 <u>Bichard Bissel</u>, the Assistant Administrator of Policy and Program
Coordination for the Agency for International Development (AID] welcomed the
Consultative Group, noting the importance of such a mechanism as an antidote to
uninformed duplication of efforts and as a basis for informed, less wasteful
programming. He noted that AID is providing considerable support for programmes
of child survival and assists many programmes in developing countries that
focus on the school-

aged
cohort. Little has been done in between those two, however, to support child
care and development. Even so, Mr. Bissel encouraged the Group's efforts noting
the natural follow-

on
of early childhood development to child survival and the need to begin
attending to the "eleven who survive" (see below). He mentioned as well the
potential influence on primary schooling of early interventions that improve
preparation for school.<p>
<p>
	In his remarks, Mr. Bissel urged the group to keep in mind that, with  early
childhood interventions as with other programmes, there is a need to look at
specific demands of particular environments when making programme choices.
There is also a need to consider the sustainability of programmes (within the
resource context in which programmes exist). That is hard to do if programmes
are imposed from outside and does a double disservice if governments cannot
pick up the programmes later. To the extent the Consultative Group can
contribute to fostering local adaptability and to increasing attention to
sustainability it will be performing a useful function.<p>
<p>
	<u> Robert Myers</u>, Coordinator of the Consultative Group, briefly recounted
the evolution of the consultative mechanism. He mentioned four characteristics
which, when taken together, distinguish this Group from others. First, it has
evolved as an<u> informal mechanism</u> with participation loosely defined to
accommodate different levels of interest and involvement while allowing also
for the varied organizational possibilities and constraints existing among
organizations interested in being involved. Second, the mechanism looks
<u>beyond survival to focus on development</u> of surviving children. (Myers
noted  that 11 of 12 children now survive to age one. By the year 2000 it is
estimated that 18 of 20 children will live, and many countries in the Third
World have already reached that level with an Infant Mortality Rate below 50,
making a look "beyond survival" increasingly central for programming.) Third,
the Consultative Group has emphasized <u>mental and social development</u>,
including attention to the interaction of care givers and children, to
nurturance, to language and cognitive development, and to socialization and
early education.   Fourth, the Consultative Group <u>cuts across traditional
sectoral and academic lines</u> in an attempt to overcome isolated viewpoints,
in which knowledge specialization and turf battles within organizations cut the
child into pieces, making integrated attention difficult. The conscious
crossing of lines by the Consultative Group is evident in the theme of the
meeting (combining health, nutrition, and psycho-

social
components) and in the Group's work linking early childhood development to
programmes of women-

in-
development
and to primary schooling.<p>
<p>
<b><u>Programme Information Exchanges</u></b><p>
<p>
	An explicit policy governing the support of child care and development
projects or programmes was an exception rather than the rule among those
present. Indeed, it seems that governments and national organizations in the
developing world are considerably ahead of donor organizations in their
thinking about, and support for, early childhood development programmes.
Nevertheless, international support was being provided for a wide range of
activities intended to benefit children, ages O to 6, in developing countries.
That includes support for such diverse activities as: pre-

natal
programmes to improve the health of women, child care within income-

generating
projects, assistance for a large-

scale
national service of integrated child development, research on home learning and
the transition to primacy school, the testing of early childhood development
measures (and other methods of studying children's development), the
preservation of indigenous toys and games, and longitudinal research examining
forms of child care provided to four year olds and their effects on enhancing
performance in primacy school.<p>
<p>
	Running through the presentations were frequent references to:<p>
<p>
 		 Support for integrated, multi-

sectorial
approaches.<p>
<p>
		 A desire for increased community participation.<p>
<p>
		 The importance to child survival and development of women"s health and
women's 		access to resources, including education and time.<p>
<p>
		 The potential of child development programmes for motivating women to
participate in health/nutrition programmes.<p>
<p>
		 An interest in improving monitoring and evaluation.<p>
<p>
		 The importance of recognizing how varied are the settings in which
programmes are located.<p>
<p>
		 A need to look beyond "technological" fixes.<p>
<p>
		 A need for basic descriptive information.<p>
<p>
Discussion of the Topic, "<u>Combining Health, Nutrition, and Psycho-

Social
Components in Programming for Early Childhood Care and Development</u>"<p>
<p>
	 Although there seems to be almost unanimous agreement that a multi-

faceted,
integrated approach to programming for child care and development is desirable,
that has often been difficult to achieve in practice. The meeting examined why
that integration is difficult, and under what circumstances integration might
realistically be expected. It also identified examples of ways in which such
integration has been achieved (or was being sought).<p>
<p>
	 The topic was approached from two directions. First, child care and pre-

school
programmes were looked at as entry points for health and nutrition components.
Second, the discussion turned to how psycho-

social
components might be included within health and nutrition programmes.
Inevitably, the discussion also brought out the somewhat limited and false
nature of this dichotomized approach, adopted as a discussion device. Other
examples of ways in which the several components might be combined were cited
as, for instance, in an integrated community development approach, or by
integrating the content of educational programmes for a variety of audiences,
or by incorporating all components into women's income-

generating
programmes.<p>
<p>
	1. <u>Child Care and Pre-

School
as Entry</u><p>
	<u>Points for Maternal and Child Health Care</u><p>
<p>
	 The discussion of how to add health and nutrition components into programmes
of day care began with a presentation of outcomes from a World Health
Organization (WHO) meeting held earlier in the year to discuss that topic. In
the documentation far that earlier meeting, a typology had been set out in
which various kinds of day care (at the work-

place,
in formal pre-

school
centres, in community-

run
centres, and in home day care arrangements) were examined for the feasibility
of use as vehicles for delivering different health care components to young
children of different ages. Health components were distinguished in terms of
their promotional, preventive or curative nature, and whether they responded to
nutritional, health (infection), security (from accidents), or developmental
needs. (See Attachment C for one rendering of the typology). Among the
conclusions from the WHO meeting were the following:<p>
<p>
	 If day care is to be used as an "entry point" for maternal and child health
care, a range of programme alternatives is needed, with selection of the
appropriate one depending on the age of the children in day care, the social
and geographic circumstances in which care is given, the type of care giver,
and the location of the care giving (work, neighbourhood, home). Accordingly,
planners and funders of programmes need better descriptions of existing child
care arrangements, through case studies, and national surveys.<p>
<p>
		 A minimum standard of quality is required for day care. Some characteristics
of quality care were discussed.<p>
<p>
		 Unless a primary health care system is already in place, using day care
arrangements to deliver MCH services is unlikely to be successful.<p>
<p>
		 Day care and its extension as an entry point for health care should be seen
as complementary to, not a replacement for, the family.<p>
<p>
		 Formulating a programme should begin with a situational description of
children's needs, followed by an evaluation of how well the family meets those
needs (recognizing that many will be fulfilled by the family), and by an
assessment of how formal and non-

formal
arrangement do, and might do more to, complement family functions in meeting
those needs.  That diagnostic process would identify where additional support
is needed and allow planning of the activities, materials,... required to
provide it. In so far as possible the diagnostic process as well as the
organization and conduct of activities should be participatory.<p>
<p>
	The WHO meeting went on to try and define the kind of training, technology,
materials, and technical assistance that would be required in the different day
care circumstances to use the day care effectively as an entry point for MCH
components of PHC.<p>
<p>
	These and other points from the earlier meeting were set out in a summary of
the meeting provided as background reading.<p>
<p>
	 <u> Discussion</u>.   The focus on "day care" as an entry point seemed too
narrow.  A distinction was therefore made between day care, with its
connotation of custodial caretaking with perhaps some educational content for
children, and "child care," which would include not only a "minimum package" of
services needed for adequate attention to the needs of children, but also a
parental education component. From this broadened definition followed comments
suggesting that the original typology, set principally in terms of where
organized day care occurs, needed to be supplemented by looking at who would be
trained in each of these circumstances. The earlier WHO discussion had focussed
on the training of day care professionals or para-

professionals,
providing them with knowledge about preventive and curative health and
nutrition activities. The broader view was that the "entry point" should really
be training of the parents of children in day care arrangements. The question
then became, "What day care circumstances and what methods would favor
education of parents and other caretakers?"<p>
<p>
	 With a broadened view of the problem to include parents came also discussion
of the method implied in considering "day care as an entry point."  Some
concern was expressed that, in spite of specific attention in the WHO typology
to preventive and promotional as well as curative activities, a curative
emphasis was implied and was likely to prevail unless a different approach was
formulated. Not only would it be necessary to impart knowledge to parents and
other caretakers but it would also be necessary to avoid lecturing them on what
to do, and to motivate participation by linking discussion to highly valued
ideas (e.g. "helping the child be more intelligent") or activities (e.g. income-

generating
projects or community and group discussions of mutual problems). Several
participants suggested that health themes, per se, did not seem to be highly
motivating for parents. Where child care occurs in factory settings, it may be
possible to obtain released time of mothers form the kind of discussions
suggested above. That is more difficult for other forms of day/child care, and
so motivation to attract parents would be critical. Women's organizations exist
in many countries that can be mobilized to this end.<p>
<p>
<p>
	 One participant suggested that educational messages are usually delivered at
the health centres, not day care centres, which provide services for children.
But mothers are in a hurry, and so that medical model does not always work very
well. This led to the observation that messages and desired outcomes should be
differentiated, with those requiring more time or learning (e.g, learning new
forms of food preparation) provided in a discussion setting, perhaps attached
to a child care arrangement.<p>
<p>
	The Group was reminded of the importance of distinguishing child care needs
and arrangements by the age of the child being served. Although the
documentation made that distinction clearly, discussion in the Group quickly
slipped into undifferentiated treatment, with 0-

1
and 3-

6
year olds lumped together.<p>
<p>
	One participant observed that day care seemed to be primarily an urban
phenomenon, associated with a relatively stable source of income, providing
services for a fairly self-

selected
group. That idea was countered with examples of early childhood programmes
(that also provide "day care") from India, Kenya, Zimbabwe, Peru, and
Thailand.<p>
<p>
	A question was raised about the status of serious evaluation of child care
programmes -- in general, and as entry points for health and nutrition. Several
solid evaluations of child care programmes were mentioned, some of which
included attention to health and nutrition components as well as to cognitive
and social development. There was, however, a clear need for additional
systematic evaluation of child care alternatives.<p>
<p>
	Finally, the discussion turned toward the political contexts of governmental
decision-

making
about support for child care arrangements and for their use as extensions of
the public health system. Noting that most child care is still informal and
much of the growth has been in community-

based
or private programmes, a question was raised (but not answered) about the
dynamics by which a growing demand for child care creates a political
imperative to support expansion and improvement of child care. Can one
anticipate pressure points on policy and act accordingly? There was a question
also about the inevitability of increased control and decreased flexibility
with increased involvements of governments. Can a co-

partnership
between the private sector/community/parents and government be forged, or does
government involvement inevitably lead to a shift of responsibility and
control? (Additional attention would be given to this issue in conjunction with
the Colombian case to be described below.)<p>
<p>
	This discussion was followed up in Working Group No. 1, reported upon below.
<p>
<p>
	<b><u>2. Integrating Psycho-Social Components</u></b><p>
	<b>into Programmes of Health and Nutrition</b><p>
<p>
	The second approach taken to the theme turned the topic around by looking at
how developmental components might be worked into programmes focussed on
survival and growth. Two complementary case studies were presented as a basis
for discussion. The first was an action research project demonstrating
integration of psycho-

social
components into a nutrition programme (that was in turn, part of an integrated
rural development programme in rural Northeast Thailand). The second case study
was of an on-

going
set of activities integrating psycho-

social
components into a Colombian national programme of child survival and
development by mobilizing the educational system. In both cases, attention was
given to the process as well as to the content of the activities.<p>
<p>
	<u>The Thai case study</u>.   A case study of the integration of psycho-

social
components of early childhood development in a nutrition education programme of
rural Northeast Thailand was presented by Dr. Nittaya Kotchabhakdi of the
Department of Pediatrics, Ramathibodi Hospital in Bangkok.   Her background
paper, written for the meeting, reported results of a nutrition education
programme based on use of five video modules for the training of community
workers and for the education of parents. The modules dealt with differences
between well-

nourished
and  malnourished children, the value of breast-feeding, basic food groups,
cooking of a supplementary food product, how to encourage babies to eat, and
the importance of providing infants and young children with stimulation and
play materials.<p>
<p>
	 The action research examined children's nutritional status and maternal
knowledge, attitudes, and child regarding practices. Village mothers of under-

two
aged children were interviewed individually prior to introduction of the media-

based
nutrition education, and at 2, 10, and 14 months later. A comparison was made
between families in randomly-

assigned
"treatment" and control villages.<p>
<p>
	 In the paper data from the study were presented that responded to two main
hypotheses:<p>
<p>
		 a. Improved mother-

child
interaction will have a positive effect on child nutritional status, acting
through improvements in maternal understanding of the child's needs and better
feeding of supplementary food.<p>
<p>
		 b. Child rearing practices will be more appropriate if mothers recognize
their children's perceptual and learning abilities, and if mothers recognize
their own potential to help children grow and develop better.<p>
<p>
	Although the research did not show a significant reduction in prevalence of
malnutrition among children of all ages (below the age of two) during the
period of the study, there were important improvements in maternal
understanding of the childrens' needs and changes in feeding  practices. The
persisting malnutrition may have been due to continued early introduction of
semi-

bulky
sticky rice to infants (a practice which interferes with breast-feeding), and
to inadequate breast milk production in rural malnourished lactating mothers.
Significant improvements were found in the percentage of mothers intending to
give their baby colostrum, in maternal awareness of infants' perceptual
abilities, in knowledge and attitudes toward breast-feeding, in child play and
play materials, and in supplementary feeding practices. Random observation
during home visits revealed some changes in mother-

child
interaction, in existing play   materials, and in the type of cradle being
used.<p>
<p>
	In her presentation, Dr. Kotchabhakdi demonstrated dramatically, through a
video presentation, how much mothers and fathers can be helped to recognize
their own abilities to foster development through interaction and by making
changes in the child's environment (e. g. as simple a things opening hammocks
so babies can see what is around them). Once it is  understood by mothers that
a baby of two or three weeks is a seeing, hearing, and reacting person (most
mothers did not think that was the case), changes in behaviour followed
naturally. The presentation illustrated the way in which an increased feeling
of maternal competence can motivate women and lead to self-

sustaining
behavioural changes.<p>
<p>
	Among other research findings were: the importance of seasonal variations, the
superiority of the videos over radio presentations (which can be good reminders
but did not get across the initial message as well), the power of person-

to-
person
exchanges, and the value of an entertaining presentation.<p>
<p>
	<u> Discussion</u>. A question was asked about what benefit the participating
women saw in the programme, Although supplementary food was being made
available, it had to be purchased. That was done in part so as not to use money
or food as an incentive. Rather, the attraction seemed to be a combination of a
fairly personal approach in which field staff backed the video presentations
with personal discussion, of a relatively entertaining presentation, of a
message that related to everyday life, and to the immediate enjoyment that
women seemed to get from seeing immediate results of some of the recommended
actions. <p>
<p>
Related to the above point was a discussion of the process used in the action
research project. Rather than impose a brand of Western-

verified
"scientific" knowledge, the project began with a preliminary survey of existing
customs, then used results to build upon what the community was already doing.
Rather than tell the mothers what to do, the project helped them to discover
ways of controlling their own environment. Although technology was used, the
basic premise of the project was "social" rather than "technological." A
distinction was made between imposing <u>values</u> in the name of science
(e.g. an assumed value placed on "independence") and suggesting
<u>activities</u> that help respond to a value or need that has been defined
locally.<p>
<p>
	When asked what printed materials were used, the response was that only the
growth chart seemed to be useful. pamphlets and leaflets did not seem to work
so well, but a systematic evaluation was not made.<p>
<p>
	Some skepticism was voiced about the feasibility of raising the limited action
research project to a national scale. Did all villages have television so that
the video technology could be carried to them? What would happen when local para-

professionals
rather than university researchers were made responsible for presenting and
discussing the messages? In response, Dr. Nittaya indicated that there was
usually at least one television set in each village so that the medium was not
new and the technology was feasible. Also, the project had actually been
expanded into 40 provinces and the videos had been used to train trainers.
Unfortunately, this is recent and there has not yet been an evaluation of the
expanded programme. However, in the pilot study, an important part of the
success of the project came from the fact that mothers spread the word,
removing dependence on the university personnel.<p>
<p>
<p>
	The discussion also brought out that 97 percent of the village women had had
at least a 4th grade education.<p>
<p>
	No study had been done of costs.<p>
<p>
	School children were also brought into the project. Apparently the upper
primary school children liked the idea of helping younger children. The
teachers encouraged them to make toys. Dr. Nittaya helped the Ministry of
Education to write up external readings for 5th and 6th grade children. There
had been no formal evaluation of that aspect of the programme, but village
health workers reported informally that siblings were in fact more involved
with their younger brothers and sisters.<p>
<p>
	A question was raised about the benefits on the women involved (as well as on
the children who had been emphasized in the discussion and in the evaluation),
One participant hypothesized that one would find important effects on women's
self esteem and her social behaviour. It would be interesting to see whether
women asked more of delivery systems as a result or whether, feeling
"empowered," they took the burden of development more on their own shoulders.
Dr. Nittaya indicated she would like to carry out such a study but there were
not enough hands and not enough time to do it.   In Bangkok, something similar
had been done in which an effect was found on the verbal ability of
participating mothers.<p>
<p>
	The fact that this project was carried out in Buddhist communities led to a
discussion of the role of religion in maintaining or changing child rearing
behaviours, Dr. Nittaya said that many monks were very supportive. At an
abstract level that was easy to do because the messages corresponded with the
religious concerns about peace and harmony and love. There are books by monks
on childrearing, and there are dramas that identify the "good mother's role.
"What the monks have difficulty dealing with are the emotional issues. These
observations led to comments about an approach being taken by UNICEF in Latin
America which seemed very similar. Meetings had been held with the Latin
American Bishop's Conference. Various ways were found in which the messages of
the church and the health, nutrition, and early development messages of child
survival and development programmes come together.<p>
<p>
	In closing the discussion, an intriguing, if unanswerable, question was asked:
"Did desirable childrearing behaviour never exist in the society, or did it
exist and was forgotten?" The latter position is implied in the notion that one
can "rediscover" and build upon local traditions that have fallen into
disuse.<p>
<p>
<p>
	<u>The Colombian case study</u>. Jairo Arboleda for Save-

the-
Children/USA,
and Vicky Colbert from UNICEF/Colombia described their on-

going
experience with helping to set in motion a programme of the Colombian
government that is intended to mobilize the Colombian educational system to
improve child survival and development. Within a National Plan for Child
Survival and Development, this set of activities is supposed to help
institutionalize successes attained through a National Immunization Campaign,
to clarify institutional roles for an effective and sustained effort, and to
look beyond survival to development of the young child. Three initiatives were
described briefly but not discussed in detail: 1) incorporation of health,
nutrition, and development objectives into the primary school curriculum of
ruralschools, 2) the training of "health scouts" as part of the secondary
school curriculum, and 3) including child survival and development components
into normal schools and selected programmes for training professionals within
the universities.<p>
<p>
	 A fourth initiative was emphasized in the presentation -

--
providing family  education for child survival and development in rural areas.
This part of the overall programme would prepare parents, other adults, and
older siblings to promote child survival and to provide adequate child care
during the first  five years of life. The effort builds on the work of Save-

the-
Children,
USA which had developed a set of 10 "child protecting behaviours" as the
essential  component of its approach to increasing child survival in the 58
countries it supports around the world. The original list of 10 hefiaviours
dealt with  health, nutrition, and sanitation. In the adaptation to Colombia,
the list was expanded to 16 behaviours. Behaviours directed toward enhancing
socio-

emotional
interaction were specifically included. Thus, psycho-

social
elements were combined with health and nutrition components in programming. The
list of behaviours is as follows:<p>
<p>
1.		Use of oral rehydration therapy for diarrhea.<p>
<p>
2.		Vaccination of women and children.<p>
<p>
3.		Acquiring and using clean water.<p>
<p>
4.		Sanitary disposal of excreta.<p>
<p>
5.		Appropriate nursing, weaning, and feeding of children.<p>
<p>
6.		Monitoring of child growth and health.<p>
<p>
7.		Finding competent care in case of severe or complicated 	illness.<p>
<p>
8.		Appropriate feeding of pregnant and lactating women.<p>
<p>
9.		Expressing affection to the child in smiling, talking, and 				singing
during feeding, bathing, and clothing the child. 	Avoid any of the previous
actions when you are over tense.<p>
<p>
10.	Interact with the child using songs, story telling, music, and showing and
naming of toys and other objects.<p>
<p>
11.	Facilitate child's games, play with them and make toys using materials
available in the environment.<p>
<p>
12.	Support the child so that he develops the ability to express and movement
of his body: crawling, walking, dancing, and running.<p>
<p>
13.	Promote the expression and communication of the child through painting,
modeling, singing, stories and other.<p>
<p>
14.	Allow the child to do things independently such as eating, getting dressed,
bathing, going to the toilet, selecting the games and the companions with whom
to play.<p>
<p>
15.	Prevent accidents of the child, especially in the handling of work tools
and the activities in the fields and at home.<p>
<p>
16.	Register the child with the civic authorities.<p>
<p>
<p>
	 In order to operationalize delivery of this family education programme, rural
educational institutions are being used. Execution is decentralized, relying on
state and local levels, with mobilization centered on groups of 10 to 15 adults
who are responsible for introducing the desired behaviours into their homes. A
first step in introduction is an assessment of the prevalence of the desired
behaviours and of the viability of adoption. An agenda and a series of meetings
is then set up to deal with one of the behaviours at a time. As part of the
programme, local resources will be drawn upon, including the identification and
involvement of "positive deviant" mothers who already practice the behaviours
and who can explain them to others. Posters, phamphlets, manuals and other
publications are made available to each family.<p>
<p>
	Key features of the initiative are:<p>
<p>
		 Integration (of content and organization)<p>
<p>
		 A family focus with grouping of families<p>
<p>
		 Decentralization (facilitating participation and NGO involvement)<p>
<p>
		 Grouping of families<p>
<p>
		 Large-

scale
use of reinforcing materials made available to families<p>
<p>
		 Use of exisiting infrastructure.<p>
<p>
	Because the programme is at a very early stage, an evaluation has not yet been
carried out, but anecdotal evidence points toward the feasibility of correctly
implementing the strategy with the desired results.<p>
<p>
<u>	Discussion</u>. Considerable interest was expressed in the way in which
theColombian programme build upon existing infrastructure. Particular attention
was given to working with existing groups rather than trying to get around them
to set up something new. In each case, whether the school or the church or the
military or another, the effort has avoided trying to operate by fiat. Rather,
it has explored with each organization the points in common and the existing
points of the doctrine and structures that provide natural points of linkage.
In the medical schools, for instance, there are particular courses that treat
the themes behind the behaviour. In secondary schools, biology course material
provides a natural point of contact. The Catholic church is in agreement with
many of the principles articulated and so has been willing to work ideas into
its counseling for new couples and other activities that are part of its
regular religious services.<p>
<p>
	In contrast with Thailand, it was felt that print media can have an effect in
Colombia.<p>
<p>
	   A missing behaviour was pointed out. In much of the Western world
"touching" in not encouraged, but it is an important expression of affect
already existing in the indigenous culture which should be reinforced and
retained.<p>
<p>
	The need for evaluation was strongly expressed by participants, both as a
guide to the programme and because the results would be of interest more
broadly.<p>
<p>
	The special circumstances present in the Colombian case were noted. For
instance, funds were available that were not being used effectively (through a
two percent payroll tax). Also, there was strong Political commitment. and a
national immunization campaign had just been carried out that provided an entry
point. In reply, it was suggested that there are always special circumstances
present. The trick is to identify them and to build upon them.<p>
<p>
	Common to both the Thai and Colombian cases seemed to be the following:<p>
<p>
		1. Political support and commitment.<p>
<p>
		2. Well-developed infrastructure that could be called upon.<p>
<p>
		3. A relatively well-

developed
level of human resources.<p>
<p>
		4. A technology that helped make the desired outcomes concrete.<p>
<p>
		5. Available financial resources from national sources.<p>
<p>
	Discussion of the Thai and Colombian cases were continued in Working Group No.
2 (see below).<p>
<p>
<b><u>Some Distinctions</u></b><p>
<p>
	From the presentations and discussions came a number of distinctions  helping
to define and analyze complementary ways of integrating or combining  health,
nutrition, and psycho-

social
components of early childhood care and development. First was a set of
distinctions related to different points in the process of defining and
implementing programmes. Integration might occur:<p>
<p>
 at a conceptual level;<p>
 in the setting of policy and in planning;<p>
 in organizing and carrying out a programme; and. ultimately, in the minds and
actions of individual caretakers.<p>
<p>
<p>
<u>Conceptual integration</u>. A concept of "total" or "holistic" development
of the child seemed to be accepted by all present. However, several
clarifications were made during the meeting that sharpened and helped to
operationalize that idea.<p>
<p>
	1. <u>The starting point for development</u>. Dr. Lucas reminded the group
that development begins with conception. So that the idea of total development
must include attention to the pre-

natal
period and to the health, nutritional statui, and well-

being
of the mother during pregnancy.<p>
<p>
	2. <u>From "day care"" to "child care."</u> Dieter Berstecher questioned the
care " as a starting point for discussion because it was too narrow -

-

implying a kind of formal, centre-

based
custodial arrangement for fixed periods of time, when the concept of total
development reguires broader attention to the range of environments, including
the home, in which the child is developing. The term "child care" was suggested
to capture that conceptual broadening.<p>
<p>
	3. <u>From "mother" to "caretaker."</u> Several participants encouraged the
group not to restrict discussion of developmental influences to the  mother.
Fathers, siblings, grandparents, and other caretakers (or better  yet, care
givers), should be included when thinking about programmes to  enhance the
total development of the child.<p>
<p>
	<u>Integration in Policy and Planning</u>. There is a tendency to think in
terms of a health policy, a nutrition/feeding/agricultural policy, an
educational policy, etc., but not a child development policy. The same is true
for plans, which are often made by sectors, with little integration of the
various components that affect the young child in a synergistic manner. It was
observed, however, that integration at the level of policy or plan is much
easier than integration in implementation.<p>
<p>
	<u>Integration in Programme Implementation</u>. Most implementation occurs on
a sectoral basis so that administrative integration is difficult. Participants
seemed to chorus the difficulties of achieving integration in the
implementation of programmes. The Indian Integrated Child Development Service
(ICDS) has had problems of integration, despite some concerted and creative
efforts to achieve such integration. Most discussions of implementation seem to
focus on administrative integration, and often on devices for overcoming the
vertical nature of the several delivery systems involved. The ICDS. for
instance, has created inter-

sectoral
committees at several levels. These sometimes do not work because geographical
responsibilities are assigned differently for health, nutrition, and early
education sectors or because the relative prestige of the various sectorial
actors is different. In some places, integration is being sought by assigning
implementation responsibility to NGOs whose task is then to act as a bridge
across the sectors. It was noted that integration was more likely to occur when
a strong organization was in place at the level of the village or district that
could do the integrating. One suggestion was that often, the most that could be
expected would be geographic convergence of programmes, not integration.<p>
<p>
	Although administrative integration is difficult to achieve, integration of
the <u>content</u> of programmes seemed to be more feasible. Much of the
discussion at the meeting had to do with ways in which the content of
programmes might contain the several elements desired, working with each of the
sectors and with various organizations involved in implementation. In large
part, this was thought to be a training problem.<p>
<p>
 	<u>Integration at an Individual Level</u>. In the last analysis, an
integrated view of child development is sought in the minds and actions of care
givers.   Again, the problem seems to be an educational one requiring a look
not only at the formal ways of transmitting knowledge about early care and
development hut also attention to the cultural and social influences on child
care. More than simply broadcasting messages with integrated content to a vast
public seemed to be called for.<p>
<p>
	Another set of distinctions was made in terms of the many kinds of
<u>individuals and organizations involved in the delivery of early
childhood</u> <u>programmes</u>, each requiring a different approach in order
to try and achieve integration of health, nutrition, and psycho-

social
components into their work. These included: the academic community with its
knowledge specialization, the several professional communities (doctors,
nutritionists, nurses, educators, child development specialists, etc. whose
training often leaves out or treats poorly one or more of the components), para-

professionals,
funders, policy-

makers,
NGOs and PVOs, the churches, etc.  Any broad attempt to combine components
would have to examine barriers and possibilities to integration in the training
and activities of each of these groups.<p>
<p>
	These distinctions were suggested as appropriate to keep in mind in the
working group discussions.<p>
<p>
<b><u>Reports of the Working Groups</u></b><p>
<p>
	Two Working Groups were set up, corresponding to the two main approaches made
to the theme of the meeting. Each group was provided with several guiding
questions to discuss, including, for example, under what circumstances
combining components might occur, where the focus of efforts should be, and
what resources are available. Each was asked also to suggest what the
Consultative Group might do to promote integration.<p>
<p>
	<u>Working Group No. 1: Day Care and Preschool Programmes as an Entry
Point</u><p>
<p>
	1.   All types of day care (governmental, locally organized non-

formal,
and others) should provide an adequate environment that will facilitate
physical and psychological development of the child including health,
education, and nutrition as their basic components.<p>
<p>
	2.   In order to accomplish a comprehensive approach to health. PHC should
work specifically in collaboration with the education sector (day care centres,
etc.). This is also true for the different levels with each sector system.<p>
<p>
	3.   Assuming that more specific developmental actions are already well
established, and there is an excellent health network, we identified several
activities in the health area that could be accomplished by the day care
worker:<p>
<p>
	--    Provide a healthy environment (stimulation), accident prevention and
model behaviour for an appropriate child care minder.<p>
<p>
	--    Screen children with simplified instruments or indicators and refer them
to health centres or related professionals.<p>
<p>
	--     Promote health activities with emphasis on health education and
monitoring of growth and development to be provided to parents and community
members.<p>
<p>
	--     In close connection with the health worker, undertake preventive
services, such as a complex level of diagnoses and collaborative preventive
actions such as in major anemia and deworming as well as specific treatment
required for any other diseases.<p>
<p>
	4. In order to accomplish the health activities mentioned it would be
necessary to analyze the functions and training already existing with each
section involved, mainly health and education.<p>
<p>
	Based on the above, we identified two aspects that need to be addressed by the
Consultative Group:<p>
<p>
	-   Emphasis on <u>training</u> is essential to a comprehensive approach.
Specifically, attention should be given to training of middle level supervisors
for both sectors (health and education). Training centres should include
information in their curriculum from each sector involved (mainly health and
education) and should also include the necessary tools for dissemination of
knowledge for in-

service
training to grass-

root
workers.<p>
<p>
	-   Develop<u> indicators and instruments</u> to facilitate evaluation of
health status, including growth and development monitoring, and a follow-

up
system to evaluate the referral system.<p>
<p>
<u>	Working Group No. 2 -


Summary Report</u><p>
<p>
	<u>Procedure</u>. The group was to consider the assignment with reference to
integration at: 1) a conceptual level (academics, etc.), 2) a policy level (how
policy gets set), and 3) an implementational level/users level (geographical,
organizational, content, combining resources). It was asked to keep in mind
also the various actors: academics, professionals (medicals doctors/nurses,
nutritionists,...), funders/policy makers/planners, users (care givers), the
general public, social institutions, Buddhists, Catholics, etc., NGOs, etc.<p>
<p>
We talked around a number of points using the above guidelines but did not get
around, for shortage of time, and possibly lack of a systematic approach, to
addressing how these levels and people or organizations are combined in any
particular programme. We spent quite a bit of time on Question 1 (see below),
briefly discussed Question 2 (see below) and finally <u>underlined what we need
to do</u> in terms of getting the whole cycle of change or intervention
started, and implemented. Lastly, we had a few recommendations to the
Consultative Group on what it would do in the near future.<p>
<p>
	<u>Question No. 1</u>. Why is there not more attention to psycho-

social
development particularly to mother-

child
(care giver-

child)
interaction, for children 0-

2?<p>
<p>
		The term, "psycho-

social,"
addresses cognitive, personality, emotional, and social 	development vs.
physical growth. Possible explanations given for the lack of attention
include, but are not restricted to:<p>
<p>
	 Not enough is known in this area; the child development field is in its
infancy in some parts of the world, e.g. Africa.<p>
<p>
	 There is an under-

utilization
of psychologists and educators who could provide answers (psychologists have
low income, less prestige, no power, in comparison to medical doctors).<p>
<p>
	 Psychologists themselves are of different persuasions, use different tests
(often developed and normed elsewhere), and attempt to generalize, ignoring
cultural variations. Cross-

cultural
psychology is therefore important as a balance.<p>
<p>
	 The importance of attachment in the early years is over-

emphasized.<p>
<p>
	 Psycho-

social
outcomes are not discrete -


they need to be measured, not once, but repeatedly.<p>
<p>
	 The audience seems uncomfortable (psycho-

social
= threatening; indicators appear "soft" for other professionals).<p>
<p>
	 Vertical arrangement, rather than intersectorial, integrative (ideas
integrations, organization integration, bringing people together, content
integration).<p>
<p>
	<u>All in all</u>, the concept is recognized as important, there are a number
of road-

blocks
that make it difficult for us to fully address its different aspects, and to
articulate it in a manner understood by our varied audiences.  <u>The
challenge</u> for the professionals is to <u>simplify</u>, nay, <u>demystify
</u>the concepts of psycho-

social
development. In the meantime, what do we do? This leads to Question 2.<p>
<p>
<u>	Question No. 2</u>: What needs to be done within child survival programming
to respond to psycho-

social
needs of children 0-

2?
<u>A Prior Question</u>:   Why choose 0-

2,
why not 0-

6?<p>
<p>
	 Attention to mental and social development before age 3 is minimal at best.<p>
	 Programmes attend to ages above age 3.<p>
	 Programmes for survival, health and nutrition have grown: hence we are using
it as an entry point.<p>
	 Early intervention is important for longer term cognitive development.<p>
<p>
	<u>What should we do?</u> We need to "sell" the product (Vance Parkard,
"Hidden Persuaders"). To do this, we need to know where our audience is coming
from.<p>
<p>
	 Provide simple, concrete, operationalized statement.<p>
	 Provide rationale for your intentions, especially for academics.<p>
	 Break the message into meaningful, do-

able
chunks.<p>
<p>
	<u>The Thailand Example</u>. The importance of interaction with the child was
pointed out (action research, training field level workers). We notice it is
also do-

able.
We recognize: maternal competence; nutrition (you get more food eaten by the
child if you know how to handle the social interaction with the child). <u>The
Colombian Example</u> illustrated the importance of starting from the
concrete.<p>
<p>
<u>A Wider Rationale</u>. Why start early childhood education?<p>
	 The moral argument -


every child has a right to developing.<p>
	 The scientific argument -


early years are critical.<p>
	 The social-

equity
argument -


affect poor more.<p>
	 The economic argument -


investment brings economic return.<p>
	 The population argument -


fertility rates decrease.<p>
<p>
	We need to piggy-

back
psycho-

social
development on other programmes, but we can also use it as an entry point to
community development. To stress that in the final analysis it is the family
and the community that provide the anchor for all activities related to psycho-

social
development and sustainability of those activities.<p>
<p>
	Focus of effort should be on advocacy,<u> especially to the top</u>.<p>
<p>
	<u>Recommendations for Consultative Group</u>. We did not get to a point of
fully addressing how the conceptual, policy level, and implementation level
issues could be addressed in a single programme. Nevertheless we felt we had
enough concrete points to enable us to make some recommendations.<p>
<p>
	1.   Clarification and verification of measures on psyche-

social
development are needed.<p>
<p>
   	2.   There is a need to analyze medical curricula and nutrition manuals
(say of 2-

3
professions) to determine what elements of psycho-

social
development are needed. Make appropriate changes and design appropriate in-

service
and pre-

service
training accordingly.<p>
<p>
	3.   Make a case for feeding as a social activity.<p>
<p>
	4.   Look for ways in which videos could be used for advocacy.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b><u>Consultative Group Activities and Finances</u></b><p>
<p>
	<u>Activities</u>. Although the Consultative Group remains an informal
mechanism it has carried out a range of information-

gathering
and dissemination activities. A summary of these activities is provided in
Attachment 0. During 1985 and 1986, eight review or concept papers were written
and distributed. Three issues of the <u>Coordinators' Notebook</u> were
produced. A Knowledge Network has evolved that now includes approximately 400
individuals or institutions in 90 countries. Also available are several trip
reports providing information about meetings and early childhood programming in
countries visited by the Coordinator.<p>
<p>
<u>	Finances: 1987 and Beyond</u>. Financial support for activities of the
Consultative Group is in place, at a level of approximately $225,000, for
activities anticipated in 1987. This includes the support given in-

kind
by UNICEF, providing office space and covering the cost of communications,
photocopying, and mailing. The Ford Foundation, AID and UNICEF are the main
financial supporters in 1987, with contributions to the joint exercise also
coming from Carnegie, IDRC, the Aga Khan Foundation, and UNESCO. Some funds are
committed for 1988.<p>
<p>
<u>	Activities: 1987</u>. A tentative work plan for the Coordinating Unit for
1987 was presented and discussed. It is anticipated that during the year, a
minimum of four review/concept papers would be completed and three or four
issues of the <u>Coordinators' Notebook</u> produced. The Knowledge Network
will continue to grow slowly. The Consultative Group would also help to
organize and provide Summary Reports for three or four meetings. Other possible
activities for 1987 and beyond are suggested in the report of the Advisory
Committee (see Attachment E). A review and evaluation would be carried out
during the first half of i987 to assist the Group in deciding what course to
take in the future.<p>
<p>
<u>	 Looking Ahead</u>. The attached report from the Advisory Committee
strongly recommends continuation of the Consultative Group mechanism and
provides suggestions for a variety of information-

gathering
and dissemination activities which, in its opinion, need to be undertaken.<p>
<p>
	When the Committee's report was discussed on the third day of the meeting,
several topics received particular attention. The measurement problem was
mentioned from several perspectives as important to take on. Included among the
concerns were ethical as well as technical questions related to the development
and use of early childhood development measures. Part of the task seemed to be
demystification. Another part was reaching agreement among people from
different schools of thoughts.<p>
<p>
	Considerable support was expressed for organizing a process to make available
good video tapes of early childhood experiences. It was clear from the meeting
itself that good videos can have a strong impact.<p>
<p>
	The link to women's programmes was also emphasized. A suggestion was made that
this might be a theme for the next Consultative Group meeting.<p>
<p>
	Not in the Committee's report but receiving attention in the discussion was a
review and synthesis of training experiences at various levels, from the
training of medical doctors to the training of community-

based
para-

professionals.<p>
<p>
	Several of the organizations present made statements in support of continuing
the Consultative Group, UNICEF indicated it was willing to continue its
financial contribution beyond 1987 at approximately the same level. AID
suggested the Group consider increasing the level of activity, with a somewhat
more institutionalized structure, and said it would be willing to consider
contributing to support at the higher level as long as AID did not become the
major funder. The World Bank thanked the Consultative Group for helping re-

open
discussion of the early childhood care and development topic within the Bank
and thought the Consultative Group mechanism might help the Bank in the future
by continuing the discussion and helping assess requests the Bank might
receive. A hope was expressed that the Bank could continue to be involved
modestly as a participant in the mechanism. Save-

the-
Children
thought an arrangement might be made for its participation by helping translate
the <u>Coordinators' Notebook</u> into Spanish.    <p>
	In order to improve communication about current policies and programmes, a
suggestion was made that participants might send a note on this to the
Coordinator every three months. The Coordinator would then send out the
information gathered in a kind of <u>Newsflash</u> to the Consultative Group
participants.<p>
<p>
	The Committee's recommendation to learn more from the practices and
experiences of NGOs was in need of additional focus. One way to do that would
be to look specifically at the role of NGOs in service delivery vis-

a-
vis
governments. How do NGO and governmental institutional frameworks fit? Do they
cooperate, and if so, and with what effect? Also, in conjunction with NGOs, the
earlier discussion was recalled about ways in which religious organizations can
and do provide vehicles for improving the total growth and development of young
children.<p>
<p>
	The Consultative Group and its Coordinating Unit might do more advocacy for
programmes of child development than it has done to date, beginning within the
participating organizations.<p>
<p>
	Participants felt the role of the Advisory Committee should be strengthened.<p>
<p>
<u>	Evaluation/Review</u>. The general tone of the discussion led to the
suggestion that the proposed evaluation to be completed by June 1987 be seen as
formative in nature, and largely prospective. The exercise should, however,
include an independent look at the quality of the work being produced by the
Coordinating Unit. It should also seek out the value to practitioners as well
as to the participating agencies, making a virtue of the fact that national
governments and local organizations seem to be running well ahead of
international agencies in this field. (Indeed, a suggestion was made that the
"inter-

agency"
label should be dropped, and that more emphasis should be put on assisting
field efforts.) To put the proposed evaluation/review in motion, it was agreed
that the Coordinator should, after further consultation with participating
agencies, recommend several possible evaluators, with a final selection made
from the list by a three-

person
committee composed of the Coordinator, and staff members from Ford and
UNICEF.<p>
<p>
