Attachment E<p>
<p>
<b><u> REPORT OF THE ADVISORY COMMITTEE</u></b><p>
<p>
<b>Third Inter-

Agency
Meeting of The Consultative Group</b><p>
<b>on Early Childhood Care and Development</b><p>
<b>January 12-

14,
1987</b><p>
<b>Washington, D.C.</b><p>
<p>
<p>
	The Advisory Committee to the Consultative Group on Early Childhood Care and
Development is composed of the following six members, in alphabetical order:<p>
<p>
		Lukas Hendrata (UNICEF/New York HQ)<p>
		Nittaya Kotchabhakdi (Child Dev. Unit/Ramathibodi Hospital, Thailand)<p>
		Cigdem Kagitcibasi (University of Bogazici/Istanbul, Turkey)<p>
		Barnabas Otaala (National Teacher Training College/Lesotho, Africa)<p>
		Sheila Vir (Aga Khan Foundation/New Delhi, India)<p>
<p>
It may be worth noting that the members represent a wide distribution and
representation in terms of geographical (continental) diversity and types of
organizational and professional affiliation.<p>
<p>
<b><u>Observations and Conclusions</u></b><p>
<p>
	The Advisory Committee met three times during the Third Inter-

Agency
Meetings of the Consultative Group and made the following observations and drew
the following conclusions on the basis of the Consultative Group discussions.<p>
<p>
A.	First of all, the starting point of the discussions was the assumption that
the Consultative 		Group would and should continue. It would, indeed, be very
disappointing if the recent 		accomplishments and the potential contributions
of this group and especially of the 		Coordinating Unit are not adequately
recognized and supported. This might lead to the 		dissolution of the Group,
one of the available options, which is not at all acceptable. Thus, 		the value
and importance of the Consultative Group are strongly endorsed.<p>
<p>
B.	 Secondly, and in substantive terms, there needs to be the basic recognition
that early 		childhood development covers the total span of time beginning with
the pre-

natal
period 		and extending into the start of primary schools. Thus, early child
development 		programmes fit within this time span.<p>
<p>
C.	Several suggestions were made for procedural/administrative action;
information gathering 		and synthesizing activities; programme directions and
dissemination of information for the 		Consultative Group.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b><u>Regarding Procedural Orientations:</u></b><p>
<p>
	1. In the activities of the donor agencies, including the Consultative Group
activities, attention should be given to drawing upon  and strengthening the
services of developing country institutions and individuals for consultancies
and projects. In conjunction with this point, the Coordinating Unit could
develop a roster of institutions and individuals to be called upon for
consultancies.<p>
<p>
	2. A concerted effort should be made in crossing bureaucratic and academic
boundaries; interdisciplinary and inter-

sectorial
approaches should be fostered.<p>
<p>
<b><u>Regarding Information Gathering/Synthesizing and Programme
Directions:</u></b><p>
<p>
	1. The diversity among and within developing countries should be recognized.
An effort should be made to collect baseline information where this is lacking.
Equity should be observed in geographical/other orientations.<p>
<p>
	2. The Consultative Group/Coordinating Unit should foster inventorying and
analyzing of projects and programmes (much as is being done by UNICEF and
UNESCO in the Latin American region).<p>
<p>
	3. Programmes emphasizing family and community involvement should be
encouraged.<p>
<p>
	4. A set of case studies should be put together based on successful
experiences. These cases should include information about antecedents,
description of what was done, discussion of problems and lessons learned and
evidence of project impact.<p>
<p>
		a. One set might deal with projects in which child care arrangements' hate
combined health/nutrition and psycho-

social
components in different ways.<p>
<p>
		b. Another might look at child care as related to women's work.<p>
<p>
The case studies should then be used as fertile ground for learning and
exchanging ideas.<p>
	5. The Coordinating Unit should organize analyses of existing indicators,
instruments, and in general, measurement devices that are intended for use in
screening, monitoring, and evaluating early childhood development.
Clarification and cross-

cultural
validation of measures should be undertaken. A series of regional workshops
should be held to set criteria for <u>developing</u>/choosing/analyzing
indicators and instruments. In this process culturally sensitive professional
expertise should be tapped.<p>
<p>
	6. A comprehensive definition of child care should be developed including
categorization of the different forms it may take. Toward this end pilot
projects should be carried out in several countries designed to provide
statistics about the range of child care programmes that exist, with the idea
of developing a system of information that could map and track the coverage and
general characteristics of child care. Consideration should be given to the way
in which such statistics and information systems might assist effective
programme implementation.<p>
<p>
	7. Analyses should be done of the training materials for health and nutrition
professionals and for educators to see how the topic of early childhood
development is treated and with recommendation for reform. This might begin
with analyses of medical school curricula and nutrition manuals.<p>
<p>
	8. There should be a focus on women in early childhood development research
and programme implementation. This focus should integrate the productive and
the reproductive roles of women rather than pitting one against the other.
Toward this end "women in development" approaches in  theory and practice
should be made compatible with early childhood development approaches by
further concentrating on the intersecting needs of women and children.<p>
<p>
	9. Research and programming for parent education should be encouraged as a
means of supporting/educating/empowering parents and other care givers. This
would lead toward providing a more healthy environment for child development.<p>
<p>
	10. A comprehensive review/evaluation of home/family day care programmes
should be undertaken. Diversities as well as commonalities should be
established regarding these programmes.<p>
<p>
<b><u>Regarding Dissemination of Information:</u></b><p>
<p>
	1. An issue of the <u>Coordinators' Notebook</u> should be devoted to
presenting information from a variety of sources describing minimal needs of
good day care centres.<p>
<p>
	2. The <u>Notebook</u> should be translated into other languages.<p>
<p>
	3. A catalogue should be made of existing videos prepared as training or
advocacy materials. The best of these should be selected for translation, if
necessary, for reproduction, and for distribution to interested institutions. A
composite video might be prepared showing  experiences from a range of projects
and programmes.<p>
<p>
	4. A meeting of major international and national NGOs should be organized.
Each participating institution should be asked to prepare one or more case
studies, in line with the previous suggestion regarding case studies.<p>
<p>
	5. A position paper should be written to be used as an information and
advocacy document in meetings of international funders, professional
associations, and national governments.<p>
<p>
<b><u>Evaluation</u></b><p>
<p>
	The Consultative Group should stress the importance of and promote thinking
and work toward evaluation activities in all early childhood development
research and programming.<p>
<p>
<b><u>Administrative Issues</u></b><p>
<p>
	Staffing of the Coordinating Unit, frequency and timing of the Consultative
Group meetings, etc., need to be discussed and determined.<p>
