Timing      Introductory course      Pre-service course
             (1-2 weeks)                      (2-3 months)
             2 hours sessions regularly    regular in-service

Trainers    Nurse, community worker from  Supervisory staff
             PHC network, existing staff      Health professional
             from other programmes            External agency

Evaluation  Observation of practice       Written exams
                                                              Observation of practice
______________________________________

</pre>
<p>
One way to develop on-going support for the caregiver is to identify those who
can be trained as trainers/supervisors.  It is best if these people emerge from
among current staff, rather than being brought in from outside.  Once trained
as supervisors they can train new caregivers who enter the programme and offer
on-going support for all staff. <p>
 <p>
Beyond the needs of the caregiver, there are the needs of the supervisors and
trainers.  Given the nature of the materials which will be developed and the
concepts of integrated health, education and care in child care programmes, it
will be important to develop a technical support system for trainers and those
actually involved in using the new information and technologies within the
community.  These are likely to be personnel from health services.<p>
<p>
In sum, training and support are on-going activities within a child care
programme.  Attention to these aspects of the effort is necessary to create and
maintain a quality service.  But it cannot be assumed that because a training
programme is in place a quality programme is being provided.  To know whether
or not the programme is effective, it is important to establish monitoring and
evaluation processes.<p>
<p>
5.4.  <u>Monitoring and Evaluation
</u>
<p>
<p>
As with training, monitoring and evaluation are on-going processes.  Monitoring
essentially means <i>to keep track/to make observations</i> of what is
happening on a day-to-day basis.  When the information is gathered at any point
in time it is possible to evaluate the programme.  Monitoring and evaluation
can be done in relation to external criteria established for the programme, or
it can take place in relation to criteria developed by the programme itself.
External monitoring generally is done in relation to regulations established by
an outside agency.  Internal monitoring yields data on the effectiveness of the
effort.  These two methods of assessing the programme are described below. <p>
<p>
     5.4.1. <u>The monitoring of regulations</u>. <p>
<p>
Early childhood programmes that are part of formal systems are generally
required to meet certain minimal standards.  Monitoring in this instance is
associated with an assessment of compliance with externally-established
regulations.  It is generally conducted by people outside the day-to-day life
of the programme.  And while it is argued that this is required in order to
assure that children are being provided for in a safe, healthy environment,
historically there has been an inherent tension between the standards of health
care provision established by regulatory bodies and the realities of the
contexts within which child care is being provided. (Zigler, et al., 1983;
Ruopp, et al., 1979; Nelson, 1982).  <p>
<p>
A related tension is between standardised national norms and allowance for
regional and local variation.  These tensions exist even in developed countries
where there are relatively more resources available to providers to make
adequate provision for the care of young children.  The issue is exacerbated in
developing countries with grossly inadequate resources available for child care
programming. Another tension is the result of the fact that standards and
regulations are generally set by public bodies (i.e. ministries of health or
social services), while in many countries the great majority of early childhood
programmes are provided by non-governmental organisations.<p>
<p>
There is no question that young children should have a safe, healthy,
stimulating environment within which to play and learn.  The problem is that
the definition of a safe environment differs, depending on the value system of
the definer (Steiner, 1981; Harman, 1978).  To some extent value differences
can and should be worked out in the goal-setting process.  As goals are
established, they can be translated into operational terms which then define
standards and regulations.  <p>
<p>
Standards and regulations are frequently developed in relation to the following
areas:<p>
<p>
 the physical environment (inside and out): size, structure, light, air,
safety, sanitation, etc;<p>
<p>
      the staff-child ratio and/or group size;<p>
<p>
      staffing, the structure, training and/or credentials of providers;<p>
<p>
 months of operation, length of day, hours of operation;<p>
<p>
 fees and financing;<p>
<p>
      the types and variety of services to be provided.<p>
<p>
Unfortunately, as the list suggest, the balance of attention in regulating
early childhood programmes is frequently given to the monitoring of the
<b>static</b>, easily measured dimensions of a programme (i.e. the number of
square feet/child, the number of toilets, etc), none of which have been
demonstrated to have a significant impact on developmental outcomes for
children.  On the other hand, there are a variety of environmental conditions
that are known to promote the healthy development of young children. (Zeitlin,
1993; Werner, 1982; Berruta-Clement, 1984)  These more <b>dynamic</b>
dimensions (e.g. the patterns of adult-child, child-child and child-environment
interactions) speak to the programme process and need to be included in any
system of standards and regulation of child care.  In order to try and
integrate these more dynamic variables into regulations, the following are
suggested as an alternative framework for monitoring programmes: <p>
<p>
      adequate provision for health, safety, nutrition and shelter;<p>
<p>
          consistent caregivers;<p>
<p>
          adult and peer models of appropriate cognitive and social behavior, and
opportunities to interact with these models;<p>
<p>
          appropriately communicated and consistent expectations and limits;<p>
<p>
          a recognition of and allowance for children's individual interests and
developmental pattern;<p>
<p>
          a physical and social environment that encourages active exploration
and provides opportunities for learning;<p>
<p>
          feedback, both positive and negative, that provides the child with a
positive sense of self and a trust of others.<p>
<p>
While not so easily addressed in regulations nor accessible through simple
monitoring techniques, these variables are key to the implementation of quality
child care programmes and should be built into any child care system and
included in the monitoring process.  <p>
<p>
One example of an attempt to include both the static and dynamic variables in
an assessment tool developed by WHO (1990).  Their Child Care Facility Schedule
includes the following categories:<p>
<p>
          I.  Physical Environment<p>
         II.  Health and Safety<p>
        III.  Nutrition and Food Service<p>
         IV.  Administration<p>
          V.  Staff-Family Interaction<p>
         VI.  Staff-children Interaction<p>
        VII.  Observable Child Behaviour<p>
       VIII.  Curriculum<p>
<p>
Within the international community there is recognition that  early childhood
care and development will remain far more personal and informal than other
kinds of social programmes.  On the other hand, there needs to be a means for
assuring that quality experiences exist for children.  At the present time
there is a great deal of tolerance when programmes fail to meet minimal
standards.  Ultimately it will be necessary to develop regulations which
recognise that family and community values vary across the range of child care
settings, and that these differences will continue to exist (OEF, 1979; Bruner,
1980; Bronfenbrenner, 1980; Clarke-Stewart, 1977).  <p>
     <p>
     5.4.2   <u>Evaluation</u>.  <p>
<p>
As with all components of a child care programme, MCH services require adequate
monitoring of children's development, growth and health so that the needed care
can be provided when growth and/or development lags. To assure that the
services are effective, evaluation systems need to be put into place within the
programme.<p>
<p>
In the majority of cases those involved in developing early childhood
programmes respond to an expressed need, bringing to the situation their
knowledge and experience, and the programme either succeeds or fails, or lies
somewhere along that continuum.  But frequently programme developers are not
able to step back from their day-to-day actions and responsibilities in order
to understand what is happening in the process.  Thus, regardless of the
outcome, they are not able to look at what happened along the way.  <p>
<p>
In order to assess the impact of a programme and to understand what has and has
not worked within the programme, evaluation should be built into the effort
from the beginning. Programme evaluation takes two forms.  <b>Formative</b>
evaluation is a way to monitor on-going activities, the process of putting the
programme into place.  By looking at what happens along the way it is possible
to see areas where the programme needs to be improved. Documentation of
day-to-day activities and the development and use of simple monitoring
instruments can be invaluable in collecting formative evaluation data.  A
formative evaluation is particulary important as the project is getting
started.  It will provide information on whether or not appropriate procedures
are being used to introduce programme components.<p>
<p>
The second kind of evaluation focuses more on programme impact.
<b>Summative</b> evaluation provides an assessment of whether or not programme
goals are being met.  In order to provide the most useful information,
summative evaluations should include an assessment of what children and
families looked like before the programme began, perhaps provide an assessment
of progress at some mid-point in the programme and then assess the impact of
the programme when the child leaves the child care setting. Summative
evaluation is frequently more formal than the formative evaluation and may
include people from outside the programme.<p>
<p>
Both of these aspects of evaluation are important in a situation where an
attempt is made to add or upgrade programme components.  And they must both be
designed in relation to programme goals.  For example, if the programme is
seeking to have an impact on health in the family, then there need to be ways
of assessing if there are changes in the family's health.  If the programme
seeks to increase children's knowledge in relation to specific health content,
then there needs to be a way to test that knowledge.  <p>
<p>
Evaluation activities can be built into and be an integral part of programme
activities.  For example, one of the concerns in most programmes is the
physical growth and psychosocial development of the child.  Growth charts such
as those described in the section on materials have been developed in a variety
of cultures that allow children's growth to be followed periodically.  This
evaluation tool can be administered by staff within the child care programme,
and it can be used with parents. <p>
There is good evidence to support the fact that it is relatively easy for
experienced mothers to make rough and usable estimates of whether a child is
severely or only mildly retarded, normal or in advance of his/her peers in
specific, broad areas of functioning such as language, socialization and
general comprehension.  Even health and physical growth can be monitored
effectively by frequent observations.  While the anecdotal observations are
important, the more formal, but simple, growth charts which monitor growth,
development and the health of the child provide information both on the child's
progress and the effectiveness of the child care programme.  Thus if one of the
programme goals is to increase the mother's awareness of her child's growth and
development, then using the growth chart with her, or teaching her how to use
it, achieves the goal of increasing her understanding of growth and development
as well as provides a way to evaluate the child's progress. (Donohue-Colletta,
1992)  <p>
<p>
Another approach to the evaluation of programme outcomes has been taken by the
Consultative Group on Early Childhood Care and Development, working with
researchers in developing countries to develop two sets of instruments within a
given country.  One is a <i>Child Readiness Profile</i> and the other is a
<i>School Readiness Profile</i>.<p>
<p>
The impetus for this approach came from two concerns.  First, there are
continuing questions about the effectiveness of various child care programmes.
Thus there is a need for outcome measures that will indicate the relationship
between children's participation in child care programmes and their growth and
development.  The second concern comes from those who believe high dropout and
repeater rates in primary school are the result of children not being "ready"
to learn when they enter primary school.  To respond to these concerns a
readiness profile will be developed that provides a picture of the child's
nutritional status, health status, pre-literacy and pre-numeracy skills, social
relations skills, self-esteem and family knowledge, expectations and support.<p>
<p>
As noted, a complementary profile is being developed for schools.  All the
blame for school failure cannot be put on children and their families.  Schools
also bear part of the responsibility.  Thus, it is equally important to have a
measure of how well the school is doing.  The variables in the School Readiness
Profile include: availability and access; quality of schooling, adjustments by
schools to local conditions, and teacher expectations.<p>
<p>
In sum, monitoring and evaluation activities are important to assess the
effectiveness of a child care programme.  There are two points in time when an
evaluation of the effort is important in relation to the introduction of MCH
components.  First, it is important to know if the current system of provision
is effective (i.e. would be MCH components be introduced into an already
effective set of services?)  If current provision is not meeting its
objectives, then the inputs required from the health sector would necessarily
involve improving the quality of the total programme in addition to introducing
MCH components.  If the system is effective and MCH components are introduced,
a second evaluation point would be to determine the extent to which MCH
components have been introduced successfully. <p>
<p>
As noted, the inputs required from the health sector would differ depending on
the services currently being provided. One of the inputs is financial.  The
financial requirements necessary for the development and expansion of child
care systems needs to be understood before the health sector becomes involved
in working with these systems.  The costing of alternative approaches to child
care is discussed in the next section.<p>
<p>
<b>6.  Costing of Alternative Approaches</b><p>
<p>
Despite growing concern about costs, they are frequently addressed in the final
rather the initial stages of planning.  Costs should be addressed early in the
process of creating a programme and costing should be an integral part of
project development.  Financial requirements are a key variable in assessing
the feasibility of integrating MCH components effectively into child care
systems. <p>
<p>
This section focuses on how to define the costs of a programme, develop a
budget, and determine resource requirements in relation to programme benefits
and effectiveness.  A clear definition of the costs can lead to pragmatic
standards for judgments about whether to begin a project and whether or not to
expand or replicate a programme.  A knowledge of the relationship between costs
and programme outcome can aid in planning and improving the use of resources.
Before looking at the relationship between these two, it is useful to define
more specifically the costs of early childhood programmes.<p>
<p>
6.1.  <u>The Costs Associated with Child Care Programmes</u>. 
<p>
     <p>
Costs go beyond the actual expenditures of a programme.  They include in-kind
contributions and human resources donated to the effort as well as the monetary
input.  When costing a given programme, different people can come up with
widely variant results, depending on which of these variables they choose to
include in their calculations.  For example, a funding agency may be concerned
only with how much it needs to contribute to make the effort successful.  In
another instance, someone might be trying to illustrate how important the
community's contribution is to the programme, so in-kind contribution are
included.  A third individual, trying to estimate what it would cost to
replicate the effort on a large scale, could well be concerned about costing
all the elements. Thus, the reasons for collecting the data will determine what
is actually costed.  This, in turn, will make a difference in the costs of the
programme per beneficiary.<p>
<p>
Generally those items that require actual payment (salaries, equipment,
supplies, materials, transportation, etc.) are included in any costing.
However, frequently the in-kind or voluntary contributions are not costed.
Many early childhood programmes rely heavily on community contributions in the
form of donations of land and/or a building for the programme, voluntary labour
in building classrooms, providing food and cooking the meals for children, and
sometimes even the volunteering of a caregiver's time.  When these programmes
are costed, the contribution of the community may or may not be valued in
monetary terms.  The extent to which these variables are taken into
consideration are important in determining the real costs of the effort.  And
while the costs of the community's contribution might not be important in terms
of the day-to-day operation of the programme as it stands, there are
implications <p>
when the programme is being considered for expansion.<p>
<p>
In addition to whether or not community input is costed, there are several
dimensions that have a major impact on the budget.  These include the phase of
project development, the type of facility being used for the programme, and
staffing.  Each of these is described more fully.<p>
<p>
     6.1.1  <u>Phases in programme development</u><p>
<p>
Costs vary depending on when they are assessed during the life of the
programme.  For example, during a pilot phase there are expenses that will not
be present once the programme has been put into place.  As the project is being
developed there is the cost of establishing and furnishing the centre.  There
may be expenses associated with pre-service training that later will be
converted to a budget allocation for continuing in-service training.  There is
likely to be technical assistance provided in the early years that is
discontinued once those implementing the programme are well trained.  And there
are likely to be high monitoring and evaluation costs as the project gets
underway.  <p>
<p>
When pilot projects are developed there is frequently considerable investment
in evaluation, sometimes nearly equivalent to the entire budget for the
project.  This may be necessary when a new idea is being tested, as it is
important to be able to closely monitor project development and make
appropriate corrective actions.  However, this type of evaluation is not
necessary as the programme becomes regularised.  From among the instruments and
techniques used in evaluation of the pilot project, it will be possible to
identify those that yielded the most useful data.  Only these should be
included as part of the on-going programme.  This will greatly reduce
evaluation costs.  <p>
<p>
The expense of on-going evaluation activities should not be such that it limits
programme expansion and discourages governments from adopting the programme on
a larger scale.  The evaluation component of on-going programmes should
represent about 10% of the total budget. <p>
<p>
Thus, in analysing costs it is important to define where the project is in its
development.  This will help differentiate between the costs associated with
start-up and those that will be incurred as the project continues over time.
<p>
<p>
     6.1.2.  <u>Programme setting</u>.  <p>
<p>
As has been noted, there are programmes that have been developed by the
community where the community has provided the space, in some instances a
purpose-built child care centre.  In other instances, the programme operates in
make-shift settings.  While child care in purpose-built settings may be more or
less adequate in terms of meeting criteria of safety and promotion of healthy
practices, there are many settings where it would take considerable input from
the health sector to upgrade the centre to reach even minimal standards.<p>
<p>
<p>
     6.1.3.  <u>Staff credentials have cost implications</u>.  <p>
<p>
In general, there are three levels of staff: professional,
paid-paraprofessional and volunteer para-professional.  The use of staff at
these three different levels has implications for costs, both in terms of
paying the individual, and in terms of training.  While the salary of a
professional caregiver is higher than that for para-professionals, they are not
necessarily more costly to the programme.  There are trade-offs in terms of
training.  A professional will have had basic training in child care, including
health, nutrition and child development.  Thus, in order for them to implement
the MCH components, it may require very little in terms of additional training
and on-going support to make them competent child care providers.  Also, if the
conditions of work are favourable and they are receiving a reasonable salary
relative to others in the community, they are likely to continue their work
with the programme.<p>
<p>
Having para-professional staff is quite different.  On the surface it might
appear that it is less costly to staff a programme with para-professionals.
While their pay may be low, or non-existent, they are also likely to be
untrained.  Thus the costs of providing them with adequate training so that
they can implement a child care programme may be proportionately much higher
than in a programme where the staff are professionals.  Further, they will
require more intensive on-going support.  If they are receiving little of no
pay, they are likely to leave if other opportunities are available.  This
results in a high turnover rate, which means that there would be a need to
constantly have a pre-service training programme available.<p>
<p>
The phase of programme development, the nature of the facilities and staffing
are but three of the programme variables that have an impact on the budget.
However, since they are likely to contribute heavily to the costs of the
programme, they have been highlighted.  In order to consider all the costs of a
programme, what follows is a brief discussion of the full range of components
that need to be included in constructing a budget for a child care programme.
<p>
<p>
6.2. <u>Constructing a Budget.
</u>
<p>
<p>
It is important to realise that while there are some fairly standard categories
to be taken into consideration when constructing the costs of a programme,
there is no formula for determining what proportion of the costs should go to
personnel, what proportion to the facility, what proportion to management, etc.
While all the same categories of costs need to be considered for each
programme, their relationship to one another will be determined by the setting.
For example, in a village without electricity and running water, where the
centre is a make-shift building, the maintenance costs are minimal.  However,
there might be very high costs in terms of obtaining food for the children in
the programme because it has to be brought in from outside the community.  On
the other hand, a facility in an urban area may have high costs for maintenance
(electricity, heat, water, custodial service, etc.) relative to the costs of
feeding the children in the centre.  Thus, when considering the costs to
programmes of introducing MCH components and materials, it must be recognised
that in some instances the introduction of the various technologies may
represent a very large additional cost to programmes in some settings, while
being easily integrated into current budgets for other programmes.<p>
<p>
In constructing the budget for a programme the following are categories which
need to be taken into consideration:<p>
<p>
     6.2.1.  <u>Capital costs</u>.  <p>
<p>
These are all the costs associated with the physical center.  There may be
costs for land, the building, and perhaps the costs of a vehicle and basic
equipment for office support and for the centre itself.  These costs are
necessarily high as the programme is being established.  They should be
relatively low as the programme becomes fully operational, but they must be
considered once again if there are plans to expand the programme to additional
settings.<p>
<p>
     6.2.2.  <u>Personnel</u>.  <p>
<p>
These are the costs associated with the people that will be involved in the
effort, from the Director of the project, to Supervisors/Trainers, to the
actual caregivers and those who work directly with parents, to auxiliary staff
who provide support either on a full or part-time basis.  In a pilot project,
as the programme is being developed and people are being trained, the ratio
between staff and children may be quite high.  Once in place, however, the
programme may be able to serve a larger number of children and their families
with the same number of staff.  As the programme is being costed for expansion,
it is possible to look for economies of scale.    <p>
<p>
     6.2.3.  <u>Operations and supplies</u>.  <p>
<p>
This category includes all the things that have to be continually supplied to
or purchased by the programme.  It includes the educational materials that are
used with the children and with parents, food that needs to be purchased for
the nutritional aspect of the programme, office supplies, and all the recurrent
maintenance costs that allow the programme to function (electricity, telephone,
transportation for teachers, vehicle maintenance costs).  It also includes the
special services that may be need to be purchased, such as the costs to the
programme for immunizations, or the hiring of a bus to transport children.<p>
<p>
     6.2.4.  <u>Human resource development</u>.  <p>
<p>
Included in this category are all the activities that are undertaken to
strengthen personnel within the programme.  The primary activity in this
category is training.  The costs of training will depend on: the credentials of
those currently employed, the nature of the training required, the type of
agency providing the training, the training plan (the allocation of time to
pre- and in-service training and who is responsible), and the kind of on-going
support which is necessary. <p>
<p>
Also included in this category are the costs of consultants who are brought in
to help up-grade the effort, either on a one-time basis or periodically.  Over
time there may also be costs associated with sending staff for more specialised
training (e.g. sending a caregiver to a short course so that she can be
upgraded to a Supervisor as the programme develops, providing management
training to administrative personnel who will be required to manage a larger
system as the programme expands).<p>
     6.2.5.  <u>Monitoring and evaluation</u>.<p>
<p>
There are costs associated with the monitoring and evaluation of the project.
These may include the costs of hiring an evaluation group or personnel who are
not normally employed by the project, or it may mean providing an increment in
pay to current staff if they take on increased responsibility in relation to an
evaluation.  Also in this category are the costs of developing instruments to
be used in evaluation, data analysis, documentation, and report writing.  <p>
<p>
Each of these costs needs to be calculated for three distinct phases in a
programme: for the pilot phase, for project implementation and then for
expansion.  It will also be necessary to relate each of these costs to funders.
If the cost is to be covered in the pilot and implementation phase by the
community, it cannot be assumed that these same aspects of the programme will
be provided by the community where the programme is to be introduced.  It may
well be that as the programme is transferred these elements will have to be
included in the budget, particularly if the programme is being introduced into
a poorer community.  These costs must be anticipated.<p>
<p>
Costs do not exist in a vacuum.  The costs of a programme cannot be evaluated
in isolation of the benefits or outcomes.  As there is great variance in terms
of the costs associated with different kinds of child care programmes, there
are also differences to be considered when assessing the benefits of these
efforts.<p>
<p>
<p>
6.3.  <u>Outcomes/Benefits</u>  
<p>
<p>
Economists and planners are increasingly concerned about making wise
investments.  This is judged by calculating what is accomplished as a result of
putting money into a programme.  In order to assess the benefits, the goals of
the programme have to be clear.  For example if the effort is designed to
provide a specific service (e.g. immunization) for children in a given age
group then it is fairly easy to measure the outcome.  It is simply a matter of
tabulating what percentage of the children are now immunized and comparing that
with the percentage immunized before the project.  The cost of each
immunization, can, in fact be calculated.  There is a clear direct relationship
between costs and benefits.  However, if an organisation is involved in the
implementation of an integrated programme of care for young children and their
families, then the outcomes are much more elusive.  They are harder to define
in terms of specifics and they are difficult to measure.  <p>
<p>
But the difficulty of measuring the benefits is only one of the problems in
terms of defining programme outcomes.  Another problem is that it is often
difficult to recognise the full benefits of a programme.  Even when programme
goals might be limited to having a positive impact on the child's success in
school, there are frequently spill-over benefits to the family that will
probably go undocumented and perhaps unnoticed. For example, through parent
education groups a mother may gain enough self-confidence that she decides to
get additional training and seek a better job. <p>
<p>
It is even more difficult to determine benefits in programmes that have broad
community development goals.  The quality of life in a village may be changed
as a result of an initial investment in an early childhood programme.  And
while those operating a community-based child care initiative would like to
think that their programme provided the impetus for upgrading the life of
people in the village, it is hard to ascribe changes in the village (such as
the addition of a water pump, the establishment of a part-time health clinic,
for example) to the investment in the child care.  The relationship between the
costs and the benefits is much less clear than in a single-focused programme.
<p>
<p>
In addition to the spill-over effects of programmes while they  are operating,
there are sometimes long-term benefits that are unanticipated and therefore not
included in an assessment of outcomes.  One of the most noteworthy longitudinal
studies on the impact of early childhood education found that over time the
impact of a preschool experience could be measured in terms of adult
behaviours.  Those with preschool were more likely to complete high school,
they were less likely to be delinquent, they got better jobs and were able to
stay off welfare. (Berruta-Clement, J.R. et al, 1984).   These benefits were
not anticipated when the programme was initially evaluated and costed.  <p>
<p>
Thus before determining the outcomes or benefits received in relation to the
amount of money invested, those involved in making the calculation have to
agree on what is going to be included in the costing of the project and how
benefits will be defined.  As noted, this calculation may not be of much
interest to those involved in the programme, but when the programme is being
considered for expansion, these calculations are important.  <p>
<p>
<b>7.     The Way Forward</b><p>
Because of its commitment to meeting the basic health needs of all by the year
2000, the World Health Organization is seeking ways to have a widespread impact
as effectively and efficiently as possible.  In considering where the health
sector should invest its resources one of the questions is, where it is
cost-effective to do so?  <p>
<p>
In recent years there have been several significant shifts in the way young
children have been viewed by health care professionals.  There has been a shift
from a focus simply on child survival to a concern for overall development,
accompanied by a shift from looking only at the child to a focus on the family
and the context within which the child is living.  There has also been a shift
from a medical to a social science model of health, accompanied by a shift from
treatment to concern about prevention.  These shifts have led to increasing
concern about how to create multi-disciplinary programmes for children and
their families.  This document argues that one alternative is to invest in the
integration of primary health care components into early childhood programmes.
<p>
<p>
The research on the relationship between early childhood experiences and later
growth and development provides a persuasive argument in support of developing
quality child care programmes.  Evaluation of programme experiences in a wide
variety of settings, under less than optimal conditions, also suggests the
power of early childhood programmes.  <p>
There is a considerable body of early childhood programming experience.  This
experience comes from rural and urban areas, from developing and developed
countries, from the health, education and social services sectors, and from
informal community-based initiatives to the more formal pre-schools. Some of
these efforts have provided integrated services, including  health, education,
growth and development concerns. <p>
<p>
While there is interesting research currently being conducted that will provide
additional insights into the way to work most effectively with children and
their families, there is enough known about the impact of early experiences on
later development that it is possible to move forward in terms of actually
developing curricula, materials, and training strategies to increase the
delivery of MCH components through early childhood programmes.  Given what is
known, guidelines and materials for implementing health activities within child
care settings can be developed and tested.<p>
<p>
The health sector is in a position to spearhead the promotion and
implementation of child care programmes as part of an integrated primary health
care approach.  While these programmes would need education and social sector
support, the lead needs to be taken by the health sector.  The challenge for
the health sector is to develop strategies for expanding their conception of
health services to include a broad range of developmentally and contextually
appropriate health activities. <p>
<p>


